<FIRST>u a AM-ChicagoSchoolReform 2ndLd-Writethru a0415 10-12 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago School Reform, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0415,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elections Wednesday and Thursday Will Put Reform in Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE turnout figures; picks up 5th graf:
`Officials said ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150,000 Chicagoans voted to elect local
school councils Wednesday as part of sweeping reforms that will
give parents more control of an education system labeled the worst
in the nation.
   At issue is the quality of learning in a system whose 410,000
students make it the nation's third largest, but whose low test
scores and high dropout rates in 1987 caused then-Education
Secretary William Bennett to brand it the nation's worst.
   The final tally is expected to show that more than 30 percent of
the parents voted in the elections, school officials said.
   An early tally of votes cast showed that 150,401 people voted.
Officials said that included 70,053 parents, 55,319 community
residents and 25,029 ballots cast by Chicago Public School staff
members.
   Officials said there were a number of reports of irregularities
in the balloting, most caused by inexperienced election judges and
ballots at some schools that had more than 20 candidates.
   ``I want to be part of the reform _ I think this is one way of
having a solution to the problems in the schools of Chicago. I feel
it's a responsibility of the parents,'' said Nacer Boundaoui, who
voted at Robert Healey Elementary School, where his son attends
first grade.
   Boundaoui led his 4-year-old daughter, Assia, into the school
gymnasium and stood behind a wooden screen hiding a metal school
desk, where he marked his vote on a paper ballot.
   The elections _ Wednesday at the city's 469 elementary schools
and Thursday at 71 public high schools _ were part of a reform
package passed last year by the Illinois General Assembly. Reform
also included cutting administrative jobs and shifting money in the
$2.26-billion school budget to educating low-income students.
   Community activists spent weeks trying to mobilize residents to
vote, but predicted a 50 percent turnout among parents with
children in school. School Board spokesman Bob Saigh said that
turnout was low by late afternoon, but was expected to improve by
the time polls closed.
   The 17,256 candidates sought 5,400 unpaid positions on the 540
councils, each of which will include six parents, two teachers and
two community residents without schoolchildren. School staffs will
elect the teacher members. The 11th member of each council will be
the principal of the school or schools the council oversees.
   The councils, scheduled to begin their monthly meetings within a
week of the elections, will have authority to hire and fire
principals, develop school-improvement plans and spend money.
   The councils would receive much of the authority previously
vested in the school system's central bureaucracy, headed by a
superintendent and the Chicago Board of Education. The old board of
mayoral appointees was scrapped under the plan and a seven-member
interim board, also appointed by the mayor, is running the system.
   Ultimately, a 15-member permanent board will be named by the
mayor, following screenings by citizens' panels.
   At George B. McClellan school, Mayor Richard M. Daley was one of
about 60 people who had voted by 11 a.m.
   ``I'd like to have them coming in, but it's slow,'' said
election judge Alfreda McLain, surveying the empty polling place at
McClellan. ``Maybe they don't understand that they should help the
public schools.''
   A survey by Designs for Change, an education research and
advisory council that helped shape the reform package, found that
nearly equal numbers of candidates came from low-income
neighborhoods as middle-class sections of the city. Participation
was as high at mostly black and Hispanic schools as at integrated
schools, the survey found.
</TEXT>
