<FIRST>u a AM-Lyphomed-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0425 10-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lyphomed-AIDS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Distributing AIDS-linked Pneumonia-Fighting Drug Free to
Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with cost of drug, quotes from officials;
a version moving on business wires; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lyphomed Inc. has been distributing its drug
pentamidine, used to combat AIDS-linked pneumonia, free to poor
patients, the company said Wednesday.
   The company announced its plans to give away the drug in
February, but the actual distribution was held up until after the
drug won full government approval in June, said spokeswoman Melissa
Marsden.
   Community health organizations have been notified of the
availablity of pentamidine for the poor and for those who lacked
insurance to cover its costs.
   Ms. Marsden said there have been no recent talks within the
company about reducing the cost of the drug to the paying public.
Lyphomed, based in suburban Rosemont, has been accused by AIDS
activists and others of overcharging for the substance.
   Lyphomed's action represents the first time a company has
distributed an approved drug to poor patients free of charge,
company officials and federal Food and Drug Administration
spokesman Brad Stone told The New York Times.
   Since 1984, Lyphomed has produced an injectable form of the drug
for use in patients who already have contracted pneumocystis
carinii pneumonia, a life-threatening form of pneumonia that is the
leading cause of death among AIDS patients.
   In June, the company obtained approval for marketing an aerosol
version to be taken once every four weeks as a preventive measure
by people likely to contract that form of pneumonia.
   Lyphomed charges about $100 wholesale for a monthly dose.
Patients pay up to $200 for the same dose through doctors and
pharmacies.
   Last month, the People With AIDS Health Group said it would
import the drug from England, where is it cheaper, and sell it to
AIDS patients in this country at a lower cost that the drug can be
bought here.
   Lyphomed said its charge is appropriate, given the research
money it spent developing the drug.
</TEXT>
