<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bishops-Mideast     10-12 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bishops-Mideast,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Attack Israeli Rights Abuses, Call for Palestinian Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three U.S. Roman Catholic archbishops said
Israel should negotiate directly with Palestinians over ``territory
and sovereignty,'' and criticized Israel for alleged human rights
abuse.
   The joint statement by Archbishops Roger Mahony of Los Angeles
and William Keeler of Baltimore and Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York also called on Syria to leave Lebanon.
   Their statement, to be presented to the nation's 300 bishops,
asked the Bush administration to take more action in negotiating a
peace in the Middle East that meets the security needs of Israel
and the ``long-denied rights'' of Palestinians.
   But it also called on Palestinians to pursue ``sovereign
co-existence'' with Israel.
   ``The key to successful political dialogue will be Palestinians
willing to discuss secure boundaries and stable political relations
with Israel and Israelis willing to discuss territory and
sovereignty with Palestinians,'' the statement said.
   ``We feel as Christian leaders in the Catholic community that we
have a responsibility to ... pull factions that have been in
conflict together, to be instruments of peace,'' said Mahony,
chairman of the committee that drew up the statement. ``We see this
as a moral challenge. There is a better way to live.''
   The statement, ``Toward Peace in the Middle East: Problems and
Principles,'' will be presented to the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops' fall meeting Nov. 6-9 in Baltimore.
   Rabbi A. James Rudin, national interreligious affairs director
of the American Jewish Committee, and Judith H. Banki, his
associate, said they were troubled by the bishops' ``premature''
support for Palestinian sovereignty.
   They also said that in criticizing Israel's handling of the
Palestinian uprising, the prelates failed to give equal weight ``to
Israel's very real problems and legitimate rights in maintaining
order in the territories,'' and a 40-year history of terrorist
attacks by Palestinians.
   An Arab-American leader praised the statement.
   ``The addition of such a respected moral voice on the side of
Palestinian independence is an historic development at a critical
juncture in the Palestinian-Israeli conflict,'' said Abdeen Jabara,
president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee.
``History will record that the moral authority of the American
Catholic Church was indisputably on the side of peace in the Middle
East.''
   The prelates cited Israeli responsibility in the beating deaths
of Palestinians and people not involved in the uprising against
Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the demolition
of homes and arrest and detention without trial.
   They said the statement was devised after consultations with the
Vatican, religious leaders in the Middle East, U.S. policymakers
and major Jewish, Arab and Christian organizations.
   ``It is our conviction that a truly open moment for peace exists
in the Middle East, and that the United States has an indispensable
role to play in the peace process which has moved us to write this
statement,'' said the committee.
   The nearly 2-year-old intefadeh, or Palestinian uprising, is a
cry for justice and personal and political identity that demands
``on both moral and political grounds, a response by the United
States government,'' the prelates said.
   They stopped short of calling directly for the creation of a
Palestinian state. But they said the United States must go beyond
the approach of the Camp David accords of the late 1970s, which
gave Palestinians a secondary role in the peace process, and grant
``their right to participate as equals, through representatives
selected by Palestinians, in all negotiations affecting their
destiny.''
   Having opened political discussions with the Palestine
Liberation Organization in December 1988, ``the United States now
has the opportunity to use its influence and relationships to
foster a more extensive dialogue among Israel, Palestinians and the
Arab states,'' the prelates wrote.
   They also called for a ``clear, consistent'' U.S. policy
``pressing Syrian withdrawal from Lebanon.''
   They called on the Arab states and Palestinians to recognize
Israel's right to exist, and asked the Arab nations to establish
full diplomatic relations with Israel.
   ``Anything short of this leaves the `legitimacy' of Israel
undefined in the policy of the Arab states, and reinforces Israel's
position that the only road to survival is one requiring superior
military power.''
</TEXT>
