<DOCNO> AP891012-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NewsSurvey     10-12 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-News Survey,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Outdraws Pierce, Frank in Public Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four out of five Americans know why Zsa Zsa
Gabor has been in the news lately, but only about one in 10 can
identify Samuel Pierce or Barney Frank without help, according to a
news industry survey.
   The survey, released Wednesday by the Times Mirror Center for
the People &amp; the Press, showed that Washington news gets a low
rating when people are asked what stories they are following very
closely.
   Stories about Frank, a Democratic congressman from Massachusetts
who has admitted having sex with a male prostitute and then hiring
him as a personal aide and driver, were followed by only 6 percent
of those surveyed.
   This made the Frank affair one of the lowest-interest stories
since the surveys began in 1986, equaled only by the
influence-peddling scandal that drove former Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita from office in May.
   Only 12 percent of the 1,234 adults interviewed by telephone
correctly identified Frank.
   Ten percent knew that Pierce was the former housing secretary
whose administration of rental subsidy programs for the poor is
under investigation by Congress.
   But 80 percent knew that Ms. Gabor was tried in Beverly Hills,
Calif., on charges of slapping a policeman. The survey was
conducted Oct. 5-8, a week after the actress was convicted.
   The most closely followed story in the survey was Hurricane
Hugo, with 60 percent saying they kept up with developments closely.
   This made it the third-ranking story in public interest since
the surveys began, exceeded only by the 1986 Challenger space craft
explosion at 80 percent and the rescue of young Jessica McClure
from a Texas well in 1987, which 69 percent said they kept up on.
   Times Mirror said in a news release that the difference in
public response to the Frank and Hugo stories ``is in keeping with
a pattern that has become clear from the monthly findings of the
Times Mirror News Interest Index. Public attentiveness to coverage
of news events is high, while public attentiveness to news about
most personal scandals is usually low.''
   Times Mirror also said its October findings ``dramatically
reinforced'' previous indications that news from Washington, even
when it has far-reaching consequences, often gets little attention.
   No major Washington story in the latest survey was followed
closely by as many as 25 percent of Americans. The most closely
followed Washington story in the history of the surveys was the
Supreme Court decision in July upholding a Texas law against
burning the American flag. It was followed closely by 51 percent of
those surveyed.
   Overseas stories often get a low rating also. The elevation of
the once-outlawed Solidarity Union to a role in governing Poland,
for instance, was followed closely by only 12 percent of those
surveyed in July.
   In the latest count even interest in overseas events, such as
the flight of East German refugees to West Germany at 31 percent
and the failed coup attempt in Panama at 29 percent, outdrew
Washington stories.
   Only 19 percent paid close attention to attempts in Congress to
repeal the new catastrophic illness insurance plan. Among persons
over age 50, this rose to 36.
   House approval of a cut in the capital gains tax drew close
attention from 14 percent. Among people with family incomes of
$50,000 or more, this increased to 26 percent.
   The study was conducted by the Times Mirror Center for the
People &amp; the Press, a division of The Times Mirror Company, which
publishes the Los Angeles Times, Newsday, the Baltimore Sun, the
Hartford Courant and other newspapers and owns broadcast stations.
   The center said the study was subject to a 3 percent sampling
error.
</TEXT>
