<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     10-12 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President and Falklands War Leader Freed from Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Leopoldo
Galtieri, who led Argentina into the 1982 Falklands War and was
imprisoned for negligence in its defeat, has been freed by
presidential pardon.
   Galtieri said nothing to reporters on his release Wednesday from
Campo de Mayo army base on the outskirts of Buenos Aires.
   Galtieri, 63, was one of 39 retired generals and admirals
pardoned Saturday by President Carlos Menem along with dozens of
people accused of being leftist terrorists and 174 soldiers who
rebelled against the former government.
   Galtieri's pardon also voids pending charges against him in
civilian court of human rights abuses.
   Menem, who took office July 8, said the pardon was needed ``to
close and stitch the wounds'' of the past so the South American
country of 32 million people might concentrate on its economic
problems.
   He said a second pardon is pending that will free Mario
Firmenich, co-founder of the Montonero urban guerrillas, and six
officers convicted of kidnap, torture and murder during the
military dictatorship's 1976-83 crackdown on leftist subversion.
   The officers include Jorge Videla and Roberto Viola, both former
presidents and former army commanders-in-chief.
   Galtieri was president from December 1981 to June 1982. The
Supreme Council of the Armed Forces convicted him of negligence in
May 1986 for his handling of the 74-day Falklands War against
Britain, which Argentina lost _ a loss that led to the end of the
military junta and 1983 election of a civilian goverment.
   Galtieri began the war on April 2, 1982, to recover the South
Atlantic islands held by Britain and claimed by Argentina since the
early 19th century.
   The military's highest tribunal ruled that he did not anticipate
or prepare for a British counterattack, nor was Argentina's defense
of the islands properly coordinated.
   Galtieri also had faced federal court charges in the shooting
deaths of 13 political prisoners in December 1976, nine months
after President Isabel Peron was ousted in a coup and the new
military regime stepped up its crackdown on subversion.
   Rights groups oppose Menem's pardon and plan to challenge its
constitutionality in court.
   The Roman Catholic Church, major newspapers, two of the three
largest political parties, and influential business and farm
organizations endorsed the pardon and indicated they would support
its extension to Videla, Viola and Firmenich.
   At least 8,960 purported leftists were arrested and never seen
again _ presumed executed _ during the ``dirty war'' against
subversion, a presidential commission found. Some rights groups put
the total closer to 30,000.
   The armed forces insists it quelled an armed insurrection by
using the same tactics as guerrillas.
</TEXT>
