<FIRST>r w PM-PakistanNuclear     10-12 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan Nuclear,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Again Reports Pakistan Doesn't Have the Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is ``disturbed'' by Pakistan's
continued nuclear program without outside safeguards but says that
nation does not have a nuclear weapon, according to a congressional
aide.
   The president must make such a certification every year for
Pakistan to continue receiving U.S. aid.
   Bush sent a letter to Congress saying continuation of aid would
``significantly reduce'' the chances of Pakistan acquiring such a
weapon, the legal formula he is required to use for aid to continue.
   But according to the aide's description of the letter, Bush said
he ``continued to be disturbed by the fact that Pakistan is
continuing its unsafeguarded nuclear program.''
   Pakistan's nuclear program has posed the spectre of a nuclear
arms race with neighboring India for years. India exploded what it
called a nuclear ``device'' in 1974, a device it insisted was not a
weapon.
   In February, Pakistan's ambassador to the United States said his
country had deliberately refrained from taking the final step of
assembling a weapon.
   During her visit in June, Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto told a
joint session of Congress that Pakistan had no nuclear weapons,
would not build them and would not provoke a nuclear arms race with
India.
   The congressional aide who discussed Bush's letter is on the
staff of Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the Asia
subcommittee of the House Foreign Affairs Committee. He spoke on
condition that his name not be used.
   He said Solarz expressed ``mixed feelings'' about the
president's letter _ glad that Bush was able to make the report he
did, but still worried about the Pakistani program _ and expects to
hold hearings on the matter.
</TEXT>
