<FIRST>r w PM-Census-Aliens     10-12 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Census-Aliens,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Refuses to Consider Census Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators will decide
whether illegal aliens will be excluded from next year's census
following the House's refusal to take up the issue on its own.
   The House voted Wednesday not to take up the measure, which has
pitted Sunbelt states whose populations have been swollen by
illegal aliens against Frostbelt states that stand to lose House
seats after the census.
   By a 232-184 vote, the House used a parliamentary maneuver
steered by Rep. Silvio O. Conte, R-Mass., to keep the census
measure off the floor.
   That vote instructed House negotiators to accept a provision in
the Senate version of the State, Justice and Commerce
appropriations bill to condemn the continuation in power of Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega in Panama. The rules permit only one set of
instructions to a conference committee.
   The move blocked Rep. Thomas Ridge, R-Pa., from offering his own
set of instructions on the census question to the House members of
the same committee.
   Ridge's provisions would have ordered the House negotiators to
accept another Senate-passed provision, this one to barring the use
of any money for the Census Bureau to count illegal aliens in its
1990 head count.
   The census bureau has always counted residents regardless of
citizenship. Past efforts to exclude illegal aliens from the count
have always died in committee.
   Under current census rules, California, Florida and Texas, with
many illegal aliens, expect to gain House seats and New York,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and Illinois are among those expected
to lose seats.
   ``The question is simple,'' Ridge said. ``Are people who have
entered our country illegally entitled to representation in the
United States Congress? I say no.''
   Even though it was apparent they would not have a chance to get
a vote on the Ridge proposal, backers of the census change used the
hour devoted to the Noriega censure to debate the census issue.
   Ridge and others characterized it as a matter of political
fairness. ``I want equal representation for American citizens,''
argued Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa.
   Opponents argued that any change in census rules at this point
would cost $1 billion, including the cost of reprinting forms and
retraining the census-takers. They said it was not clear counters
could even get accurate information on citizenship.
   Opponents have said the Senate provision is clearly
unconstitutional, since the Constitution requires a census of
``persons.'' When the Constitution wants something to apply only to
citizens, it clearly says ``citizens,'' according to this argument.
</TEXT>
