<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-12 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher against the Japanese
yen Thursday, while share prices dove on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 144.60 yen, up 0.70 yen from Wednesday's
143.90-yen finish. It opened at 144.25 yen, and moved between
143.70 yen and 144.65 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 444.73
points, or 1.26 percent, to 34,795.34. It was this year's
second-largest one-day loss, following a 489.90-point decline June
15, dealers said.
   Many stock players sold issues in fear of another discount rate
increase, since Wednesday's increase seemed to have failed to
support the yen, said Masaya Hashizume, a dealer with Nikko
Securities.
   ``The most discouraging factor was the dollar's strength despite
the rate hike, not the hike itself,'' he said.
   Investors sold issues, such as constructions, that they had
bought because of the yen's strength.
   The Bank of Japan raised its official discount rate, the key
lending rate charged commercial banks, by 0.5 percent to 3.75
percent. The discount rate also affects other domestic interest
rates, and discourages stock investment.
   Satoshi Sumita, Bank of Japan's governor, told a news conference
Wednesday the central bank made the hike in consideration of recent
flucutuations in exchange markets, domestic economic trends,
consumer prices and the money supply.
   In currency dealings, ``market players were still inclined to
buy the dollar because of the Greenspan comment Tuesday, which had
a much stronger impact on the market than the Bank of Japan's
discount rate hike,'' Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank
in Tokyo, said.
   U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted to
U.S. and Soviet officials in Moscow on Tuesday that the Fed would
not ease U.S. interest rates in the near term regardless of the
currency's movements.
   Citing the yen's weakness despite the discount rate hike,
Takeuchi blamed the Greenspan comments for the worsening foreign
exchange fluctuations.
   A trader with the Bank of Tokyo said Wednesday, ``There is good
demand for the dollar, though the market remains a bit nervous.''
   Stock players were concerned whether the Federal Reserve Board
would lower its official interest rates based on the U.S. wholesale
price index for September, which is due Friday, the Bank of Tokyo
trader said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Market analysts say a discount rate cut by the U.S. central bank
would be the best remedy to halt the dollar's excessive rise after
a series of discount rate hikes in Europe and Japan, in addition to
concerted central bank interventions.
   Interest rate reductions tend to weaken the value of a currency.
</TEXT>
