<FIRST>r w PM-CruiseShips     10-12 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Ships,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Needs Tighter Control Over Cruise Ships, Board Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard should tighten control over
the safety of cruise ships that carry 7 million passengers a year,
the National Transportation Safety Board says.
   The board on Wednesday approved a series of recommendations for
the Coast Guard, cruise ship lines, operators of other passenger
ships and states for improving the safety of small and large
passenger vessels.
   Board member Jim Burnett said 264 people have died in passenger
ship accidents in the United States in the last 25 years.
   He acknowledged that is not many fatalities compared to the more
than 1,000 annual deaths in small boating accidents. ``But the
potential is there for a disaster that could double that figure in
one incident,'' said Burnett.
   Major foreign-flagged cruise vessels regularly carry hundreds of
Americans out of U.S. ports while remaining largely free of U.S.
regulation, he said.
   The five-member board, which oversees safety for all modes of
transportation, cited untrained crews that speak no English, a lack
of life vests, inadequate safety equipment, unsafe ship designs and
other problems on the foreign-flagged pleasure ships operating out
of U.S. ports.
   Burnett said solving the problems could be costly for some ship
operators but could save hundreds of lives.
   The panel also called for far more Coast Guard vigilance over
domestic passenger vessels and recommended that states also more
closely regulate the safety of boats operating on their waterways.
   The recommendations were accompanied by a study of passenger
ship safety which covered 36 passenger vessel accidents or
incidents that killed 176 people and injured another 364 in the
last 15 years.
   Although only five of the fatalities were in foreign-flagged
cruise ship accidents, board members said the potential for a major
catastrophe is high. The ships regularly carry several hundred
passengers but often have no plans for handling a major emergency,
investigators said.
   ``We're seeing a lot of vessels 10 years old with a brand new
coat of paint but lacking any of the safety equipment we're seeing
on newer vessels,'' said James Kolstad, acting board chairman.
   The board can only recommend actions and has no rule-making
powers. Its final report, which is to be edited and revised before
release, will be sent to Congress, the Coast Guard, passenger ship
companies and other interested parties.
   The board asked the Coast Guard to seek authority to investigate
accidents in international waters involving passenger vessels that
regularly operate out of U.S. ports, regardless of the flag they
fly.
   Investigations now usually are conducted by the country where
the ship is registered, and board officials say the inquiries often
do little to protect the safety interests of U.S. citizens. Nearly
all U.S. cruise companies register their ships in countries where
requirements are less strict than those for U.S.-registered ships.
   The board urged that all passenger vessels operating out of U.S.
ports be required to meet international safety regulations as well
as additional requirements.
   The report called for centralized fire control systems, heat and
smoke detectors with automatic fire door releases, sprinkler
systems, fire doors with holes for hoses to pass through and an
English-speaking crew that can communicate with each other and
passengers in an emergency.
   John Lauber, another board member, said passenger ship companies
have been ``driving through loopholes'' in the law that allow them
to escape safety regulations applying to larger vessels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
