<FIRST>r w PM-US-Germany     10-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Germany,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans See Little Choice for East Germany But Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's communist leaders have little
choice but to make reforms like those in the Soviet Union under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, say two top West German military
officials.
   ``It's inconceivable that (East Germany) will stay as it is'' in
view of changes in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary, West
German Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg told reporters after
meeting with President Bush.
   Stoltenberg, who met with Bush on Tuesday, and NATO
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner, a former West German defense
minister who visited Bush on Wednesday, held separate news
conferences on Wednesday.
   They both said East Germany and other East European countries
will face mounting problems if they continue to resist reforms.
   ``The major disagreeable thing for them is that if they continue
... their tough repression, they will not be able to manage the
change, they will not be able to peacefully develop their
countries,'' Woerner said.
   Stoltenberg added: ``If they do not move, there could be even
further growing tensions. And you could imagine some very dangerous
developments we all should want to avoid.''
   But Stoltenberg said East German reforms won't lead to
reunification of East and West Germany anytime soon. Reunification
would have to wait until democracy spreads through the rest of
Eastern Europe and could be accomplished within German
confederation in the larger European Community, he said.
   West German officials understood from Soviet authorities that
Gorbachev's public calls for greater flexibility by East Germany
were repeated in his private meetings with East German leader Erich
Honecker, said Stoltenberg.
   ``Indications give us the impression that he said, `You must go
on and move ahead; otherwise, the situation gets dangerous,'''
Stoltenberg said.
   Honecker indicated on Saturday that he planned to stick to his
hard-line approach as his country tries to stem the flow of its
citizens to the West. More than 100,000 East Germans have fled this
year, some of them by climbing over walls into the embassies of
western nations.
   The East German Communist Party's Politburo issued a statement
Wednesday indicating far more flexibility. ``All expressions of
opinion and suggestions for attractive socialism in the GDR (East
Germany) are important,'' it said. ``We are open to discussions.''
   Gorbachev is working to keep the Warsaw Pact together while
revitalizing COMECON, the Soviet bloc economic counterpart to the
European Economic Community, said Stoltenberg.
   Gorbachev ``may not like all attitudes and decisions of the
communist leadership in East Berlin, (but) he wants to keep them in
the camp and work with them,'' he said.
   The defense minister said Gorbachev appears ready ``to tolerate
remarkable special movements'' in different East European
countries, but that ``the Warsaw Pact stays together'' even if in a
new form.
   Stoltenberg arrived in Washington Monday and has met U.S.
officials including Vice President Dan Quayle, Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney and Secretary of State James A. Baker III. He is due to
visit U.S. and German forces at military bases in Norfolk, Va., and
Texas before returning to West Germany Friday.
   Woerner has been holding similar meetings.
</TEXT>
