<FIRST>r w PM-Thornburgh'sTravels     10-12 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh's Travels,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Travels Cost Twice As Much as Predecessor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department paid the FBI $730 to
fly Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to Pittsburgh May 15 and spent
$5,260 for the return trip the next day on a Marshals Service jet,
government records show.
   The twin-engine Marshals Service jet flew from Oklahoma City to
take Thornburgh back to Washington after the attorney general voted
in the Pennsylvania primary, met with FBI agents and was
interviewed by a hometown radio station.
   The May 16 return flight was one of three trips Thornburgh took
aboard Marshals Service aircraft in the last five months at a total
cost of $80,181, according to travel records released by Justice
Department spokesman David Runkel.
   The figures show Thornburgh spent $154,618 for 47 flights on
government aircraft between Oct. 7, 1988 and Sept. 4, 1989. That
was more than twice the travel expenses incurred by his predecessor
during a comparable time period.
   Trips by former Attorney General Edwin Meese III cost the
government $74,247 between Oct. 1, 1987 and when he left office
Aug. 8, 1988, Runkel said.
   Runkel acknowledged Thornburgh has traveled more frequently than
Meese but attributed much of the greater cost to ``the incredible
charges of the Marshals Service'' for their planes.
   ``The attorney general told me when he saw those charges for the
first time he ordered ... those charges reviewed to determine if
the department is being ripped off,'' said Runkel.
   He said Thornburgh told him the charges ``appear to be
outrageous and that he wants them looked at again.''
   U.S. Marshals Service spokesman Stephen T. Boyle said the
Justice Department's accountants ``went over the bills in some
detail before they reimbursed us to determine if they were indeed
valid and justifiable and apparently felt they were because they
paid the bill'' for all three flights.
   Boyle said the bills reflected the costs of fuel the Marshals
Service used to fly the planes.
   A letter Boyle wrote last week to two news organizations
detailing the travel expenses said the twin-engine jet Thornburgh
took for the Pittsburgh-to-Washington flight was requested May 12,
three days before the attorney general left Washington on the FBI
turboprop.
   Runkel made Boyle's letter and a similar response by FBI
spokesman Milt Ahlerich available to reporters. The letters were
written in response to questions from The New York Times and the
Los Angeles Times.
   The Marshals Service also listed a $46,792 bill for Thornburgh's
Aug. 6-9 trip to Mexico City for meetings with Mexican officials
and to Honolulu, where the attorney general addressed the American
Bar Association.
   Following the Mexico City meetings, Thornburgh and several aides
flew from San Francisco to Honolulu aboard a Boeing 727 normally
used by the Marshals Service to transport prisoners.
   In addition to the expenses it billed the Justice Department,
the Marshals Service estimated that it cost $32,232 to divert the
Boeing 727 from carrying federal prisoners.
   Thornburgh and his aides also flew a twin-engine Marshals
Service jet on a June 12-14 trip to Texas at a cost of $28,118.
   Runkel said Thornburgh has been flying aboard government
aircraft because of FBI concerns about his personal security and
the secrecy of his communications while in flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
