<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Martinez     10-12 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Martinez,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Special Session on Abortion Ends in Futility</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Florida Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Democrats are already claiming
that Gov. Bob Martinez' losing bid to place further restrictions on
abortion will hurt his re-election chances next year.
   The Legislature defeated a series of anti-abortion proposals by
the governor, then adjourned its special session Wednesday. Florida
taxpayers spent more than $100,000 for the fruitless session, the
third called by the governor this year.
   Even the first-term Republican governor's glib campaign manager,
J.M. ``Mac'' Stipanovich, wasn't his usual talkative self. ``I'm
not going to spin it,'' he said. ``It's an issue he feels strongly
about. I'm going to let him do it.''
   Martinez said he was unconcerned about taking a political risk
on abortion. ``I stood for my convictions,'' he said. ``I don't
think the people in any state have an adverse feeling for someone
who stands up for his convictions.
   ``With me, it was a matter of value, a matter of conviction, not
a matter of politics.''
   House Republican Leader Dale Patchett and Sen. Richard Langley
said they thought the session may have helped the governor slightly
by solidifying his support among anti-abortionists.
   ``I think the governor will have a net gain,'' Langley said.
``People have got to respect him. He knew it was not a popular
thing to do, but it was a genuine conviction of his.''
   State Republican Chairman Van Poole also was busy Wednesday
trying to repair any damage done to the GOP's lead candidate for
next year. ``He had a lot of courage to call this session,'' said
Poole.
   Many Democrats said Martinez would pay the price at the polls
next year for his anti-abortion stance.
   ``The governor's profile as a blundering manager, as a
blundering political strategist who cannot read the sentiment of
the people of Florida is now carved in stone,'' said Party Chairman
Simon Ferro. ``There's nothing he can do to chisel away at it and
make it better. That is the profile Floridians are going to be
voting for or against next year.''
   State Sen. George Stuart, who is seeking the Democratic
gubernatorial nomination, said Martinez wasted taxpayers' money by
insisting on the session.
   And the chairman of the House Health Care Committee, Rep. Elaine
Gordon, said Martinez ``has awakened a sleeping giant and they will
be there to help him be defeated.''
   On Tuesday, Republican state Sen. Marlene Woodson-Howard decided
she would challenge Martinez for the GOP nomination come September.
   ``This is costing the governor a great deal,'' said Eleanor
Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority. ``If
nothing else, he's seeing a primary he might not otherwise have.''
   Although the abortion issue itself wasn't the key reason for her
candidacy, Woodson-Howard said the governor's insistence on the
unpopular session was another example of ignoring lawmakers' wishes.
   ``He didn't build consensus and he didn't count his votes, and I
think that's crucial,'' she said.
</TEXT>
