<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     10-12 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says 315 Missing After Search for Guerrillas' Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. investigators have found no
evidence to support charges the SWAPO guerrilla movement still
holds political prisoners _ but also failed to determine the
whereabouts of 315 alleged detainees, a U.N. official says.
   Martti Ahtisaari, head of the U.N. contingent monitoring
Namibia's transition to independence, said Wednesday that the
search for the missing people would nevertheless continue.
   Under the U.N.'s independence plan, both the South-West Africa
People's Organization and the South African-led security forces
were required to release all prisoners.
   Many of the more than 200 people freed by SWAPO alleged that
hundreds of others had been held along with them and either were
dead or still in custody.
   Ahtisaari sent an eight-member investigating team last month to
Angola and Zambia, where SWAPO maintained camps during its 23-year
bush war against South African rule of Namibia.
   The team's report, released Wednesday, said 448 of 1,100
allegedly missing people were alive and free, 71 were found to have
never been detained and 115 were believed to have died in
circumstances that were not specified. Others could not be
identified and 315 were unaccounted for.
   The U.N. investigators said they visited 30 locations in Angola
and Zambia during their three-week trip, including six sites where
prisons definitely operated. They said the prisons had been
dismantled and vacated.
   Ahtisaari said the team found no evidence that the alleged
detainees had been moved from any of the locations.
   Many of the former SWAPO detainees have alleged they were kept
in underground pits and tortured persistently into making false
confessions that they were South African spies. SWAPO officials
have acknowledged torture did take place.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I, but agreed
last year to grant independence as part of a regional treaty that
also calls for withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's
northern neighbor.
   SWAPO is favored to win the most votes in U.N.-supervised
elections Nov. 7-11 for an assembly that will draft a constitution
for an independent Namibia. It must win two-thirds of the votes to
have total control over the assembly.
</TEXT>
