<FIRST>r w PM-BradyLawsuit     10-12 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady Lawsuit,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former White House Press Secretary Loses Lawsuit Against Gun Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House press secretary James Brady
cannot recover damages from the maker of the handgun used by John
Hinckley in a 1981 assassination attempt on President Reagan, an
appeals court has ruled.
   The District of Columbia Court of Appeals ruled Wednesday that
R.G. Industries Inc. and its German parent company, Roehm, cannot
be held responsible for injuries received by Brady and Washington
D.C., police officer Thomas Delahanty.
   The appeals court rejected an argument by attorneys for Brady
and Delahanty that the .22-caliber pistol Hinckley used in the
shooting was inherently dangerous.
   ``The marketing of a handgun is not dangerous in and of itself,
but rather the result of actions taken by a third party,'' the
court said.
   Brady told The Washington Post he was disappointed by the
decision and that he hoped state legislatures would consider
enacting laws to establish the right to sue gun manufacturers.
   ``They're the ones that make them in the first place. And that's
what bothers me,'' Brady said.
   Brady, Delahanty and Secret Service agent Timothy McCarthy were
wounded along with Reagan in Hinckley's assassination attempt. A
suit the three men filed against Hinckley is pending in federal
court.
   Brady's wife, Sara, has become a national spokeswoman in the
campaign to ban the sale of handguns and to register firearms.
</TEXT>
