<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Pope     10-12 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Clash Breaks Out During Pope's Visits to Former Portuguese Territory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O`LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DILI, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banner-waving youths opposed to
Indonesian rule of East Timor fought baton-wielding police in the
territory today before the altar where Pope John Paul II was
finishing his benediction to about 60,000 people.
   At least four people were injured.
   Hurling chairs and shouting ``Viva independence!'' and ``Viva
Papa!'' about 20 youths unfurled a banner in front of the the altar.
   As the pope looked on, plainclothes police hit the youths with
canes. Much of the crowd scattered, but about 100 people came to
the aid of the youths, hurling chairs at the police.
   The protesters were supporters of Fretilin, the pro-independence
movement that has been fighting Indonesian troops since the
Portuguese left the former colony in 1975 and it was annexed by
Indonesia.
   They got to within 100 feet of the steps to the high altar where
the pope stood watching. The pope did not seem directly threatened.
   In his homily, the pontiff had urged Indonesia to respect the
human rights of the people of predominantly Catholic East Timor,
which comprises half of Timor Island in the southeastern reaches of
the Indonesian archipelago.
   As white-cassocked priests and seminarians moved quickly to calm
the crowd, the pope, surrounded by Vatican and Indonesian
bodyguards, moved toward his car.
   From there he went directly to the airport as scheduled and flew
off to Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, the world's most populous
Moslem country. After he left, youths began to chant ``Viva
Fretilin!''
   Dili General Hospital reported four women admitted after the
incident, all of whom had been battered by the surging crowd.
   There was no immediate report of arrests.
   Girl Scouts, who had been serving as ushers in front of the
altar, wept as they were caught up in the clash. The incident
lasted about 15 minutes. The crowd then left the dusty arena
peacefully.
   Security at the Mass was light and provided by unarmed police
and militia. The Indonesian army, which has a garrison of 13,000 in
East Timor, was apparently not deployed.
   Indonesia admits to having suffered ``thousands of casualties''
in the guerrilla war over the territory Portual ruled for 450
years. Indonesia had dismissed the strength of the separatist
guerrillas, saying only 200 remain in the hinterland.
   In his homily, the pope made no direct mention of Indonesian
rule, which is not recognized by the Vatican, but referred instead
to ``those who are responsible for life in East Timor.''
   Addressing the crowd, the pope urged Indonesia to ``act with
wisdom and good will towards all'' in the search for a peaceful
solution to East Timor's problems.
   Referring to the anti-Indonesian guerrilla war, the pope said
East Timorese had ``experienced destruction and death as a result
of conflict.''
   ``You have known what it means to be victims of hatred and
struggle,'' he said. ``Many innocent people have died while others
have been prey to retaliation and revenge.
   ``For too long you have been suffering a lack of stability which
has rendered your future uncertain. This distressing situation''
has prevented the economic development needed to prevent hunger and
unemployment.
   The pope urged Indonesia to bring about ``a speedy improvement
of conditions of life'' in East Timor.
   The visit came on the fourth day of his pilgrimage to Indonesia.
   The pope was met by Defense Minister Benny Murdani, the former
army commander who planned the takeover of East Timor. Murdani is
the highest placed Roman Catholic in the government of Indonesia,
which has 157 million Moslems and 5 million Catholics.
   Indonesia has been anxious for the visit to be seen to lend
respectability if not official recognition to its rule of East
Timor, which has a population of 590,000, of whom almost 80 percent
are Catholic, according to the Vatican.
   The pope had justified his visit by saying it would be ``an
offense to Timorse Catholics'' if he did not visit the former
Portuguese colony while on a state visit to Indonesia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0504EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Panama-CoupWidow     10-12 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Coup Widow,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widow of Panama Coup Leader Says He Was Betrayed By Comrade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of the leader of an unsuccessful coup
against Panama Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega said the military
uprising failed because a second military leader pulled a
last-minute double-cross.
   Adela Bonilla de Giroldi said in interviews published today that
the switch helped doom efforts by her husband, Maj. Moises Giroldi
Vega, to overthrow Noriega last week.
   Giroldi, his widow said, planned the coup with a longtime
friend, Maj. Francisco Oleochea, commander of the elite Battalion
2000.
   Battalion 2000, a crack anti-riot unit, was airlifted to the
scene of the fighting and _ instead of helping oust Noriega _ went
on to lead troops loyal to Noriega in crushing the coup.
   ``Everything was ready,'' Mrs. Giroldi told The New York Times.
``But Oleochea was playing a winner's game and he failed to come
through because of his cowardice. He committed treason.''
   In an interview with The Miami Herald, she countered U.S.
officials' assertions that leaders of the failed coup were divided
over what to do with the Panamanian leader.
   ``Everything was perfectly coordinated,'' Mrs. Giroldi said. ``I
don't think there ever was a dispute.''
   She told the Times the coup was ``very well organized and coldly
calculated.''
   Mrs. Giroldi, 36, told both newspapers the U.S. military in
Panama had been informed in advance of the coup, and the coup had
been plotted by junior officers in the Panamanian Defense Forces
fed up with Noriega's alleged corruption and ``drunkenness.''
   But the Herald termed Mrs. Giroldi's responses ``evasive'' when
she was asked to what extent the U.S. military had promised to help
the rebels.
   ``My husband was convinced that the Americans and his own
companions within the defense forces would support him,'' she said.
   Mrs. Giroldi is staying with her three sons, her brother and her
father at a secret location in Miami. She was not at military
headquarters during the Oct. 3 coup attempt.
   She told the Times her information came from officers who took
part in the coup and fled to the United States.
   Mrs. Giroldi also told the Herald that her husband may have lost
the last chance for a successful coup by not killing Noriega.
   ``My husband may have had a moment of weakness,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
