<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-12 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Review Questions $4.7 in Spending By Housing Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Antonio Housing Authority may have
violated state or federal laws through questionable spending
practices that exceeded $4.7 million, according to a federal report.
   A review by the inspector general's office at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development also said the San Antonio agency
should be required to pay back $84,260 it spent for such items as
Rotary Club membership fees and banquets.
   The investigators say the housing authority had $4.7 million in
questionable spending and have recommended that the HUD regional
administrator in Fort Worth require an accounting of where that
money went.
   In the Oct. 3 review, investigators reported possible violations
of law or conflicts of interest in several areas, including
procurement and contracting practices and the use of non-profit
corporations.
   Apolono Flores, the housing agency's executive director,
disputed the allegations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>USDA Suspends Company From Export Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss-based grain company has been suspended
by the Agriculture Department from participating in a farm export
program because of the firm's ties to a fugitive commodities trader
in Switzerland.
   The company, Richco Grain Ltd., has received $95 million worth
of government-owned grain as subsidies under the Export Enhancement
Program since 1986.
   USDA temporarily suspended the company effective Sept. 29
because of its connections to Marc Rich and a Rich associate,
Pincus Green. Both fled to Switzerland in 1983 before their
indictment for criminal tax evasion, racketeering, mail and wire
fraud.
   Robert Thomajan, an attorney for Richco, said the company would
appeal the USDA action.
</TEXT>
