<FIRST>r a PM-LostTickets     10-12 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost Tickets,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Tosses World Series Tickets in Trash; Finds Them at Dump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor and his wife went rummaging
through the dump for World Series tickets after he unwittingly left
the precious ducats with other papers that had to be thrown away.
   Dr. Michael Smith and his wife, Pam, ended up raking through 3
tons of trash at the Marina garbage disposal site Tuesday before
finally finding them.
   The 43-year-old gastroenterologist had attended the final
National League playoff game Monday with his 12-year-old son, Rory.
Afterward, they left their Series tickets in the car.
   The next morning, when Smith started looking for the tickets,
the tickets were nowhere to be found. He figured they had been
thrown out and called Forest Disposal Co. to try to head off the
trash truck.
   Mia Litch of the Monterey Regional Waste Management District
radioed the landfill operators to clear a site for the Smiths to
wade through the garbage.
   ``The people were real nice at the dump,'' said Smith.
   Truck driver David Hare dumped the garbage and spread it out for
the Smiths, who recognized some of their garbage. Heartened, they
dove into the pile. Two hours later, the Smiths found the slightly
soiled tickets.
   ``It was not real pleasant,'' said Smith. ``But I tell you, the
outcome was worth it. My son and I are going to the games to see
the Giants win.''
</TEXT>
