<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Syria     10-12 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Syria,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Begins Into Reports Syrian Fighter Flew Into Israel Undetected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel launched a top-level probe today into
reports a Syrian major flew a MiG-23 fighter jet undetected across
one of Israel's most sophisticated defense lines before landing at
a civilian airfield.
   The seven minutes that the Syrian pilot spent in Israeli air
space before landing and defecting caused an uproar over possible
flaws in the air defense system.
   The daily Yediot Ahronot's main headline questioned ``How a MiG
Flew for Seven Minutes _ Without Interference.'' The
English-language Jerusalem Post ran a front-page analysis about
upgraded Syrian air attack capabilities.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin was angered that he did not even
know about the flight until after it landed, the Hadashot daily
reported.
   The investigation was launched by Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan
Shomron at the urging of Rabin, Israel radio said. It said a
brigadier general was heading the probe.
   Both Israel radio stations and most newspapers reported the air
force failed to scramble inteceptors before the Syrian
fighter-bomber landed near Haifa, a city of 250,000.
   Syria is Israel's most implacable foe in the Middle East. The
Golan Heights, over which the Soviet-built plane swooped into
Israel, were annexed by Israel after being seized from Syria in the
1967 Middle East war.
   The Davar newspaper said the plane came across the Golan at a
level of just 100 feet at a speed of 745 mph.
   Witnesses said the plane buzzed houses in the northern town of
Afula flying at 165 feet and town council leaders demanded to know
why civil defense officials were not warned, Israel radio reported.
   Members of the left-wing Citizens Rights Movement and the
right-wing Tehiyia Party called for a paraliamentary debate on the
flight.
   Rabin said the plane was detected by Israeli radar officers and
patrol aircraft, but refused to confirm or deny reports that the
air force failed to scramble fighters to intercept the Syrian
warplane.
   ``All this will be clarified after a full inquiry into the
matter,'' he said.
   The radio said the MiG-23 was carrying two 23-mm cannons and 200
rounds of ammunition but its bomb racks were empty.
   The plane, flown by Maj. Adel Basem, 34, landed before noon at
an airfield used by crop-dusting planes at Megiddo, 60 miles north
of Jerusalem, an army communique said. Israel radio said Basem
asked for asylum.
   Workers at the airstrip said they were stunned by the plane's
arrival.
   The plane turned around on the runway ``and the pilot got out
and said, `I am asking for asylum, I have no intentions of war,'''
the Haaretz newspaper quoted one as saying.
   The radio and major dailies said Basem sat in a supply building
at a corner in the airfield for 20 minutes before air force
officials arrived. Other witnesses said they saw no Israeli escort
planes.
   Davar quotes Basem as telling an airstrip worker that he
defected because of poor treatement in the army, including one
incident in which secret police broke his arm and hit him in the
ribs after he requested better housing.
   In Damascus, a Syrian official said the pilot did not defect but
was forced to make an emergency landing. An Israeli army spokesman
denied the plane had technical problems.
   The craft had no visible signs of an engine fire reported by
Syria.
   Rabin indicated Israel could tell that the Syrian plane had no
hostile intentions, but refused to provide details, saying:
   ``It's difficult to explain the difference between an airplane
coming to carry out an operation ... and a pilot deciding to cross
the border during a training flight.''
   He defended Israel's handling of the affair, saying:
   ``In this case, it's good we did not shoot it down. We got an
advanced MiG-23 of the MLD version. It's one of the most advanced
versions of MiG-23 supplied to the Syrians after 1982.''
   ``Of course it will serve as a source of information for us and
the others,'' including the United States, Rabin said.
</TEXT>
