<FIRST>r i PM-Fashion 1stLd-Writethru a0501 10-12 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fashion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short Hemlines, Bare Midriffs Dominate Milan Runway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIL1</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DANIELA PETROFF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sexy clothes with lots of bare skin have
become a symbol of the ``moda Milanese.''
   A year ago Gianni Versace introduced his Band-Aid mini skirt, no
more than 12 inches from top to bottom. There were few who dared to
don the skimpy garment, but the message caught on quickly.
   Above the knee hemlines became a way of life.
   For the spring-summer 1990, the trend to hike the hemline
continues, with mid-thigh the preferred length. In the wake of the
mini, designers are also showing a myriad of short-petticoated
party dresses and short shorts.
   For those who prefer to keep their knees to themselves, the
Milan runway offers lots of pants, either super loose or skin tight
and airy chiffon dresses and skirts which flow softly down to the
ankle.
   But the real novelty in the sexy department is the above the
waist nude look.
   Models with bare backs, bare midriffs, even bare breasts paraded
down the runway in a myriad of bra tops, bustiers, low-back dresses
and see-through blouses. To emphasize the look, Giorgio Armani in
his Emporio collection sent a model down the runway in nothing but
a pair of Armani jeans.
   This accent on the female torso spells good news for beauty
farms and fitness centers. No one will want to be caught with the
proverbial midriff bulge.
   In general, the 40 Italian designers showing their warm weather
wears in Milan this week, including Armani, Versace, Ferre, Krizia
and Fendi have each gone their individual way, with less of a
common thread to the collections than in past seasons.
   However they have all agreed to promote one item _ the fringe.
Usually long and silky it appears on shawls and scarves, as well as
decoration on any type of clothing. Often it makes up the hemline
of a skirt or dress.
   In the color department the news is that bright shades are back
on the Milan runway after many a season of drab grays and browns.
Designers draw inspiration for their cheerful palette, from the
rich colors of tropical fruit, or the many fruit flavors of Italian
ice cream: mango, banana, papaya, coconut, kiwi, raspberry,
apricot, peach, watermelon, orange, lemon, lime and many more.
   Footwear for next spring and summer will be mostly flat by day,
and sometimes even by night.
   The newest shoe is the Krizia ankle strap platform shoe, taken
right out of the 1940's.
   Gold and beads are back in a big way, appearing in large
bracelets, necklaces and earrings, as well as decoration and
sequining in the more eleborate evening wear.
   The five-day, semi-annual Italian ready to wear shows end
Thursday night with a gala performance by Moscow's Bolshoi theater,
at Milan's famed La Scala opera house, followed by a buffet dinner
in the foyer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrug     10-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Distributing AIDS-linked Pneumonia-Fighting Drug Free to
Poor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of a drug used to combat AIDS-linked
pneumonia is giving it free to poor patients, but those who can
afford to pay for treatment will continue to do so, company
officials said.
   Lyphomed Inc. in February announced plans to give away the drug,
pentamidine, but actual distribution was held up until June pending
full government approval of the drug, spokeswoman Melissa Marsden
said Wednesday.
   The company, based in suburban Rosemont, charges about $100
wholesale for a monthly dose. Patients pay up to $200 for the same
dose through doctors and pharmacies.
   AIDS activists and others have accused Lyphomed of overcharging
for the substance. But the company maintains its charge is
appropriate, given the research money it spent developing the drug.
   Community health organizations have been notified of the
availablity of pentamidine for the poor and for those who lack
insurance to cover its costs.
   The company said it will send supplies of the drug several times
a year to groups of doctors who have large AIDS practices in New
York, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Houston, Dallas, Chicago and
Miami. The groups are filling out questionnaires that ask them how
much pentamidine they think they will need. The company said it
also may send the drug to other groups.
   Lyphomed's action represents the first time a company has
distributed an approved drug to poor patients free of charge,
company officials and federal Food and Drug Administration
spokesman Brad Stone told The New York Times.
   Since 1984, Lyphomed has produced an injectable form of the drug
for use in patients who already have contracted pneumocystis
carinii pneumonia, a life-threatening form of pneumonia that is the
leading cause of death among AIDS patients.
   In June, the company obtained approval for marketing an aerosol
version to be taken once every four weeks as a preventive measure
by people likely to contract that form of pneumonia.
   Last month, the People With AIDS Health Group said it would
import the drug from England, where is it cheaper, and sell it to
AIDS patients in this country at a lower cost than the drug can be
bought here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
