<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-12 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cooler Temperatures Over Plains; Winds in the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm over central Canada brought cooler temperatures to the
northern Great Lakes today and the Pacific Northwest was shrouded
in clouds.
   Temperatures were in the 80s Wednesday as far north as southern
Minnesota and western Wisconsin, into the 90s in Nebraska and 94 in
Dodge City, Kan., but began falling in the night.
   Temperatures dipped to near freezing early today in parts of New
York state, patchy fog covered parts of northern New England and
Maryland and rain fell in the Pacific Northwest. Elsewhere in the
country, it was mostly fair.
   Winds gusted to 55 mph at Ames Monument, between Cheyenne and
Laramie, Wyo.
   Skies were clear in most of the eastern and southern parts of
the country Wednesday, with a few showers over Florida, central
Georgia, parts of Wisconsin and Minnesota and along the northern
Pacific Coast.
   Other reports early today:
