<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ComingOutDay     10-12 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coming Out Day,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homosexuals Hold `Coming Out' Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of those who attended a second annual ``National Coming Out
Day'' around the country acknowledged that they were veterans of
homosexual-pride events, and they said the real ``coming out''
process is done privately.
   ``My coming out was when I opened the dictionary at age 14 and
looked up the word `homosexual' and realized that applies to me,''
said John Blakeslee, 34, of Providence, R.I.
   Blakeslee was among some 50 people who attended a rowdy Rhode
Island Statehouse rally and said they hoped it would encourage
others to seek out the state's homosexual community rather than
isolating themselves in despair.
   ``Gay youth has three times the risk for suicide as straight
teens,'' said Jon Winkleman, 22, of Warwick, R.I. ``When I was a
teen, I was afraid that my parents would stop loving me.''
   Elsewhere, hundreds of homosexual men and women celebrated their
sexuality with rallies, films and discussions Wednesday.
   ``National Coming Out Day is great. It's like a holiday,'' said
Tony Cheek, executive assistant at the Los Angeles Gay and Lesbian
Community Services Center, where about 500 people gathered.
   The celebration at the center included discussion of such films
as ``The Life and Times of Harvey Milk,'' about San Francisco's
murdered homosexual city supervisor.
   Cheek said the day's highlight was an open microphone at which
people could tell their own stories of coming out _ slang for
publicly acknowledging one's homosexuality.
   ``Some were funny, but there were a lot of tear-jerkers,'' he
said. ``We had a lot of first-timers.''
   At the University of Massachusetts in Amherst, students were
asked to wear black or pink to support the celebration. Black,
always a popular choice of students, proliferated on campus by
midmorning.
   ``This campus is so diverse, civility and being aware of social
issues is really important,'' said Max Mitchell, a senior and
president of the school's Lesbian Bisexual and Gay Alliance.
   In Boston, the Massachusetts Senate gave all but final approval
Wednesday to a bill banning discrimination against homosexuals in
housing, credit and employment.
   The bill, which has died in the Senate for each of the last 17
years, moved along after Senate President William Bulger ruled that
amendments offered by several opponents were merely delaying
tactics.
   ``This really is the people's victory,'' David LaFontaine of the
Coalition for Lesbian and Gay Civil Rights. ``We are going to
herald this as a major step forward in the civil rights movement.''
   The Atlanta Gay Center sponsored a help-line and bought local
advertising to commemorate a homosexual rights march in Washington
two years ago. Homosexual residents had their names printed in the
ads as part of the commemoration.
   North of San Francisco Bay, the Marin County Board of
Supervisors voted 4-0 to proclaim Wednesday ``Marin Coming Out
Day,'' despite protests by evangelical ministers that the county
should not be endorsing homosexual lifestyles.
   Ken Searle, pastor at Marin Christian Life Church in Novato,
said he was ``very disappointed'' because the board's action ``will
be perceived by the community as an endorsement of the lifestyle.''
   Supervisor Al Aramburu, one of two who wore ``Coming Out''
buttons, said the proclamation reflects a ``spirit of respect.''
   ``I think we respect one another as human beings,'' he said.
   Cheek said holding the annual day helps end homophobia by
letting the heterosexual world know that there are homosexuals all
around them.
   ``If you find out your next door neighbor that you've known all
along is gay, then how can you hate him?'' Cheek said.
</TEXT>
