<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald 1stLd-Writethru a0481 10-12 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Tribal Chairman Accused of Bribery, Fraud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY that MacDonald was not charged
in all 11 counts; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, MacDonald's son ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE GAP, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navajos' suspended chairman has been
charged with taking more than $400,000 in bribes and kickbacks
while leader of the nation's biggest Indian tribe. He promised to
``stand up and fight'' the allegations.
   The criminal complaints filed Wednesday in Navajo Tribal Court
also included charges of fraud, conspiracy and elections violations
against the suspended chairman, Peter MacDonald, who is under
investigation by a special U.S. Senate committee.
   Special prosecutors hired by the tribal council also filed
charges against MacDonald's son and the tribe's suspended vice
chairman.
   MacDonald was charged with more than 100 offenses. One complaint
charges him with bribery, fraud, ethics violations and conspiracy
in the tribe's purchase of the Big Boquillas Ranch in Arizona in
1987.
   A second complaint alleges violations of the Navajo election
law, including charges that MacDonald accepted $115,500 in
undocumented cash and services from non-Indians and corporations.
   A third charges him with bribery, extortion and other counts in
connection with consulting contracts MacDonald purportedly entered
into with outside businesses in 1986 through 1989. Prosecutors
allege he pocketed more than $300,000.
   MacDonald's son Peter ``Rocky'' MacDonald Jr. is charged with
conspiracy in the ranch purchase in a fourth complaint and
suspended Vice Chairman Johnny R. Thompson is accused of ethics
violations in a fifth.
   The elder MacDonald said the charges were only a rehash of
allegations that surfaced during last winter's U.S. Senate hearings.
   ``Those lazy, good-for-nothing lawyers'' spent thousands of
dollars to come up with nothing more than ``allegations using the
testimony of the Senate hearings,'' he said. The 60-year-old
MacDonald, who was put on paid administrative leave in February,
said he had no plans to resign.
   ``There's no reason to give up as long as I'm alive and I'm
breathing,'' he said. ``The cause is valid in terms of these people
(supporters), and knowing what is happening to Indian nations _
what has happened to the Navajo _ it affects my children and my
grandchildren, and I'll continue to stand up and fight.''
   Tribal Interim Chairman Leonard Haskie, meanwhile, said he asked
the federal government to speed up its investigation of allegations
that MacDonald shared in the $7.2 million profit turned by Tracey
Oil and Gas Co. of Scottsdale, which bought the Big Boquillas from
Tenneco West for $26.2 million and sold it to the Navajos less than
24 hours later for $33.4 million.
   The complaint filed Wednesday alleges that MacDonald used his
position to talk the council into allocating the money.
   The tribe is suing MacDonald and others for $24 million in
damages in the ranch purchase.
   In January, the Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs began
an investigation of the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs, but became
embroiled in probing corruption of various tribal leaders.
   The most prominent target was MacDonald, who was in his fourth
term at the helm of the 225,000-member tribe.
   Among witnesses who testified under immunity of MacDonald's
taking kickbacks from contractors were Rocky MacDonald, who said
under-the-table payments were referred to as ``golf balls.''
   The elder MacDonald has maintained that taking gifts is a
prerogative of Indian leaders.
   He repeated his claim that the federal government wants to oust
him and other tribal leaders so it can plunder the natural
resources on reservations.
   MacDonald made his comments Wednesday in this north-central
Arizona community about 150 miles northwest of the tribal capital
and 250 miles north of Phoenix.
   Appearance summonses will be mailed to MacDonald, his son and
Thompson. They have 14 days to respond, and no attempt will be made
to arrest the defendants until then, officials said.
   Special prosecutor Robert Rothstein said in Window Rock that he
and his Santa Fe, N.M., law firm investigated up to 100 past or
present tribal officials and did not focus only on MacDonald.
   If convicted on all counts, MacDonald could be sentenced to 15
years in prison, fined up to $59,500 and prevented from holding
public office on the reservation for 114 years.
   ``I'm glad they think I will live that long,'' he said.
</TEXT>
