<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USAToday     10-12 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USA Today,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Newspaper's Red Ink Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of USA Today, Gannett Co.'s
national newspaper, say the 7-year-old publication continues to
post losses and is experiencing a decline in advertising pages,
according to a published report.
   The Washington Post in today's editions quoted the officials as
saying Gannett's flagship paper probably would not be profitable
this year, but they were hopeful for its first full-year profit in
1990.
   ``Not making money this year is somewhat painful because it's
something we've been driving for,'' said Tom Curley, president and
chief operating officer of Arlington, Va.-based USA Today.
   Curley estimated that USA Today, in which Gannett has invested
$800 million, will end the year with about $2 million in losses,
down from a loss of $26 million in 1988.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``We consider it a hugely successful
year'' for the newspaper overall.
   The newspaper is being affected by an industry slowdown in
advertising and the opening of five new printing sites in the past
two years, Curley said.
   USA Today carried 785 pages of advertising in the third quarter,
Gannett reported Wednesday in its quarterly report. That was the
lowest total in almost three years. For the first nine months of
1989, the paper's ad pages were off 4 percent, but its ad revenue
was up 13 percent due to higher rates.
   Curley said USA Today's total revenues would increase to $320
million this year, up 7 percent from last year. He also told the
Post that circulation between April and September was 1.75 million,
an increase of about 100,000 from the same period last year.
   Gannett on Wednesday reported third-quarter earnings were up 11
percent to $83.1 million, or 52 cents per share from $75.1 million,
or 47 cents per share, last year.
   Newspaper industry analyst John Morton told the Post that USA
Today's chances of getting into the black next year depend on the
strength of the U.S. economy.
   ``If things continue to soften and national advertising is weak,
they could have another year like this one,'' Morton said. ``If
there's a recession, (profitability) would be hopeless.''
</TEXT>
