<HEAD>Kidnapped Infant Returned Safely, Woman Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abducted newborn has been reunited
with his teen-age mother, and a woman who had told neighbors she
was pregnant was booked for investigation of kidnapping.
   Debra Marie Lucas, 36, was jailed without bail Wednesday,
accused of abducting 6-pound, 1-ounce Lee Thao late Monday only
hours after his birth.
   Authorities said a woman in a visitor's gown approached the
mother in her room at Mercy General Hospital and told her she had
to take the baby for a feeding.
   The mother, Kazoua Thao, a 15-year-old Hmong immigrant who
speaks little English, told authorities she thought the woman was a
nurse.
   Sgt. Gary Gregson said police went to Lucas' home on a tip from
someone who identified her from a drawing distributed to TV
stations and newspapers.
   The child, in good condition, was found at Lucas' house and
reunited with his mother at the hospital.
   Lucas' neighbors said she had told them she was pregnant and had
taken a maternity leave from the convalescent home where she worked
as a licensived vocational nurse, Gregson said.
   ``But whether she was in fact pregnant is not known,'' he said.
