<SECOND>PM-Remains Found,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parolee Leads Police to Girl's Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parolee led police to skeletal remains
believed to be those of a kidnapped 11-year-old girl he said he
accidentally killed two years ago.
   Sheriff Howard Ensley said the remains were found late Wednesday
in a shallow grave near here and would be analyzed at the state
crime lab. ``I hope this is the little girl's body so it will bring
peace of mind to her family,'' he said.
   Charles Blassingame, 43, was brought to Georgia from Marinette,
Wis., on Tuesday to help find the body of Tammy Lynn Maciulis, who
disappeared from her mother's apartment in Marinette in 1987.
   Blassingame pleaded guilty in Marinette on Monday to kidnapping.
Under a plea bargain, he told authorities where the girl was buried.
   Blassingame was on parole from Georgia after serving seven years
for assault and burglary and had been living in the same apartment
complex as the girl. He was apprehended three days after her
disappearance.
   He told authorities he accidentally ran over her and drove to
Georgia to bury the body.
   Wisconsin prosecutors had said they would consider bringing
murder charges if a body were found. ``I just totally can't believe
he accidentally ran her over with his car,'' Marinette County
District Attorney Tim Duket said this week.
   Under the plea bargain reached in Marinette, Blassingame will
serve 25 years in prison for the kidnapping. Authorities said he
had agreed to plead guilty to extortion if Tammy Lynn's body were
not recovered.
