<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Police, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0518,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Finds Riot Squad Behavior Despicable, Acquits Officers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th, `The trial...' to ADD Rockman response.
Pickup 9th pvs, `The demonstration...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate today said white
riot police had acted despicably and unlawfully in an attack on
mixed-race demonstrators, but he acquitted their two commanding
officers of assault charges.
   A mixed-race policeman who had accused the riot squad of acting
like ``wild dogs'' called the verdict unbelievable.
   Magistrate A.S. McCarthy said there was no evidence the major
and lieutenant on the scene outside Cape Town on Sept. 5 witnessed
the assaults and they could thus not be held responsible for the
actions of their men.
   But McCarthy said the assaults in Mitchell's Plain township _
described by witnesses at the trial and shown in a subpoenaed
videotape from CBS News _ were illegal and despicable.
   In particular, he criticized the whipping of women on their
breasts.
   The videotape was shown on government television Wednesday and
today but edited to omit scenes showing police hitting people as
they lay on the ground.
   ``The court is astonished that these members cannot be
identified by the police, or if they can be identified, that they
are not in court,'' McCarthy said.
   The trial was prompted by allegations of mixed-race Mitchell's
Plain police officer Lt. Gregory Rockman, who said the squad
charged peaceful anti-election protesters with whips and clubs.
   ``It is ridiculous what the outcome was,'' Rockman told
reporters after learning the verdict. ``This means they can go
around beating people. I don't accept it.''
   He said he would press for a meeting with President F.W. de
Klerk to discuss his concerns about police violence.
   The demonstration ocurred the day before parliamentary
elections, from which members of the country's 28 million black
majority were excluded.
   Rockman testified that as he tried to get one riot squad away
from the area to decrease tension, another one charged and attacked
bystanders with glee.
   Rockman testified that Maj. Charles Brazelle, in charge of the
riot squad, threatened to arrest him when he asked him to stop the
attack.
   Brazelle was acquitted along with Lt. David Roos.
   The magistrate said national emergency regulations allow police
to use violence to end illegal demonstrations and give immunity to
the police if they act in good faith.
   The prosecution argued that the riot squad officers were not
protected by the emergency regulations in this case because it was
clear the demonstration, although illegal, posed no threat to
public safety or the police.
</TEXT>
