<HEAD>Two Deaths Reported in Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to CORRECT that two injured critically,
sted eight; recasts lead; picks up 6th graf: Armenian activists .. .</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were killed in clashes with authorities in
a restive territory claimed by both the republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan, a Soviet newspaper said today.
   The daily Komsomolskaya Pravda said S. Akonyan was killed late
Tuesday in a clash between soldiers and local residents in
Nagorno-Karabakh. R.E. Sadikov was killed Monday in the region, the
report said.
   It quoted military officials as saying they had arrested Sadikov
and confiscated a rifle from him but that he then attacked a
soldier and was killed trying to escape.
   In both cases, soldiers were injured, said the report.
   On Wednesday, Interior Ministry spokesman Yuri M. Arshenevsky
announced that eight people were injured, two critically, when
firefighters defended themselves against a crowd threatening them
with stones and firearms.
   Armenian activists in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, said one
person _ apparently Akonyan _ died in that clash.
   The bloody dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh has been going on 18
months. The region is in the republic of Azerbaijan, but the
majority of its citizens are Armenians. The republic of Armenia
wants control of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Kremlin officials have imposed direct rule in the area in an
effort to calm tensions.
   As part of the dispute, rail shipments through Azerbaijan to
Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia were cut off late this summer.
   The Azerbaijan People's Front political movement, which
organized a general strike that included a halt to rail shipments,
decided earlier this week to end the blockade.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said some freight was arriving in
Nagorno-Karabakh, but not food or fuel.
