<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the 30 House members who
voted one way in a vote on abortion restrictions on Sept. 9, 1988,
and then voted the opposite way on a virtually identical proposal
on Wednesday.
   In September 1988, the House voted 216-166 to stick by its more
restrictive provisions, limiting federal abortion aid to women
whose lives are endangered.
   On Wednesday, the House voted 216-206 to abandon its own
proposal, and instead adopt Senate language extending eligibility
to women who have been victims of rape or incest and reported the
incidents quickly to authorities.
   The Senate language that the House agreed to Wednesday included
an unrelated provision restricting federal financing for programs
that provide hypodermic needles to intravenous drug users. This
provision received little mention in the House debate but could
have influenced some votes.
   In all, 27 members voted for liberalized rules Wednesday who
were recorded as voting against them in September 1988, while two
voted against the eased limitations Wednesday who voted for them 13
months ago.
   The two voting for easing the limitations last year but switched
to opposing them on Wednesday were Reps. Marvin Leath, D-Texas, and
George Gekas, R-Pa.
   Those who opposed easing the limitations last year but voted in
favor of them Wednesday were Reps. Glenn Anderson, D-Calif.;
Douglas Bosco, D-Calif.; Matthew Martinez, D-Calif.; Alfred
McCandless, R-Calif.; John Rowland, R-Conn.; Bill Nelson, D-Fla.;
Richard Durbin, D-Ill.; Peter Visclosky, D-Ind.; Carroll Hubbard
Jr., D-Ky.; Richard Baker, R-La.; Helen Delich Bentley, R-Md.
   Also, Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn.; James Bilbray, D-Nev.; Bill
Richardson, D-N.M.; Floyd Flake, D-N.Y.; George Hochbrueckner,
D-N.Y.; Cass Ballenger, R-N.C.; Bill Hefner, D-N.C.; Byron Dorgan,
D-N.D.; Douglas Applegate, D-Ohio: Wes Watkins, D-Okla.; Arthur
Ravenel Jr., R-S.C.; Tim Johnson, D-S.D.; Jim Chapman, D-Texas:
Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas: Lewis Payne, D-Va.; Gerald Kleczka, D-Wis.
