<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0459 10-12 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Abortion Vote: Vote-Switchers Say the Public is Watching</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 3, He was, changing number from 28 to 27. A congresswoman
was recorded incorrectly in the Congressional Record a year ago.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters are focusing more on the abortion issue
this year, and some House members say that is leading them to
rethink the political wisdom of their past opinions.
   ``This year we're all listening,'' said Rep. Arthur Ravenel Jr.,
R-S.C., as the House voted 216-206 on Wednesday to liberalize
Medicaid abortion funding rules.
   He was one of 27 lawmakers who voted to allow more
Medicaid-funded abortions on Wednesday but had voted the opposite
last year. Ravenel attributed the change to increasing public
awareness following the Supreme Court's July decision giving the
states more power to restrict abortions.
   ``There's been no time that the public awareness of this matter
has been as high as it is now since I've been in public office,''
added Rep. Richard Baker, R-La., another lawmaker who switched his
vote over the last year.
   ``They're perceiving their constituencies as pro-choice;
obviously a majority of them are,'' Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., leader
of the House's anti-abortion forces, said of his colleagues after
the vote. ``Over the years, pro-lifers have been replaced by
pro-choicers.''
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who led the House fight for the
eased rules, was another who credited the climate created in the
aftermath of the high court's July 3 ruling in the Missouri case,
Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services case.
   ``The Supreme Court case made the issue real,'' she said.
``Before it was hypothetical because they always had the courts to
rely on.''
   In rejecting restrictions in place since 1981, the House agreed
to allow federal aid for abortions for poor women who are victims
of rape or incest. Conservatives lost an effort to reverse the
vote, 212-207.
   Wednesday's votes reversed the chamber's 216-166 vote of Sept.
9, 1988, by which it decided to limit federal aid to cases where
the woman's life was in danger.
   The bill now moves to the Senate, which has already passed the
eased limitations. However, President Bush has threatened to veto
the measure.
   There has been one other significant congressional victory for
abortion rights forces since the Webster decision: the House's vote
Aug. 2 to expand eligibility for government abortion aid in
Washington D.C.
   But that vote was considered easier for lawmakers because it
affected only abortions in the capital, and not their constituents
back home. Wednesday's vote has sparked strong statements from both
sides.
   ``The politicians who flip-flop on the abortion issue may find
themselves in a political no-man's land, perceived as lacking
principle and trusted by neither side,'' warned Darla St. Martin,
associate executive director of the National Right to Life.
   Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., who backs abortion rights, said he
believed Bush would veto the bill but predicted it would backfire.
   ``I would tell him by doing it, you're going to bring injury
upon yourself politically, but more important he's going to bring
injury upon his allies in the House,'' he said. ``He wins in the
short term _ the veto will stand obviously. But in the long term,
politically he's going to lose.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Olympics     10-12 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Olympics,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defector Claims North Korea Planned To Bomb Seoul Olympics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean defector claimed today
that his country planned a series of bombing attacks at the 1988
Summer Olympics in Seoul but that the plan was canceled because of
fear of retaliation.
   Suh Yong-chul, 26, who defected from North Korea last month,
told a news conference that six members of his North Korean
commando unit were trained to bomb Olympic facilities in Seoul,
including the 10,000-capacity main stadium.
   He said the plan was scrapped at the last moment because North
Korean leaders feared it could invite a retaliatory attack on a
world youth festival scheduled in July.
   Both the Summer Olympics in Seoul and the 13th World Youth
Festival in Pyongyang, North Korea, were held without disruption.
   ``Six members of our unit received special training to
infiltrate during the Olympics, but the plan was canceled. I later
knew that it was because the North feared that the South Korean
side would retaliate against the youth festival,'' Suh said.
   He also said a 1983 explosion in the southeastern city of Taegu
that killed four people was caused by a bomb planted by a North
Korean agent, who was not captured.
   The North Korean agent, Lee Chul, was awarded a top government
medal for the Taegu mission, he said.
   Four South Korean civilians were killed and two others wounded
in an explosion in front of the U.S. cultural center in Taegu in
September, 1983. No suspects were arrested but police announced at
that time that the explosion was believed to be the work of North
Korean agents.
   Suh defected to South Korea on Sept. 17 after swimming across a
river that flows along the Demilitarized Zone separating the two
Koreas.
   He said there are six units in North Korea trained in commando
attacks on South Korea. He claimed their main mission is to
assassinate South Korean leaders and sabotage government offices,
airports and industrial facilities.
   Suh said each unit has about 200 members and is under direct
control of North Korea's ruling Workers' Party. Suh's said his unit
was based in North Korea's border city of Kaesung.
   During the news conference, Suh demonstrated his commando
skills, throwing a dagger at a target seven yards away and rolling
over the floor while aiming a submachine gun.
</TEXT>
