<FIRST>r a PM-Hunt-Subpoena     10-12 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hunt-Subpoena,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Quashes Subpoena For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL POOVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge threw out a subpoena
ordering Gov. Guy Hunt to testify at a hearing for a lawmaker
accused of influence peddling.
   Rep. Lewis Spratt and two other black Democrats are charged with
extortion stemming from efforts by a former legislator to open a
dog track.
   Spratt had subpoenaed the Republican governor, U.S. Attorney Jim
Wilson, and Wilson's predecessor, John Bell, to testify Oct. 20.
Spratt's attorney said he would show that black Democrats were
singled out by white GOP prosecutors.
   But on Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Truman Hobbs granted a
motion by Hunt's attorneys to quash the subpoena. The hearing was
scheduled to consider Spratt's request for dismissal of the charges
based on racial discrimination.
   Hunt press secretary Terry Abbott said the governor is ``just
not involved'' in the case against Spratt.
   Spratt and Reps. Bobbie McDowell and E.B. McClain were indicted
in connection with effort by former state Rep. Hugh Boles to open a
pari-mutuel dog track at Bessemer. Spratt is accused of agreeing to
support Boles' measure in the Legislature in return for a promise
of stock options in the track.
   Boles was convicted in August of conspiracy and extortion.
   Spratt's lawyer, Carlos Williams, had claimed that prosecutors
ignored evidence of exortion and perjury by Hunt during his tenure
as state director of the U.S. Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service.
   Hunt denied any wrongdoing while he held the federal job. He
resigned the post in 1985 amid allegations he tried to use his
office for political purposes and tried to impede the
investigation. The investigation was later dropped.
