<FIRST>r w PM-House-EasternEurope 1stLd-Writethru a048plekilledthemselveslastyear_toEastEuropeanDemocraticMoves
10-12 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House-Eastern Europe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Urges More Aid to East European Democratic Moves</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS figure to $1.2 billion sted million in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee is
pressing an $837.5 million aid plan for Poland and Hungary, nearly
double the assistance proposed by President Bush, to encourage
those nations as they move toward democracy and free-market change.
   The committee endorsed the package 35-0 on Wednesday, choosing a
middle road between Bush's $455.5 million proposal and the $1.2
billion urged by Senate Democrats.
   The full House is expected to act on the three-year aid
authorization measure next week.
   ``Success with our help is uncertain, but failure without our
assistance is guaranteed,'' said Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., moments
before the bill was approved.
   Some Republican members said they were concerned the House bill
proposes too much spending and Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich.,
said a smaller amount is likely to emerge from the congressional
appropriations process.
   But most members said the legislation is an appropriate and
urgently needed response to democratic and free-market movements in
both Poland and Hungary.
   The House bill includes the $200 million to help Poland
stabilize its currency which Bush proposed last week, a move many
Democrats said was caused by congressional pressure to do more.
   The Bush administration took no position on the overall measure,
which builds on and expands U.S. assistance originally proposed by
the president.
   The legislation would authorize spending $837.5 million to aid
Poland and Hungary over the next three years, including $284
million in the 1990 fiscal year which began on Oct. 1.
   The largest share of the money is earmarked for Poland's new
non-communist government, which is beset with galloping inflation
and other serious economic problems.
   The House bill would authorize $200 million to operate
``enterprise funds'' to speed economic change in the two countries.
Bush has proposed spending $125 million for that purpose.
   The bill would boost the $100 million proposed by Bush for food
and livestock feed to a minimum of $125 million.
   Hamilton said the bill addresses an ``extraordinarily unique''
opportunity to wean Eastern Europe away from communism.
   ``This is an opportunity that may not come again for a long,
long time and I think we should grab it and run,'' said Rep. Robert
J. Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   Committee Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., said the aid will
``lessen the impact of the instability which must take place when
you think of the enormity of the changes'' Poland and Hungary will
have to make to transform their state-run economies.
   ``I can only say that after four decades in which we spent
literally trillions of dollars to prevent the communization of
Western Europe, this is a relatively modest amount to spend to
promote the unravelling of communism in Eastern Europe,'' said Rep.
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.
</TEXT>
