<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0466,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medellin Cartel Leader Reportedly Proposes Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with dynamite found, trafficker arrested; reorganizes
throughout; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced the arrests of
two suspected drug traffickers today and said it found 1,000 pounds
of dynamite hidden at a residence of one of Colombia's most
powerful cocaine kingpins.
   An Administrative Security Department spokeswoman said police
have arrested reputed trafficker Leonidas Vargas. She said she had
no information on the allegations against him or whether he is
wanted in the United States.
   But the newspaper El Espectador said Vargas ranks high in the
Medellin cocaine cartel and runs drug operations in the southern
state of Caqueta, where in recent years police have raided several
cocaine laboratories and seized tons of the drug.
   The paper said he was captured Wednesday at a ranch in the
central state of Tolima.
   The Administrative Security Department spokeswoman, speaking on
condition of anonymity, also said police arrested Richard Houle of
Quebec and would deport him Friday to Canada.
   Houle was a fugitive since his conviction on charges related to
cocaine trafficking in Canada, the spokeswoman said. It was not
known when he was captured or how long he had been at large.
   On Wednesday, the government announced two arrests of
traffickers who were known to be wanted in the United States.
Manuel Palma was arrested Wednesday and Jose Abello Silva was
captured Tuesday in Bogota.
   Abello directed the Medellin cartel's operations on the
country's Atlantic coast, the Administrative Security Department
said. The office said in a communique that he had undergone facial
surgery to avoid being recognized.
   In Washington, Justice Department spokesman Harri J. Kramer said
a federal grand jury in Tulsa, Okla., indicted Abello in 1987 on
charges of conspiring to import and distribute cocaine.
   Palma is wanted by federal authorities in Miami on charges of
interstate travel in aid of racketeering in connection with an
operation to launder drug money, Kramer said.
   Kramer said the Justice Department had requested that Abello and
Palma be held for extradition.
   The army said today that it seized 1,000 pounds of dynamite at
the home of Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez-Gacha, a powerful Medellin
cocaine czar on the list of 12 Colombian drug barons most wanted by
the United States.
   The dynamite found Wednesday was in an underground storage area
that had a concealed door in the ground, the army's 13th Brigade
said in a communique. Six two-way portable radios, nine firearms
and hundreds of pamphlets with threats against the government also
were found, the army said.
   Since the drug traffickers and the governmment declared war on
each other, 161 dynamite bombs have exploded in Colombia's major
cities, killing 11 people and injuring 183.
   On Wednesday, El Espectador asked the government for protection
following the assassination of two employees in Medellin.
Traffickers claimed responsibility for Tuesday's killings and
threatened to kill the paper's 11 remaining employees in Medellin.
   El Espectador has been a strong supporter of the government's
anti-drug campaign. Its main offices were bombed last month and
several of its employees have been killed, including the publisher.
   Also Wednesday, Pablo Escobar, the reputed head of the Medellin
cartel, was quoted as saying in a letter that ``Colombian peace is
more important than the considerations and conceptions of the other
governments of the world.''
   The letter asked the director of La Prensa, a Bogota daily, to
intercede with the government and end its crackdown on drug gangs.
The letter was read by the Caracol radio network.
   The letter said La Prensa and other papers should act ``for the
sake of peace'' as go-betweens in negotiations between traffickers
and the government of President Virgilio Barco.
   Barco has said he will never negotiate with the traffickers
responsible for killing scores of the country's judges,
journalists, political leaders and police.
   Escobar heads the list of the 12 Colombian drug suspects most
wanted for extradition to the United States. None has been
apprehended.
   The main weapon in the government crackdown has been a promise
to extradite those wanted on drug charges in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
