<FIRST>r w PM-RequestDenied 1stLd-Writethru a0576 10-12 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Request Denied, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0576,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Department Employee Dies Without Getting Flight Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 3, Dr. Abdallah, with time of death.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terminally ill Defense Department employee
whose request for an Air Force air ambulance ride home to
Massachusetts was denied has died, his doctor said today.
   Avram Brody had sought an airlift from Palmdale, Calif., to his
family home in Norwood, Mass., so he could be with family members
when he died. The Air Force refused, saying Brody did not meet
criteria for such help because he was not a uniformed officer, the
flight was not needed to save his life and his illness was not
caused by his work.
   Dr. Abdallah Farrukh, who attended Brody over the past several
weeks, said in a telephone interview from Antelope Valley, Calif.,
that Brody, 25, died Wednesday night of a brain tumor in his
Palmdale home.
   There was no anwer this morning at Brody's home where his wife,
Amy, and a nurse have been attending him for the past several weeks.
   The Brody family enlisted the help of several U.S.
representatives along with Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., and White
House aide Andrew Card, a Massachusetts native. But the Air Force
position remained unchanged.
   Another who worked on the case was Brad Pearson of the
Massachusetts Office of Handicapped Affairs.
   ``This one's a real sadness for the family. It's a heartbreaking
time,'' Pearson said today. ``I'm going to wonder probably for the
rest of my life if we didn't do too little, too late on this one. I
wish we could have gotten them home.''
   Pearson said of the Air Force position, ``I think that their
regulations ignored a very sad and simple reality.''
   Following publicity about the Air Force refusal to provide an
air ambulance, several private companies and individuals offered to
provide a ride for free. But by then Brody's condition had
deteriorated to the point where he could no longer be moved.
</TEXT>
