<HEAD>Man Takes Family Hostage; Two Found Dead in Burned Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENWOOD SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed man burst into a home
where his estranged wife and stepson were staying, tied them up and
set the house on fire, killing two women, authorities said.
   The stepson and the boy's grandfather escaped before the house
went up in flames, officials said.
   Police today searched for Gary Raymond Newman, 40, who had two
previous arrests for domestic violence and was released from jail
last week.
   The victims' identities were withheld.
   Newman, armed with a shotgun, entered the house about 9 p.m.
Wednesday. His estranged wife and stepson were staying with his
wife's parents there, said sheriff's Sgt. Beth Bascom.
   ``He took his stepson, his estranged wife and his estranged
wife's parents hostage, tied them up in the residence and separated
them,'' said Bascom.
   The boy escaped and ran to a neighbor's home to call police,
Bascom said. The grandfather, 76, also got away after having his
throat slashed, she said. His condition was not immediately known.
   When deputies reached the home, it was engulfed in flames,
Bascom said. Later, authorities recovered the bodies of two women
from the home, she said.
   Glenwood Springs is about 120 miles west of Denver.
