<FIRST>r i PM-Noriega-SteroidLab     10-12 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega-Steroid Lab,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Allegedly Made Millions From Steroid Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega made
millions of dollars from his investment in a lab that made steroids
for the black market, authorities said.
   Milano Laboratories of Mexico, in Tijuana's border industrial
zone, was shut down by police in April. At the time, U.S.
authorities said it was the largest supplier of steroids to a
multimillion-dollar U.S. black market.
   Noriega invested $800,000 two years ago in the lab, and his
return of about $2 million was put back into the company several
times, said Enrique Guillermo Salazar, commander of the federal
judicial police in Tijuana.
   ``We are still working to see exactly how much money was
involved, but it was many millions of dollars,'' Salazar said
Wednesday.
   Salazar said the lab was shut down because of false labeling. He
said agents found a warehouse full of steroids, antibiotics and
vitamins along with boxes of labels claiming the drugs were made by
pharmaceutical companies in the United States, Europe and Hong Kong.
   Agents also found business documents signed by Noriega, said
Salazar.
   Milano Laboratories president Juan Macklis Mercado was arrested
in Mexico City's airport Monday when he arrived in disguise from
Japan, authorities said. He was charged with evading taxes of about
$500,000.
   Many other suspects are thought to be living in the United
States, probably in San Diego, authorities said.
   Manufacturing anabolic steroids is legal in Mexico, where the
muscle-building drug is sold over the counter, but they are legally
obtainable in the United States by prescription only.
   Studies have shown that long-term use can cause heart disease,
liver failure and other maladies.
</TEXT>
