<HEAD>Farm Finds 300 Dead Squab, No Arrests Made</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUMTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vandal broke into a pigeon farm and
strangled and clubbed 300 baby birds valued at about $8,000.
   The squabs were apparently killed on Monday and discovered
Tuesday morning at the Palmetto Pigeon Plant, said general manager
Tony Barwick. The farm has raised squab since the 1920s and ships
the delicacy around the world.
   Workers had to find new parents for orphaned fledglings and move
the eggs of the dead birds into incubators, Barwick said.
   Barwick said he was particularly upset because the company was
trying to recover from damage caused by Hurricane Hugo. A security
fence was knocked down and the plant was without water for at least
a day after the storm.
   The intruder may have gotten in through the broken fence, the
Sheriff's Department said.
   No arrests have been made.

