<HEAD>Speelman Postpones Seventh Game Until Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jon Speelman of Britain has taken a time out and
postponed his seventh game of his World Chess Championship
Candidates' semifinal with Jan Timman of the Netherlands until
Saturday.
   After six rounds of the eight-game series Timman leads 3{-2{. A
win scores one point and a draw a half.
   Speelman is expected to use the free days to sharpen his opening
preparation and go all out for the victory he needs in the last two
games.
   With their time outs all taken, the fifth game between former
world champion Anatoly Karpov and fellow Soviet Artur Yusupov will
be played Thursday.
   Karpov leads 2{-1{ after four games.
   The winner of the candidates' cycle will challenge world
champion Garri Kasparov of the Soviet for his title in a 24-game
match starting in October 1990. The winning semifinalists will face
off in the candidates' final in March.
   If either contest ends in a 4-4 tie, two more games will be
played, followed, if necessary, by sudden death tie-breakers.
