<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OperaStrike     10-12 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Opera Strike,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Opera Cancels Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Opera, New York's No. 2 company behind
the Metropolitan, canceled its fall season today and threatened to
scratch its spring program unless its striking musicians agree to a
contract by next month.
   The 69-member musicians union has been without a contract since
June 1 and struck on Sept. 13, opening night of the fall season. On
Saturday, the union voted 56-4 to reject a pact, and the opera said
at the time that the season, scheduled to end Nov. 19, would be
canceled if the orchestra members did not return.
   ``Obviously, we are extremely saddened by this development
because it puts out of work hundreds of innocent people who rely on
these jobs for their livelihood and whose representatives have
urgently requested these parties to avoid this result,'' Martin
Oppenheimer, the company's vice chairman and lead negotiator, said
today.
   John Glasel, president of the union local, said that the
cancellation is regrettable and that the opera management's
deadline for reaching a contract ``exemplifies the Neanderthal
negotiating style of the company.''
   The opera and its musicians have been divided over wages and the
number of work weeks that orchestra members are guaranteed
annually. Musicians earned $755 a week under the old contract.
   Established in 1943, the non-profit City Opera stages a Broadway
musical revival in the spring and begins its summer opera season in
July.
</TEXT>
