<FIRST>u a PM-FloridaAbortion 3rdLd-Writethru a0539 10-12 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Abortion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0539,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Activists: Florida Action Marks Nationwide Political Shift</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th, `More than ...' to UPDATE with
Martinez quotes today. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `The proposals ...'; DELETES
grafs 13-14 pvs, `The governor ...' to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature's flat-out rejection of
new abortion curbs may give women their best political springboard
since the '60s, feminists say. But anti-abortion activists say
they, too, will be galvanized.
   ``It has fanned the fire,'' said Florida Right to Life President
Ken Connor. ``It's one thing to disappoint people. It's another
thing to slap them in the face. That's what the Legislature has
done.''
   In the nation's first major attempt to take advantage of a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling in July allowing new curbs on abortion, the
Legislature adjourned Wednesday without passing any of the measures
pushed by Gov. Bob Martinez.
   ``Florida has just sent a message to the nation,'' said Eleanor
Smeal, president of the Fund for a Feminist Majority and a former
president of the National Organization for Women.
   More than 10,000 demonstrators descended upon Florida's capital
as the Democratic-controlled Legislature shot down 14 proposals to
curb abortion.
   Martinez, appearing on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
insisted today that most Floridians wanted certain restrictions on
abortions but that a handful of legislators kept colleagues from
voting on measures he had proposed.
   ``They were rejected by killer committees. They didn't get to
the floor, unlike the action taken by Congress,'' he said.
   The proposals would have banned use of public funds for
abortions, required a husband's consent, made women wait a week and
undergo counseling before the operation, created a statewide center
to promote adoption and required viability tests of the fetus if a
woman was believed to be 20 weeks pregnant.
   Other measures killed would have toughened clinic regulations,
an idea lawmakers had given the best chance of approval after three
south Florida clinics were closed by the state for unsanitary and
unsafe conditions.
   The defeat had been predicted by Democratic leaders who said the
first-term Republican governor knew it would happen.
   ``He wasted taxpayers' money to make a political statement that
he felt was going to help him,'' said Democratic state Chairman
Simon Ferro. ``We ought to be embarrassed that the governor put us
through this whole fiasco.''
   Opponents said the special session, which began Tuesday, cost
more than $145,000.
   Martinez, who faces re-election in 1990, conceded his initiative
had faltered badly.
   ``I don't think it's a moment for rejoicing,'' said Martinez.
``If anything, it's a moment of sadness.''
   But Arthur J. Kropp, president of People for the American Way
Action Fund, a liberal political group, said the Legislature's
actions would make politicians across the country pay attention to
their constituents.
   ``Today's victory will be a rude wake-up call for politicians
hoping to score points at the polls by rolling back reproductive
freedom,'' Kropp said. ``Legislators in other states should take
heed: Pro-choice politics is winning politics, even in conservative
states.''
   Patricia Ireland, vice president of NOW, said the whole exercise
had the possibly unintended result of energizing younger,
previously apathetic women to fight for their rights.
   ``This is creating a new wave of feminism that we have not had
since the 1960s,'' Ireland said. ``This is one of those junctures
where the political climate has clearly changed.''
   Smeal said abortion rights' organizations hoped to turn the new
interest into political gains by recruiting more women to run for
national, state and local office.
   State Rep. Elaine Gordon, a leader of the abortion-rights forces
in the Legislature, said the Florida experience can serve as a
blueprint elsewhere.
   ``I think that it encourages pro-choice movements in other
states,'' she said. ``We will be able to provide them the incentive
and the encouragement.''
   Anti-abortion activist Carole Griffin had similar thoughts.
``Our people are angry at what we've seen,'' she said. ``We are
preparing for the 1990 elections, and now we know more of our
targets.''
   For his part, Florida Right to Life's Connor said: ``What's next
is we go back to work. We field new candidates who affirm the
sanctity and dignity of human life. We explore the potential for a
constitutional amendment.''
</TEXT>
