<FIRST>r a PM-NorthwestCrashTrial     10-12 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest Crash Trial,0211</SECOND>
<UNK>Judge Limits Airline's Ability to Collect From Plane Manufacturer</UNK>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest must show that McDonnell Douglas Corp.
knowingly sold it a defective plane if the airline is to collect
damages from the manufacturer in a jet crash that killed 156
people, a federal judge ruled.
   The ruling Wednesday by U.S. District Judge Julian Cook limits
the airline's ability to collect from the maker of the MD-80 that
crashed in 1987 on takeoff from Detroit Metropolitan Airport. Only
Cecelia Cichan, then 4, survived.
   Cook is presiding over the trial on a lawsuit by relatives of
crash victims that will determine who was at fault in the crash.
Jury selection began Oct. 2 and continued today.
   Northwest has claimed the plane had a faulty circuit breaker and
warning system that failed to warn the crew that the flaps had not
been set for takeoff. McDonnell Douglas has denied any problem with
the plane.
   The judge sided with the company's argument that the purchase
agreement for the $15 million aircraft absolved the maker of
liability unless Northwest could prove the knowing sale of a
defective product.
   Attorneys involved wouldn't comment. Cook has issued a gag order
for the duration of the trial.
</TEXT>
