<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-12 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COCONUT CREEK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 24 million tiny tourists have
taken up temporary residence in this bedroom community outside Fort
Lauderdale and they're driving the locals nuts.
   Some unknown beekeeper dropped off more than 600 hives brimming
with bees in the middle of the fast-growing town.
   ``This is driving us crazy,'' said Donna Kaszanek, owner of the
Jumping Springs riding ranch. ``There are bee droppings everywhere,
and they're buzzing all over the place.''
   Beekeepers like to bring their hives to Broward County when the
Florida holly is in bloom, then pick them up a few weeks later when
they are loaded with honey.
   ``This whole thing is incredible,'' said Al Tholl, a Margate bee
exterminator who was called in to count the hives and survey the
scene.
   ``I've had calls all day,'' said John Bastianelli, a state
agricultural inspector who handles bee complaints.
   The city is putting out the word to whoever owns the bees that
they've worn out their welcome and had better be gone by the
weekend.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How many quarters does it take to wash a
pair of llamas at a car wash? (Never mind why anyone would want to.)
   Randy Cipriano of Garland said it took about $12 worth to wash
the animals with dish soap and rinse them with fabric softener at a
car wash Tuesday.
   Cipriano, who raises the South American natives as a sideline to
his marketing firm, stopped at the car wash to prepare two of the
five llamas he plans to take to the fifth annual Llama Harvest Show
and Sale, which begins Friday at Omaha.
   He got into the business a few years ago after a hunting trip
with a friend who suggested he should raise llamas, popular as pets
and also as pack animals for long camping trips.
   ``I thought he was crazy,'' said Cipriano, who now has 13 of
them.
   So how do llamas like being bathed in a car wash?
   ``They tolerate it,'' Cipriano said. ``They have a great
disposition.''
</TEXT>
