<FIRST>r w AM-RequestDenied 310   10-12 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Request Denied, 310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Department Employee Dies Without Getting Flight Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terminally ill Defense Department employee
whose request to be flown to his Massachusetts home on an Air Force
plane was turned down has died, his doctor said Thursday.
   The Air Force said last month that Avram Brody did not meet the
criteria needed for such a government-paid flight, which it
estimated would cost $30,000.
   The 25-year-old man died of a brain tumor Wednesday night at his
home in Palmdale, Calif., Dr. Abdallah Farrukh said in a telephone
interview.
   ``This one's a real sadness for the family. It's a heartbreaking
time,'' said Brad Pearson of the Massachusetts Office For
Handicapped Affairs, who lobbied for the Brody family.
   ``I'm going to wonder probably for the rest of my life if we
didn't do too little too late on this one. I wish we could have
gotten them home.''
   Pearson said the Air Force regulations ``ignored a very sad and
simple reality.''
   The Air Force had said it would allow such a flight for
uniformed personnel, for someone whose illness had been caused by
his work or if the flight would save a life. Brody, the Air Force
said, did not meet any of those criteria.
   Also intervening in Brody's behalf were Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., several members of the House of Representatives and White
House aide Andrew Card, a Massachusetts native.
   After publicity about the Air Force refusal to provide an air
ambulance, several private companies and individuals offered to
provide a free flight. However, Brody's condition had deteriorated
to the point where he could no longer be moved.
   Brody, whose tumor was diagnosed a year ago, had been cared for
at home by his wife, Amy, and a nurse. There was no answer at the
Brody home Thursday.
</TEXT>
