<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0535,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Reaches Preliminary Accord; Aoun Rejects It</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with Christian leader rejecting peace
plan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese lawmakers reached preliminary
agreement today on a peace plan for their country, but Christian
leader Gen. Michel Aoun rejected the plan and vowed to continue his
war with Syrian troops.
   Radio stations said the plan calls for at least a partial
withdrawal of Syrian troops from Lebanon and a limit on the powers
of the Christian president.
   Conference sources said a Parliamentary committee led by house
speaker Hussein Husseini agreed on the phrasing of the plan after a
round-the-clock debate attended by the foreign ministers of Saudi
Arabia, Morocco and Algeria.
   The committee broke up in the morning and was scheduled to meet
again later to present its draft agreement to the 63 legislators
meeting in Taif.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, would not
elaborate on the tentative accord. But Najah Wakim, an Orthodox
Christian, and Hassan Rifai, a Moslem, told reporters they were
``optimistic'' after the overnight session.
   But Aoun said later: ``We cannot rebuild our country under the
shadow of an occupying force.''
   ``Let those deputies understand that our Lebanon's sovereignty
and independence are not a matter for bargaining and negotiation,''
he said in a speech carried on Voice of Lebanon radio. He vowed to
pursue his ``war of liberation'' against Syria, which has 40,000
troops stationed in Lebanon.
   Lebanese radio stations earlier quoted deputies as saying
differences over presidential powers and the issue of Syria's
military presence in Lebanon had been resolved.
   The radio stations attributed the progress to the mediation of
the three foreign ministers supervising the talks _ Prince Saud
al-Faisal of Saudi Arabia, Morocco's Abdel-Latif al-Filali, and
Algeria's Ahmed Ghozaly.
   The three countries are grouped in an Arab League committee
entrusted with finding a settlement to Lebanon's 14-year-old civil
war.
   The Voice of People, a pro-Syrian station in Beirut, and the
Voice of Lebanon, said the committee today approved a timetable for
a ``limited and phased'' Syrian withdrawal from Lebanon. They gave
no details.
   Voice of the People said that although the president will
continue to be a Maronite Catholic, his powers will be curtailed.
   He will no longer have the power to issue general amnesties or
dissolve Parliament at will. A head of state will be able to
dissolve the 99-seat Parliament only once during his six-year term,
it said.
   He also will no longer be the commander in chief of the armed
forces. Instead, the military command will report directly to the
Cabinet, traditionally headed by a Sunni Moslem.
   Once a new head of state is elected, a committee grouping the
president, prime minister and Parliament speaker, usually a Shiite
Moslem, will be formed to work on abolishing the sectarian system
of government, the radio said.
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since former President
Amin Gemayel's term ended Sept. 22, 1988.
   Under the sectarian system in force since independence from
France in 1943, Christians, mainly the Maronites, have dominated
Lebanon's Parliament, government, army and judiciary.
   Christians were once considered the majority in Lebanon. Now,
Moslems make up 55 percent of the 4 million people.
   The meeting in Taif began Sept. 30.
   The Arab committee had first proposed that Syria complete a
phased withdrawal from the Beirut area within two years.
   It offered no timetable or guarantees for a complete withdrawal
of the Syrian contingent, in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
mandate. It linked it to an Israeli pullout from south Lebanon and
the conclusion of a Lebanese-Syrian security pact.
   The Christians, who fought the Syrians this year for six months
until an Arab League cease-fire halted the bloodshed Sept. 22,
rejected the proposal.
   They conceded a quick pullout would leave a security vacuum and
allow unruly militias to take over but insisted two years was too
long for a withdrawal from Beirut. They demanded a timetable for
withdrawal from northern and eastern Lebanon.
   Moslems rejected any pullout of their Syrian protectors until
political reforms curtailing the domination of Christians in
Lebanon have been enforced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Palme 4thLd-Writethru   10-12 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0575,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Conviction in Slaying of Olof Palme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Pettersson freed. Pickup 5th
pvs, `The decision...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court today threw out the
conviction of a career criminal accused of fatally shooting Prime
Minister Olof Palme three years ago. Hours later, the defendant was
freed from prison.
   Judge Birgitta Blom of the Svea Court of Appeals said the court
ruled there was not enough evidence to show that Christer
Pettersson stalked and killed Palme as the Swedish leader left a
movie theater with his wife Feb. 28, 1986.
   Pettersson was sentenced to life in prison and had been jailed
in isolation since December.
   ``I'm surprised. I never really believed I would be acquitted,
although I am innocent,'' Pettersson, 42, told the national TT news
agency after leaving the Kronoberg Prison with his lawyer and a
police escort.
   Ms. Blom, the president of the appellate court, told Swedish
radio the decision to overturn the conviction was unanimous.
   The decision is the culmination of a sensational case that
authorities have been accused of bungling since its inception.
Police for a year pursued a series of vastly different conspiracy
theories before prosecuting Pettersson, a drug and alcohol abuser
with a long and varied criminal record.
   Pettersson was convicted in July even though no motive was
established, no weapon was found and no witnesses testified to
seeing the Swede fire five shots at the dynamic leader on a
darkened street.
   The appellate court judgment may be referred to the Swedish
Supreme Court. But because the high court usually agrees only to
hear cases that could form legal precedent, legal experts have said
it probably would not hear Pettersson's case.
   In addition, experts had said if the conviction were overturned
it would be virtually impossible to find Palme's killer, since all
the witnesses police could find pointed to Pettersson as the man
they saw at the crime scene.
   Pettersson's three-week appeal hearing was presided over by a
jury of three laymen and four professional jurors. The hearing
ended Monday.
   The court had set Nov. 2 for announcing its verdict, but the
national news agency TT said the jury concluded in only three days
that ``the investigation into the case was insufficient for a
conviction.''
   The written verdict will be released Nov. 2.
   Palme was a four-term prime minister and a dominant figure in
the international socialist and disarmament movements. He also was
a U.N. mediator in the Iran-Iraq war.
   The conviction by a tribunal of six laymen and two professional
judges was based largely on the identification of Pettersson by
Palme's widow, Lisbeth Palme, who was walking home with her husband
when he was shot from behind at close range.
   Mrs. Palme said she saw Pettersson standing a few feet away
after her husband was shot. She was grazed by a bullet and slightly
wounded.
   Several other witnesses said they saw Pettersson apparently
waiting for the Palmes to emerge from the theater.
   But no one saw Pettersson with a gun, and police failed to
produce any forensic evidence to link him to the shooting.
   Pettersson denied shooting Palme and said he was not in central
Stockholm when the killing took place at 11.21 p.m.
   One witness testified to seeing Pettersson at a train station
far from the shooting scene at the time of the slaying.
   The two judges in the trial voted for acquittal, but the six
laymen voted to convict.
   The initial investigation into the slaying focused on a series
of conspiracy theories. Most centered on Kurdish militants, others
centered on Iranian or Iraqi government assassins and still another
focused on a secret cadre of right-wing police officers upset with
Palme's leftist politics. All were dismissed as essentially
groundless.
   Four hours before Palme was shot, the files of a tax
investigation against him disappeared in a break-in at the county
administrative appeals court. All computer files were obliterated
and all documents were stolen. No connection with the killing was
ever established.
   The botched probe resulted in a series of resignations and
firings. The befuddling case has developed an aura of mystery that
has been likened to the doubts that still haunt the assassination
of former President John F. Kennedy.
   Several top police officials and Justice Minister Anna-Greta
Leijon eventually were forced to resign because of their
involvement in an unauthorized, privately led investigation into
the case.
</TEXT>
