<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0606 10-12 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0606,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tries to Keep Mississippi Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs on drug summit after 4th graf, The president</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush took time out today from
affairs of state to boost a Republican candidate involved in a
tough battle to keep a Mississippi congressional seat held by the
GOP for 16 years.
   In his return to the campaign trail, Bush echoed themes that
served him well in the 1988 presidential election, citing
Republican Tom Anderson's devotion to ``traditional values.''
   The president also emphasized Anderson's long experience as a
congressional aide and his service as ambassador to Barbados, which
Bush said made him ``a point man in the drug interdiction effort.''
   Bush also noted that he has accepted the invitation of the
presidents of Colombia, Bolivia and Peru _ the source countries for
cocaine sold in the United States _ to attend a drug summit within
90 days.
   ``I've instructed my administration to prepare for a summit that
will bring us to a new level of international cooperation in this
war we must win,'' Bush told an audience of several thousand. ``As
long as I am president, I will give as much support as he needs to
President (Virgilio) Barco (of Colombia), who is waging an all-out
fight'' against drug lords.
   Later Bush was attending a reception and dinner for GOP mayoral
candidate Rudolph Giuliani in New York.
   He also was flying to the Newark, N.J., airport to meet briefly
with Rep. James Courter, the Republican gubernatorial nominee, and
then attend a New York reception for Rep. Guy Molinari, who is
running for borough president of Staten Island.
   Bush told an outdoor rally in Gulfport that as a longtime aide
to former congressman and now-Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., Anderson
``knows the back roads of the Fifth District ... just as he knows
the corridors of Capitol Hill.''
   Anderson, 43, is running against Democratic State Sen. Gene
Taylor for the seat left vacant by the death of Rep. Larkin Smith,
R-Miss., in an August plane crash. Taylor bested Anderson in the
Oct. 3 open primary and is the favorite in Tuesday's special
election.
   ``You know Tom, and all of you know what makes southern
Mississippi what it is. Mississippi values. Traditional values. Tom
Anderson's values,'' Bush told the hometown crowd.
   Bush also used the event to echo what aides said Tuesday: he
will attend a drug summit with leaders of the Andean nations of
Colombia, Bolivia and Peru.
   He praised the citizens of Gulfport, themselves hit by Hurricane
Camille 20 years ago, for their relief efforts in the wake of
Hurricane Hugo.
   The Mississippi race is seen as a tough one for Anderson, a
longtime aide to Trent Lott, the state's Republican senator who
served in the House before his 1988 election to the Senate.
   The runoff election between Anderson and Taylor is a high-stakes
contest for both Democrats and Republicans, who have held the seat
for 16 years. It is the latest in a handful of special elections
around the country this year that serve as opening skirmishes for
the 1990 national elections and the GOP's perpetual battle to wrest
control of Congress away from the Democrats.
   Anderson has spent heavily, reporting $447,700 in spending by
the end of September, not including large television advertising
buys just prior to the Oct. 3 primary election in the 5th
Congressional District.
   But Taylor, who spent $88,606 through Sept. 27, outpolled
Anderson and a third candidate in the primary election indicating
what Democrats say is a shift away from the Republican habit.
   Anderson has touted his longtime experience in the district as
Lott's aide, and Taylor is relying on his legislative experience.
   In New Jersey, White House advance aides said they were setting
up today's planned meeting with Courter at the airport. Recent
polls showed Courter lagging 14 to 23 points behind Rep. James
Florio, the Democratic candidate for governor.
   In New York, Bush appears tonight for Giuliani, whose bid to
beat Democrat David Dinkins, the Manhattan Borough president, in
the mayoral contest is lagging.
   Democrats outnumber Republicans 5-1 in the city and Dinkins is
widely considered a shoo-in although Giuliani began the race well
ahead of both incumbent Mayor Ed Koch and Dinkins in the polls.
   A series of missteps and revelations have led to his slide,
including disclosure that his law firm was on retainer for the
government of Panama and incidents that agitated the Jewish
community. Most recently, comedian Jackie Mason, a key supporter,
was accused of making ethnic slurs against Dinkins and stereotyping
Jews.
   Dinkins also ran into ethnic criticism, leading to his
announcement Wednesday in Washington that campaign aide Jitu Weusi
would leave in the wake of criticism by the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith.
   The B'nai B'rith said Weusi once referred to Jews as ``vile
money-changers'' and ``shylocks'' and also wrote ``scores of
anti-Semitic articles.''
   Dinkins toured Capitol Hill on Wednesday, receiving a warm
welcome from congressional leaders and meeting also with Bush's
Secretary of Housing and Urban development, Jack Kemp, on housing
issues.
   Giuliani met with Kemp earlier in the month.
   Asked if Bush's visit to New York would help Giuliani, Dinkins
said, ``I assume it will help him raise some money but I don't know
that it will do him much good beyond that. New York is not a
Republican town.''
   Bush's appearance for Molinari is intended to help Molinari's
bid for borough president against Democratic incumbent Ralph
Lamberti.
</TEXT>
