<FIRST>r a PM-GunneryAccident 2ndLd-Writethru a0610 10-12 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gunnery Accident, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0610,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Dead, One Hurt in Gunnery Accident Aboard USS Iwo Jima</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs to end, bgng `The injured ...' with four grafs
to UPDATE with details of accident.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shrapnel or projectiles fired from a Navy
cargo ship during an Atlantic gunnery exercise killed an officer
aboard the amphibious assault vessel USS Iwo Jima and injured a
second sailor, the Navy said today.
   In the Pacific, two crewmen fell off the San Diego-based frigate
Downes during exercises. One was rescued and the other was missing
today, officials said. The accident occurred about 300 miles off
Tokyo on Wednesday morning.
   The gunnery accident occurred Wednesday evening as the Iwo Jima
took part in an exercise with the amphibious cargo ship USS El Paso
about 80 miles southeast of Norfolk, said Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd,
Navy spokesman.
   Lloyd said the two sailors were struck by objects fired from the
El Paso.
   ``They were both on the bridge,'' Lloyd said. ``The projectiles
apparently struck the bridge and the flight deck.''
   The El Paso was firing at a target being towed by a plane, he
said. Lloyd said the Iwo Jima sustained no apparent damage.
   The injured man, a petty officer first class, was treated on
board and then flown to Portsmouth Naval Hospital, where he was
listed in stable condition today, Lloyd said.
   He said the Navy is investigating.
</TEXT>
