<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AstronautMemorial     10-12 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Astronaut Memorial,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronaut Memorial Dedicated At Space Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ground has been broken for a ``Space
Mirror'' monument to memorialize the 14 astronauts who have died
while pursuing the goals of the space program.
   A member of each of their families was on hand at a ceremony
Wednesday at Kennedy Space Center to place a star on the
cornerstone of the Astronaut Memorial, inspired by the explosion of
the space shuttle Challenger.
   ``To Those Who Gave Their Lives To Bring The Stars A Little
Closer,'' read a plaque unveiled on the cornerstone for the $5
million memorial, to be completed next year.
   ``We honor their courage, because so few of us are courageous.
We honor their knowledge, because so few of us can understand the
unknown. We honor their quest, because it is the way to the
future,'' said Alan C. Helman, founder of the Astronauts Memorial
Foundation.
   The ``Space Mirror'' will be 42{ feet high by 50 feet wide,
constructed of mirror-finished granite with the names of the 14 cut
through its surface like a stencil. The entire memorial will track
the sun throughout the day, enabling mirrors behind the cut-out
names to reflect sunlight back through the image of the sky
reflected on the polished granite.
   Listed will be Challenger crew members Dick Scobee, Michael J.
Smith, Ronald E. McNair, Ellison S. Onizuka, Judith A. Resnik,
Gregory B. Jarvis and Christa McAuliffe; Apollo 1 crew members Gus
Grissom, Edward H. White II and Roger B. Chaffee who died in a 1967
launch pad fire; and astronauts killed in T-38 training accidents:
Theodore C. Freeman, Charles A. Bassett, Elliot M. See Jr. and
Clifton C. Williams.
   Grissom's son, Gary Mark Grissom, said it was ``about time''
they got around to building a memorial.
   ``When I was younger, I thought NASA would do something. It's a
shame that it has taken this long,'' Grissom said. His father was
the second American in space.
   Grace Corrigan, mother of Mrs. McAuliffe, the teacher who died
on the Challenger, told a reporter she doesn't believe NASA's
teacher-in-space program and others involving civilians should
resume, ``not since what has happened.''
   ``We believed everything was going to be all right when Christa
went up,' she said. ``We never thought they would take any chances.
We learned the hard way. They are never going to do that again.
They can't.''
   Most of the funds were provided by the sale of Challenger
license plates in Florida.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
