<FIRST>r a PM-PrivateFlush     10-12 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Private Flush,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Flush With Success After Board Agrees to Put Doors on Stalls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The writing was on the wall, but not the
bathroom wall, and now Arthur Hill High School's open-stall policy
is history.
   The Saginaw Board of Education agreed last week to add doors to
the school's toilet stalls after pleas from two students.
   The doors were removed in 1974 because of vandalism, but
Superintendent Foster B. Gibbs said malicious damage is no longer a
problem.
   Student council president Randon D. Morford cited a 1987 case at
another school in which state Department of Civil Rights lawyers
threatened to go to court.
   ``We are prepared to do whatever it takes to get doors on those
stalls and to protect our rights of privacy,'' he said.
   Senior Martin Schreader said students have been known to fake
illness so they can leave the building and find a restroom with
doors on the stalls.
   The board agreed to have a plan in place within three weeks.
   ``If there is not a safety or security factor, I recommend that
the doors be put on in all haste,'' said Trustee Michael L. Kiefer.
``There is a matter of personal dignity and privacy.''
</TEXT>
