<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vodka     10-12 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vodka,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vodka &amp; a Splash: Norwegians Dive For Sunken Booze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERGEN, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck loaded with 6,000 bottles of
liquor fell off a ferry, and police had to post a 24-hour guard to
keep people from diving into the fjord for the liquid treasure,
reports said Thursday.
   ``Three eager local scuba divers were there first to help
themselves. They filled plastic bags with bottles but surfaced
right into the arms of police,'' Birger Monsen of the state liquor
monopoly Vinmonopolet A.S. told the Dagbladet daily.
   The cargo, mostly vodka, was worth more than $150,000, reports
said. Vodka costs at least $27 a bottle in Norway, where liquor is
heavily taxed.
   The truck started rolling when the ferry set sail, and it
plunged into 38 feet of water. No one was injured.
   Police remained on duty through the night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1412EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain     10-12 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chancellor Says British Interest Rates Stay High, However Unpopular</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's chancellor of the exchequer
said Thursday he will continue a policy of increasing interest
rates to curb inflation, and he brushed aside fears the economy is
heading into recession.
   Addressing the annual conference of Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative Party, Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson ignored pressure to link the pound to other major European
currencies through the European Monetary System.
   ``Inevitably people ask whether there is an alternative to high
interest rates at the present time,'' said Lawson. ``Bluntly, the
answer is that there is no alternative and the policy will work.''
   The four-day conference, which ends Friday, has been
overshadowed by Lawson's decision last week to raise interests
rates to an eight-year high of 15 percent, hitting businesses and
millions of home buyers.
   Lawson's tactic of using high interest rates to curb inflation
and to try to keep the pound steady against the West German mark,
has prompted renewed demands to put the British currency into the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
   The European Monetary System links the currencies of eight of
the 12 Common Market nations in order to prevent wide swings in
exchange rate movements.
   Lawson made no mention of the issue in his speech, but later, in
broadcast interviews, he repeated the Conservative government's
position that it would join the mechanism when it felt the time is
right. He wouldn't be drawn on what the timetable might be.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who was seated alongside Lawson as he addressed
the 9,000 delegates, has set stringent conditions for British entry
to the European currency-stabilizing system. They include a
lowering in Britain's 7.3 inflation rate and that other member
countries must _ like Britain _ allow totally free movement of
capital.
   The financial markets were soothed by Lawson's speech. The
markets were watching it closely because of a recent sharp drop in
the pound despite last week's interest rate hike.
   The pound rose to $1.5520 from $1.5425 late Wednesday, and
dipped slightly to 2.9597 West German marks from 2.9632 marks.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 19
points, or 0.9 percent, higher at 2,237.8.
   Lawson, who was loudly applauded, said he has ``no easy
answers.''
   ``But I give you this pledge. I will continue to take whatever
action is needed, however unpopular it may be, to keep our economy
sound and strong,'' he added.
   The Confederation of British Industry, Britain's main business
group, said Lawson's approach was ``exactly what the situation
demanded.''
   The opposition Labor Party jibed that Lawson merely ``rehashed
failed policies'' and the Trades Union Congress, the national labor
federation, accused him of complacency.
   General Secretary Norman Willis urged British membership in the
exchange rate mechanism.
   Foreign Secretary John Major said Britain should not be
defensive about its ``common sense'' approach to the 12-nation
European Economic Community.
   ``For it is we who have breathed new life into it (the
community),'' Major said. ``It is our show. The community is
carrying out our program.''
   In another development, Transport Secretary Cecil Parkinson said
Britain will build a $310 million air traffic control center. He
said the facility, to be completed in the 1990s, will enable
Britain to handle 50 percent more flights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
