<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1402EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-RacialFight     10-12 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Fight,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Hurt, Six Arrested in High School Brawl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADAMSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 45 law officers were assigned to
keep the peace at racially tense Minor High School today after a
melee in which the principal and a teen-ager were stabbed and six
students arrested.
   Students had to pass through a metal detector and go directly to
class, bypassing their usual gathering places, including the
lunchroom that white and black students turned into a battleground
Wednesday.
   During the brawl, a teacher fired shots into the air to restore
order, teen-agers sprayed Mace on schoolmates, and some teachers
and coaches fought students, authorities and witnesses said.
   ``There was mass confusion, running and screaming everywhere,''
said police Sgt. Ronald Benson, who was knocked down and sprayed
with Mace.
   Officers today arrested two teen-agers outside and confiscated
beer, a BB gun, crowbars and spiked gloves and wristbands.
Sheriff's Lt. Earl Patterson said the two did not appear to be
students at Minor.
   Principal Judson Jones, who suffered a two-inch knife cut to his
abdomen, said a biracial committee of parents will look for
solutions to the problems.
   ``We want to address them and get back to the real job of being
here. That's to educate the kids. We seem to have lost that,'' he
said.
   Some students and police said conflict among the school's 967
students stemmed partly from black gang activity and what blacks
viewed as taunting by whites. The school northwest of Birmingham is
about 25 percent black.
   William James, a 17-year-old black senior, said the fight broke
out when a white dressed like the black rock guitarist Jimmy
Hendrix ``with dirt on his hands to make them look black.''
   He said blacks were sent to the lunchroom and whites to the gym,
but as many as 50 whites entered the lunchroom ``in a straight line
with all these wepaons _ Mace and forks. It just went off. They
jumped all these black people who were eating.''
   ``There's always been racial trouble here,'' he said. ``They
didn't want us here anyway.''
   David Doren, a 16-year-old white, said when the whites went into
the lunchroom, blacks started hollering ``and started walking
around us. We stood up and everybody started fighting.''
   Doren said that when a white student walks down a hall alone,
``four or five blacks will jump on him. They will find a person
walking down the hall and run and jump on him.''
   ``It's going to keep on going,'' he said. ``We've got to get rid
of the gangs to stop it.''
   A black senior, 17-year-old Bellamy Johnson, said blacks had
objected to the suspension of blacks for cutting their names into
their hair.
   Johnny Drummonds, a 17-year-old white, was stabbed in the
shoulder. He received stitches at a hospital and returned to school.
   Six students were arrested, said Frank Rogers, chief sheriff's
deputy. He said five were to be charged with rioting and the sixth
was to be charged with assault with intent to murder.
   A teacher who fired shots into the air in an attempt to quell
the disturbance was sent home and faces disciplinary action, said
Nez Calhoun, spokeswoman for the school board. The teacher had
carried the gun because of earlier problems, an unidentified
witness told the Birmingham Post-Herald.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Nobel-Physics-List     10-12 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nobel-Physics-List,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of Recent Nobel Winners in Physics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobels Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the winners of the Nobel Prize in Physics since 1970
and their accomplishments.
   1970: Louis Neel, French, discovery in solid-state physics; and
Hannes Alfven, Swedish, theory underlying the relationship between
magnets and electrically conducting liquids.
   1971: Dennis Gabor, British, invention of holography.
   1972: John Bardeen, Leon Cooper, John R. Schrieffer, all
American, development of theory explaining superconductivity.
   1973: Ivar Giaever and Leo Esaki, Americans, and Brian David
Josephson, British, discovery of how electrons tunnel through
conductors to become superconductors.
   1974: Martin Ryle, English, techniques in using radiotelescopes;
and Antony Hewish, English, role in the discovery of pulsars.
   1975: L. James Rainwater, American, and Aage N. Bohr and Ben R.
Mottleson, Danish, discovery of motion inside nuclei and how this
affects the shape of the nuclei.
   1976: Samuel C.C. Ting and Burton Richter, Americans, discovery
of a new subatomic ``J'' particle.
   1977: John Hasbrouck Van Vleck and Philip W. Anderson,
Americans, and Sir Nevill Francis Mott, British, theories of
electronic circuitry and solid-state
   physics used in computer memories, lasers, transistors, solar
energy cells and office copying machines.
   1978: Pyotr Kapitsa, Soviet Union, and Arno Penzias and Robert
Wilson, Americans, discovered cosmic background radiation
theoretically left over from the ``Big Bang'' that began the
universe.
   1979: Steven Weinberg and Sheldon L. Glashow, Americans, and
Abdus Salam, Pakistani, theories involving weak and electromagnetic
interaction between elementary particles.
   1980: James W. Cronin and Val L. Fitch, Americans, symmetry of
subatomic particles, instrumental in development of the ``Big
Bang'' theory of the creation of the universe.
   1981: Nicolaas Boembergen and Arthur Schawlow, Americans,
development of laser spectroscopy; and Kai M. Siegbahn, Swedish,
contributions to development of high-resolution electron
spectroscopy.
   1982: Kenneth G. Wilson, American, method of analyzing basic
changes in matter due to pressure and temperature.
   1983: Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar and William A. Fowler,
Americans, explorations of what happens as stars age, consume their
nuclear fuel, form new elements and finally collapse and die.
   1984: Carlo Rubbia, Italy, and Simon van der Meer, Dutch,
development of particle detector and discovery of subatomic ``W''
and ``Z'' particles.
   1985: Klaus von Klitzing, West German, discoveries related to
the Hall effect, describing deflection of electrons in a current
affected by a magnetic field, with applications in computers.
   1986: Ernst Ruska, West Germany, fundamental work in electron
optics and design of the first electron microscope; and Gerd
Binnig, West Germany, and Heinrich Rohrer, Switzerland, design of
the scanning tunneling microscope.
   1987: Georg Bednorz, West Germany, and K. Alex Mueller,
Switzerland, for discovery of new superconducting materials.
   1988: Leon Lederman, Melvin Schwartz and Jack Steinberger, all
of the United States, cited for their work with neutrino beams that
``opened entirely new opportunities for research into the innermost
structure and dynamics of matter.''
   1989: Norman F. Ramsey, United States, for developing method of
structure of atoms that led to atomic clock used as the
international time standard, and Hans G. Dehmelt, United States,
and Wolfgang Paul, West Germany, for method to isolate single atoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1425EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Nobel-Chemistry-List     10-12 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nobel-Chemistry-List,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of Recent Nobel Winners in Chemistry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nobels Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the winners of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry since 1970
and their accomplishments.
   1970: Luis F. Leloir, Argentina. Discovery of sugar nucleotides.
   1971: Gerhard Herzberg, Canadia. Rsearch into the structure of
molecules.
   1972: Christian B. Anfinsen, Stanford Moore and William H.
Stein, United States. Fundamental research in enzymes.
   1973: Geoffrey Wilkinson, Britain, and Ernst Fischer, Germany.
Research into organometallic compounds.
   1974: Paul J. Flory, United States. Research into polymer
chemistry.
   1975: John W. Cornforth, Britain, and Vladimir Prelog,
Switzerland. Research into stereochemistry.
   1976: William N. Lipscomb Jr., United States. Determining the
structure of boranes and their reactions under various conditions.
   1977: Ilya Prigogine, Belgium, Formulating the theory of
dissipative structures.
   1978: Peter Mitchell, Britain. Discovery of the
energy-generating potential of certain enzymes.
   1979: Herbert C. Brown, United States, and George Wittig,
Germany. Development of use of boron- and phosphorous-containing
compounds as important reagents in organic synthesis.
   1980: Paul Berg, United States; fundamental studies of the
biochemistry of nucleic acids; and Walter Gilbert, United States,
and Frederick Sanger, Britain, contributions concerning the base
sequences in nucleic acids.
   1981: Kenichi Fukui, Japan, and Roald Hoffmann, United States.
Work in theoretical chemistry in anticipating the course of
chemical reactions.
   1982: Aaron Klug, Britain. Work on the structure of genes.
   1983: Henry Taube, United States. Work in explaining chemical
reactions reactions in everything from photosynthesis in plants to
batteries and fuel cells.
   1984: R. Bruce Merrifield, United States. Development of
methodology for chemical synthesis on a solid matrix.
   1985: Herbert A. Hauptman and Jerome Karle, both United States.
Developing methods to determine the molecular structure of crystals.
   1986: Dudley R. Herschbach and Yuan T. Lee, both United States,
and John C. Polanyi, Canadian. Research showing how basic chemical
reactions take place.
   1987: Donald J. Cram and Charles J. Pedersen, both United
States, and Jean-Marie Lehn, France, for syntheses of molecules
that mimic important biological processes.
   1988: Johann Deisenhofer, a Dallas-based researcher, and West
German colleagues Robert Huber and Hartmut Michel for work done in
Germany to determine the structure of certain proteins needed in
photosynthesis.
   1989: Thomas Cech, United States, and Canadian Sidney Altman,
who showed independently that RNA, once thought to be merely a
genetic messenger, could actively aid chemical reactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1425EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Namibia     10-12 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Namibia,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Asks U.N. to Continue Namibian Rights Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department urged U.N. officials
Thursday to continue ``as aggressively as possible'' their
investigation into allegations that Namibian guerrillas have
committed human rights abuses against fellow rebels for more than a
decade.
   Department spokesman Margaret Tutwiler said the United States is
pleased that Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N. special representative in
Namibia, has pursued the allegations made against the rebels of the
South-West Africa People's Organization, known as SWAPO.
   Ahtisaari said at a news conference in Windhoek, Namibia, on
Wednesday that he has been unable so far to verify reports that
SWAPO members imprisoned, tortured and killed hundreds from their
own ranks since 1977.
   In visits to SWAPO camps in Angola and Zambia, the U.N. team
said it could not find a single detainee among the 1,100 cases it
is investigating.
   But Tutwiler said 315 people of the 1,100 have not yet been
found.
   ``We note that his report ... states categorically that the
investigation will continue,'' Tutwiler said. ``We are concerned at
this large number of persons unaccounted for and encourage UNTAG
(the United Nations Transition Assistance Group) to pursue their
cases and any others that may come to its attention as aggressively
as possible,'' she said.
   SWAPO leaders, she said, have ``admitted their organization
detained certain persons it regards as spies sent by South
Africa.'' SWAPO must ``provide a full accounting for those persons
immediately,'' Tutwiler said.
   SWAPO is expected to win a majority in the Nov. 7 elections in
which Namibians are to elect an assembly to draft a constitution
for the independence of their country, a former U.N. trust
territory governed by South Africa.
   SWAPO waged a guerrilla war against South Africa for 23 years.
That ended last April, when the parties agreed to a U.N.-sponsored
plan that spells out steps that are to lead to independence for the
mineral-rich country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PsychiatricCongress     10-12 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Psychiatric Congress,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrists to Decide Whether to Readmit Soviets to World Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLAIRE SPRINGETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the World Psychiatric
Association gathered Thursday at a conference to decide whether to
readmit colleagues from the Soviet Union.
   The international professional body for psychiatrists, meeting
for the first time in six years, is taking up the Soviet question
during its weeklong congress amid allegations that political
dissidents are still being punished in Soviet psychiatric hospitals.
   In a preliminary meeting Wednesday, the group's executive
committee, led by its president, Kostas Stefanis, recommended
re-entry for the Soviets, known officially as the All-Union Society
of Psychiatrists and Narcologists.
   The Soviet state-sanctioned society was forced to withdraw from
the world body in 1983 after allegations surfaced that dissidents
were being certified as insane.
   ``The Soviets admit that some excesses took place in their
country in the past, and say that these will not be repeated in the
future,'' Stefanis said.
   Three dissident Soviet psychiatrists who have been interned in
psychiatric hospitals and now live in the West said before the
congress opened that admitting the official Soviet group would be
``tantamount to condoning abuse.''
   One of the men, Anatoly Koryagin, said the Soviet psychiatric
establishment has admitted individual instances of wrong diagnosis
but continues to deny the systematic abuse of psychiatry.
   The congress opened in a tense atmosphere after the
association's general assembly clashed in the preliminary session
over voting procedures that will affect the ballot on the Soviet
issue.
   Delegates from the United States, Britain, West Germany, Canada
and Australia alleged that changes to voting statutes proposed by
the association's executive committee were aimed at facilitating
re-entry for the Soviets, according to sources at the meeting.
   The association's general assembly is scheduled to vote on the
Soviet question Tuesday.
   The association's executive committee executive came under fire
from some of its members in March when it gave provisional
membership to the official Soviet group, pending a final decision
at the Athens congress.
   A U.S. delegation led by a State Department official went to the
Soviet Union in February to check claims that psychiatry was no
longer being used as a political weapon. The U.S. psychiatrists
said that despite some progress, more legal safeguards were needed
to prevent the hospitalization of dissidents.
   On the basis of the U.S. report, the American Psychiatric
Association, a member of the international body, decided to vote
against full membership for the Soviet society at the Athens
congress.
   Robert van Voren, the leader of a Netherlands-based human rights
group that is campaigning against re-entry of the Soviets, said the
use of psychiatry for politcal reasons is still common in the
Soviet Union.
   ``We have evidence of 40 dissidents who are being held in Soviet
Psychiatric institutions for political reasons,'' van Voren said in
an interview.
   Van Voren's pressure group, the International Association on the
Political Use of Psychiatry, will brief delegates on allegations of
psychiatric abuse in the Soviet Union before the vote.
   The main group will also decide on whether to admit a second
Soviet society of psychiatrists, the Independent Psychiatric
Association. That association, which does not have the backing of
the Soviet government, also maintains that the political use of
psychiatry is still continuing in the Soviet Union. The
international group can admit both Soviet associations.
   The congress also will discuss about 3,400 research papers on
psychiatry written by members of the world organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
