<FIRST>r w AM-CoalStrike     10-12 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elizabeth Dole to Visit Striking Miners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole will visit
striking coal miners Friday in southwest Virginia for a first-hand
look at the six-month walkout involving Pittston Co. mines in three
states, a department official said Thursday.
   ``She's frustrated and wants something to happen. Obviously, she
wants to see the strike resolved,'' said spokeswoman Dale Tate,
adding that Mrs. Dole isn't taking sides in the dispute.
   Mrs. Dole met earlier in Washington with Pittston chief Paul
Douglas and Richard Trumka, president of the United Mine Workers.
   ``We think that's a tremendous step in the right direction,''
Trumka said Thursday about Mrs. Dole's trip.
   The UMW official spoke at a news conference during which several
international labor leaders expressed strong concern over the coal
strike.
   ``Let's not beat around the bush _ this is a union-busting
dispute,'' said John Vanderveken, general secretary of the
International Confederation of Free Trade Unions.
   Vanderveken said his Brussels, Belgium-based organization, which
represents unions with 88 million members around the world, was
preparing to file a formal complaint with the International Labor
Organization citing ``flagrant worker abuses'' involved with the
Pittston strike.
   ``We have no double standards,'' he said. ``If something is
wrong in Poland, in the Soviet Union, we say so. And if something
is wrong in the United States, we say so also.''
   Vanderveken said the handling of the coal miners' strike by
state and federal authorities demonstrated that the enforcement of
labor law in the United States is ``heavily stacked in favor of
management.''
   The delegation of foreign labor leaders met earlier Thursday
with Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles, and spent Wednesday in the
southwest Virginia coalfields after meeting with Pittston chairman
Douglas.
   Contract talks resumed Thursday in suburban Washington after a
six-week break, but neither the company nor the union expected any
breakthroughs. They cannot even agree to meet in the same room and
have been using a federal mediator to relay messages.
   The strike involving Pittston's 1,695 union employees in
Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky began April 5 and has become a
rallying point for the U.S. labor movement.
   Peter Michalzik, general secretary of the Miners International
Federation, also based in Brussels, told striking miners at a rally
Wednesday: ``The Pittston strike is the No. 1 priority in our
organization.''
   Jacek Merkel, an official of Poland's Solidarity union who
directed shipyard strikes in Gdansk, said Solidarity won its
eight-year battle for recognition with support from labor around
the world. Now, he said, he wants to stand with the UMW.
   ``My boss, Lech Walesa, appealed to our government, `Let's start
negotiating.' I wish that here, Pittston would start negotiating,''
Merkel said.
</TEXT>
