<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     10-12 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armani Looks to Morocco, But Stays in Milan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago, Giorgio Armani introduced his
liningless jacket and the ``moda Milanese'' was born.
   Now at the start of a new decade, it looks like Milan's favorite
son will continue to be the mainstay of Italian ready-to-wear,
after the success of his new spring-summer 1990 collection
presented Wednesday night.
   ``He's simply the best,'' said Kal Ruttenstein, vice-president
of fashion for Bloomingdale's.
   The Italian fashion industry breathed a sigh of relief this
month when Armani, whose annual sales are valued at $350 million,
turned down a tempting offer to become artistic director at Lanvin
in Paris.
   The once-united front of the Milanese designers has suffered
some major upsets in the past year.
   The rising star of Italian ready-to-wear, Romeo Gigli, whose
waif-like styles received mixed reviews, in March took his show to
Paris, where he was hailed as the greatest thing to hit the runway
since Christian Lacroix.
   At the beginning of the summer, Gianfranco Ferre accepted the
post of designate designer at the famed house of Dior, and his
first couture collection in July was a success.
   Ferre still designs his own label out of Milan, but whereas
optimists see the Dior job as a feather in Italian fashion's cap,
others _ including Armani _ view it as a French victory in the
eternal fashion battle between the two countries.
   In a recent interview in Italy's weekly L'Espresso magazine,
Armani commented wryly: ``Does anyone really think the French are
stupid enough to promote an Italian name?''
   For the moment, Armani is satisfied to launch his fashion
fantasy from Milan, and his new collection is proof that things are
calm in the Armani empire, which includes more than 100 Emporio
shops in Europe and the United States; 200 stores in Japan that
carry his line; and his own stores in such major capitals as Rome,
Paris, London and New York.
   The new Armani style for the spring-summer 1990, presented to a
select crowd of 1,000 fashion followers in Milan's elegant Palazzo
Senato, is long and languid. Airy fabrics and loose styles which
often draw their inspiration from Morocco give the collection a
soft, serene look.
   His new jacket is extra long, either double-breasted, with three
buttons or no buttons at all. Sleeves are often over-long, and the
newest jacket is closed over the front to button at the shoulder.
   Although the look is of natural simplicity, almost too simple
for its $1,000 price tag, the workmanship is Armani perfection, and
the fabrics are luxuriously light raw silks and feather-weight
wools.
   These jackets are worn over short, seemingly hemless skirts or
baggy trousers.
   From Morocco, Armani brought back the harem pant, which he puts
under sporty jackets by day, under tunics and lavish evening gowns
by night.
   His favorite harem pant lightly sweeps the floor in silk chiffon
or georgette, often worn with an Indian embroidered strapless top.
   For that special evening, Armani embroiders his softly draped
gowns with myriads of crystals and pearls. His new evening look is
a short embroidered gown with a puffed-out skating skirt over airy
harem pants.
   Colors match the soft warmth of a Mediterranean summer night,
twilight blue, sunset red, dusk white, pine green, burnt yellow and
terracotta orange. Prints copied the designs of delicate oriental
porcelain and Middle Eastern pottery.
   Armani is not one for ornate accessories. In keeping with the
simplicity of the collection, he displayed only large drop
earrings. Footwear is soft and flat, allowing his models to steal
down the runway like thieves in an Arabian night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
