<FIRST>r w AM-FCCBudget     10-12 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Budget,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Spending Approved by House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel Thursday authorized Federal
Communications Commission spending of $231.3 million for fiscal
years 1990 and 1991.
   On a voice vote, the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications and finance subcommittee approved the $109.8
million the FCC had sought for fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1, and
$121.5 million for 1991.
   The House panel earlier had proposed the agency receive $117.8
million for fiscal 1991. But in Thursday's hearing, Reps. Edward
Markey, D-Mass., and Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J., offered an amendment
to provide nearly $4 million more.
   They said the extra money was to cover the costs of moving and
consolidating FCC offices in late 1991 and to add staff and
facilities to help the FCC regulate an increasingly complex
telecommunications industry.
   The increase also will help the agency ``regain the strength
that has been sapped in recent years,'' Rinaldo said.
   The FCC's 1989 budget was $99.6 million, the same amount it
received in 1988.
   Former FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick told the panel earlier this
year the agency's backlog of licensing applications was soaring
because of budget restraints.
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee last
week authorized $109.8 million in 1990, but only $119.8 million in
fiscal 1991.
   In other action, the House subcommittee, on voice votes:
   _Approved a section of the 1989 Americans With Disabilities Act
that would require telephone companies to provide two-way
communications, at no additional charge to individual users, to
speech or hearing impaired people who utilize telecommunications
devices for the deaf (TDDs).
   TDDs are typewriter-like devices that permit written messages to
be sent by telephone. A telephone operator then relays either a
spoken or written message to another person.
   _Authorized National Telecommunications and Information
Administration spending of $14.6 million in fiscal 1990 and $14.7
million for fiscal 1991. The NTIA, a Commerce Department agency,
advises the White House on telecommunications policy and
administers the Public Telecommunications Facilities Program, which
makes matching capital grants to aid non-profit communications
projects.
</TEXT>
