<FIRST>u w AM-Woerner-Pact 340   10-12 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woerner-Pact, 340</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Secretary General Sees Value In Eastern Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said
Thursday that the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact assures ``a certain form
of military stability'' in Europe.
   Woerner also predicted both military alliances would survive the
1990s, even amid political change in the East and West. NATO,
according to the former West German defense minister, guarantees
peace and peaceful change.
   ``I have no doubt if you were an East European you would see it
as the main source of stability,'' Woerner said at a news
conference.
   Similarily, he said, the Warsaw Pact serves a useful purpose.
   ``It guarantees a certain form of military stability,'' Woerner
said. ``As you can see, it does not prevent change'' in Poland,
Hungary and in a ``mild form'' in East Germany.
   ``It's not our role to make a settlement guaranteeing the
existence of both or one pact,'' Woerner said. ``That would be a
major mistake. That is not the question.''
   But, he said of the Warsaw Pact: ``I only think that being
interested in military stability for the foreseeable future, the
next decade where we have to ensure a peaceful change, I think it
can and might play a useful role.''
   Woerner said the two alliances would operate in the future with
fewer weapons and in a posture of defense. However, he stressed
NATO should not be dissolved.
   ``Even in a landscape of political change we need the solid and
sound defense,'' he said. ``Turmoil is in the air every time there
is change.''
   Besides, he said, if Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev failed
in his program to restructure the Soviet Union ``someone could look
for a military solution to their problems.''
   Woerner appeared before a session of the Atlantic Council of the
United States, a private research group that promotes U.S. ties
with Western Europe.
   He was in Washington for meetings with President Bush,
administration officials and members of Congress.
</TEXT>
