<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0625,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Resolves Better Environmental Protection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with passage of resolution.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party passed a
resolution Thursday for better protection of the environment, and a
leading party official told dissidents not to use environmental
issues for political purposes.
   The offficial news agency CTK said the resolution, passed at the
end of a two-day Central Committee meeting, specified reductions in
heavy industry and metallurgy, lower energy consumption and
introduction of new technologies.
   On Wednesday, Politburo member Ivan Knotek told the committee:
``We must act resolutely against unrealistic, destructive and ...
anti-socialist attitudes manifested in the actions of the so-called
informal or illegal groups,'' CTK reported.
   ``They abuse the justified interest of our people in improving
the environment. ... Their demagogy stops at nothing.''
   Police dispersed 300 activists Sept. 13 who were protesting
construction of a coke plant at Stonava, near the Polish border.
Environmentalists also oppose a joint Hungarian-Czechoslovak dam
project on the Danube River.
   Talks between Premier Ladislav Adamec and his Hungarian
counterpart, Miklos Nemeth, on Wednesday brought little progress in
resolving the deadlock over the dam project, which Hungary wants to
halt. It ``temporarily suspended'' construction May 13, citing
environmental concerns.
   Nemeth and Adamec agreed to meet again before the end of the
month, when Hungary's parliament is to decide whether to continue
the Hungarian side of the project at Nagymaros, CTK said.
   Unlike Hungary, one of the most liberal East bloc nations,
Czechoslovakia tolerates little dissent.
   ``We should not give in to manifestations of negativism and
inconclusiveness,'' Knotek said, blaming the ``industrial
development of capitalism'' for the world's poor environmental
situation.
   ``We cannot agree with the abuse of this (ecological) process .
.. (used) as political pressure against socialist countries,
including Czechoslovakia,'' CTK quoted him as saying.
   Czechoslovakia has been plagued by pollution from coal-fueled
power plants, excessive use of pesticides resulting in high
nitrogen content in the soil, and frequent oil leaks into its
rivers.
   The daily Lidova Demokracie said Thursday the ``sickness rate''
in Prague had doubled in 15 years because of air and water
pollution.
</TEXT>
