<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1554EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-IAPA     10-12 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IAPA,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organization Says Press Freedom `Grim'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The status of press freedom in the
Americas is grim because of the danger journalists face in such
countries as Colombia and Panama, the Inter-American Press
Association concluded Thursday.
   The IAPA is an organization of 1,300 newspapers from the United
States, Canada, Latin America and the Caribbean whose main goal is
to guarantee press freedom throughout the Western Hemisphere.
   About 400 IAPA members attended the four-day assembly in this
industrial center in northeastern Mexico, 150 miles from the Texas
border.
   ``Even as representatives of the Western Hemisphere's free press
met in Monterrey, Mexico, the sound of gunshots fired by enemies of
that free press echoed off the assembly's wall,'' the report said.
   Three Colombian newspaper employees and the wife of a Salvadoran
journalist were gunned down Tuesday.
   ``While some advances are being made in nations throughout the
hemisphere, the state of press freedom in the Americas still must
be regarded as grim as long as journalists and their families are
subject to the crudest form of censorship: death by
assassination,'' the organization said in a report issued on the
final day of its 45th general assembly.
   ``Nowhere is the struggle between the forces of darkness and the
forces of light more clearly drawn than in Colombia,'' the IAPA
said.
   ``There, at least 10 journalists have been murdered this year by
henchmen of the cocaine cartel, at least 40 in the past 12 years,''
the report said.
   Although the Colombian government is attempting to fight the
drug cartels, Panama's leader, Gen. Manuel Noriega, ``is in league
with the traffickers,'' the IAPA charged.
   Noriega, who heads Panama's Defense Forces, has closed every
independent newspaper, radio and televion station and arrested,
tortured or forced into exile a long list of reporters, according
to the association.
   ``In Cuba, public enemy No. 1 of press freedoms in the
hemisphere, repression of journalists both Cuban and foreign is
worse than ever,'' the organization concluded.
   Meanwhile, promises of press reform by Nicaragua's Sandinista
government ``have not materialized,'' the IAPA said.
   The organization listed Mexico, Chile, Paraguay and the
Dominican Republic under the ``good news category.''
   Mexico ``has witnessed large steps'' toward press freedoms under
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, it said, citing the
government's pledge to sell its newsprint monopoly. In the past,
the government censored independent newspapers by withholding
newsprint.
</TEXT>
