<SECOND>AM-People-Graham Memoirs,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Katharine Graham to Publish Memoirs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred A. Knopf Inc. said Thursday it will
publish the memoirs of Katharine Graham, chairman and chief
executive officer of The Washington Post Co.
   Mrs. Graham, one of only three female chief executive officers
of Fortune 500 companies, is writing the book herself, said her
editor, Elisabeth Sifton, executive vice president of Knopf, a part
of the Random House publishing organization. No date has been set
for completion of the manuscript.
   ``I am just delighted. Kay Graham and I have been discussing her
memoirs for several years,'' Robert L. Bernstein, chairman and
president of Random House, said in a statement. He declined to say
how much Mrs. Graham was being paid.
   Mrs. Graham is one of the foremost figures in American
journalism, as publisher of The Washington Post from 1969 to 1979,
and as head of The Washington Post Co., whose media operations
include Newsweek magazine as well as broadcasting systems.
   Her father, Eugene Meyer, a banker, bought the Post at public
auction in 1933 for $825,000.
   Mrs. Graham was publisher of the Post when the newspaper made
the decision to publish excerpts from the Pentagon Papers and to
pursue the Watergate scandals.
   The Washington Post reported that Mrs. Graham, 72, declined
Wednesday to give details of the forthcoming book.
   However, Knopf said it will cover her childhood; her marriage to
Philip Graham and her subsequent career, after his death, as
publisher; and ``a life that has been rich in association with some
of the most prominent people of our time.''
</TEXT>
