<SECOND>AM-US-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia Asking $1 Billion to Promote Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs `Yugoslavia is ...' with 1 graf to ADD that
Italy is believed to be the country that has agreed in principle to give
Yugoslavia a large loan.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslav Prime Minister Ante Markovic said
Thursday that he wants $1 billion for his communist country's
banking system to cushion the anticipated blows of economic and
political reforms.
   Markovic, whose plan to institute a market-oriented economy has
been blocked by Communist Party conservatives, said he would meet
with U.S. bankers and World Bank officials to promote his request.
   Yugoslavia is asking the 152-member World Bank for a loan of
$300 million to $350 million, and has reached an agreement in
principle with one European country for a large loan, he said.
Markovic declined to name the country, but sources said it is
believed to be Italy.
   Speaking to reporters at the National Press Club, the Yugoslav
leader said he had discussed his country's banking needs with
American bankers and would bring up the problem in talks with
administration officials. He meets Friday with President Bush.
   Markovic, an engineer named to his post in March, is urging the
development of private enterprise and an end to government
interference in the running of businesses, including a halt to
subsidies of money-losing ventures.
   He also wants to reshape the banking system along Western lines
and to introduce a stocks and bonds market.
   The proposed changes are designed to stem the country's
staggering inflation rate, which has reached 1,200 percent
annually, to lower the $19 billion foreign debt and the 17 percent
unemployment rate and to ease ethnic tensions among provinces.
   Markovic advocates a multiparty system to help solve
Yugoslavia's economic problems, but the Communist Party has blocked
the democratic reforms being embraced by Poland and Hungary.
   Unlike Poland and Hungary, Yugoslavia is not seeking direct U.S.
aid, Markovic said. Rather, it wants to promote joint ventures with
American businesses and to encourage foreign ownership in
Yugoslavia.
   Markovic said his meetings here are designed to explain new
Yugoslav legislation that enables foreign investment and to attract
the same kind of interest in Yugoslavia shown by European
businesses.
   He warned, however, that ``changes are bound to bring social
problems,'' including an increase in unemployment to about 20
percent.
   ``To reduce social tensions, we have to act as fast as
possible'' to develop the private sector and the banking system, he
said.
</TEXT>
