<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1525EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-OzoneHole     10-12 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone Hole,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Says Ozone Depletion Over Antarctic Equals Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Depletion of ozone in the stratosphere over
the South Pole has equalled the record level that scientists found
in 1987, NASA reported Thursday.
   Scientists at the Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md.,
said that satellite measurements show that ozone density over the
Antarctic has declined by about 45 percent since early August, a
drop of about 1.5 percent a day.
   Arlin Krueger, Richard Stolarski and Mark Schoeberl, scientists
monitoring the south polar ozone levels, said the ozone depletion
recorded Oct. 5 matched the record low measured in 1987.
   The depletion occurs in what scientists call a ``hole'' that is
formed by a high altitude formation of clouds, extreme cold and
certain wind patterns over the South Polar area. Such a hole can
remain undisturbed for months. The the ozone depletion appears to
correct itself in the polar summer, but then reappears in the cold
months.
   ``It's becoming clear that the ozone hole is not going away in
the near future, although the depth will vary from year to year,''
Krueger is quoted as saying in a news release from the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   NASA scientists have been monitoring ozone levels over the
southern hemisphere using an instrument on board the NIMBUS-7
satellite for more than 10 years.
   Last year, ozone concentrations over Antarctica dropped by about
15 percent in September, about a third of the current depletion.
   Other studies have found some seasonal thinning of the ozone
layer above the North Polar region.
   Ozone in the stratosphere can block much of the ultraviolet
radiation from the sun. When intact, the ozone layer, in effect,
prevents damaging levels of UV radiation from reaching Earth. An
excess exposure to UV radiation is thought to be a major cause of
skin cancer, and some studies have shown that an increase in the
radiation also can harm plants and the human immune system.
   Depletion of the concentration of ozone is thought to be
increased by the interaction of certain manmade chemicals,
principally cholorfluorocarbons, or CFCs, a chemical used for
refrigerants and in the manufacture of some plastic products.
   Some U.S. manufacturers and users of CFCs have announced plans
to stop making the chemical compound or to guard against releasing
the chemicals into the atmosphere.
   Though it is a major component of smog and an atmospheric
pollutant at ground level, ozone forms an important part of the
radiation protection belt surrounding the Earth in the
stratosphere, which begins about 9{ miles above the Earth and
extends upward to about 39 miles.
   Ozone is a substance composed of three atoms of oxygen. It is
created naturally during thunderstorms. Common atmospheric oxygen
is composed of two atoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1613EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--Tobacco     10-12 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Tobacco,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Smoking Decline Not Fast Enough for Federal No-Smoking Goal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of smoking among Americans continues to
decline slowly but steadly, but the nation isn't likely to reach a
federal goal of 75 percent non-smokers by next year, federal health
officials said Thursday.
   A face-to-face survey of adult Americans, conducted in 1987,
shows that 28.8 percent are cigarette smokers, the national Centers
for Disease Control reported.
   That's down from 30.1 percent in a similar 1985 survey, but the
decline is apparently not enough for government researchers to
project meeting the official federal goal of less than 25 percent
by 1990.
   ``We're getting pretty close,'' said Dr. Ron Davis, director of
the CDC's Office of Smoking and Health. ``We're making progress,
and we're heading in the right direction.''
   CDC officials believed two years ago that the 1990 goal _ one of
several federal health targets set as this decade began _ could be
reached, partly because of a 1986 survey showing a national smoking
rate of 26.5 percent.
   But that survey, conducted by telephone, probably wasn't as
precise as the face-to-face survey reported Thursday, Davis said.
   The CDC said Thursday that smoking rates continue to fall by a
steady half percentage point a year as they've done since 1964 _
the year of the surgeon general's landmark warning that smoking
causes cancer and heart disease. At that time, 40 percent of the
country's adults smoked.
   The number of Americans who smoke will continue to drop,
possibly until just a small ``hard-core'' band of smokers is left,
Davis predicted.
   ``So far, we haven't seen any evidence of a leveling off (in
smoking's decline),'' he said.
   ``We need to intensify our efforts. ... Smokers tomorrow may be
more resistant to our message than smokers today,'' Davis said.
``We still have almost 400,000 Americans dying every year because
of smoking-related disease. We can't be complacent about smoking
rates going down.''
   The CDC's report, based on a survey of about 44,000 people,
showed that one in three adult Americans _ 39 percent of men and 27
percent of women _ uses tobacco of some sort, including cigarettes,
pipes, cigars and chewing tobacco. Among men, 31 percent smoke
cigarettes, compared to 27 percent of women.
   The report said young people are more likely to smoke cigarettes
than are older people; 33 percent of Americans age 25-44 smoke,
compared with 19 percent age 65-74 and 9 percent 75 and older.
   Five percent of U.S. adult men smoke cigars, while 3 percent
smoke pipes. Four percent use chewing tobacco and 3 percent use
snuff. The percentage of women using such alternate forms of
tobacco was well below 1 percent.
   The margin of error in the survey is 1 percent for all adults,
somewhat higher for subgroups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0142 </DOCNO>
