said in a statement. ``The station is such a part of New York, it's
really a natural outlet for me.''
   Kakoyiannis said he wasn't worried about how the mayor would
stack up with his morning drive time competition like ``shock
radio'' personality Howard Stern. ``I think he's funnier, cleaner
and more New York.''
   Others are also vying for Koch's time. New York Post Editor
Jerry Nachman denied reports in The Wall Street Journal that the
Post has an agreement with the mayor to write a column after his
term ends. But he said they're talking about it.
   ``The newspaper stories are further along than the
negotiations,'' Nachman said.
   The lame-duck Democrat, who lost the party's mayoral nomination
to Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins in September, already
has accepted a one-year post as a visiting fellow at New York
University.
