<FIRST>b w PM-DC-10Part-Crack     10-12 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Part-Crack,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Investigators Find Crack in DC-10 Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety investigators said today they
had found an apparently pre-existing crack in the engine disk
discovered in an Iowa corn field nearly three months after the
crash of an airliner that killed 112 people.
   James Kolstad, acting chairman of the National Transportation
Safety Board, said the precise ``size, nature and reason for the
crack'' has yet to be determined.
   ``There has been no determination on whether this crack was
detectable before the accident, nor has there been a determination
whether this crack is the point of origin of engine failure,'' said
board spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz. He said it had not been
determined whether the crack should have been caught in the last
engine inspection before the crash
   He and Kolstad said, however that preliminary evidence indicates
the crack existed prior to the July 19 United Airlines crash at
Sioux City, Iowa.
   The middle engine in the DC-10 disintegrated in flight, severing
hydraulic lines and making the plane almost impossible to steer.
The craft cartwheeled out of control as the pilots were trying to
make an emergency landing.
</TEXT>
