<FIRST>u w AM-Shuttle-ShortCircuit 1stLd-Writethru a0684 10-12 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Short Circuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Confirms Short Circuit on Recent Shuttle Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New information throughout; no danger to astronauts, problem
corrected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A short circuit, lasting about 1 1@2 seconds,
caused some sparks and smoke on the middeck of the space shuttle
Columbia on its flight in August, NASA said Thursday.
   ``There is no ndication the astronauts were ever in any
danger,'' said NASA spokeswoman Sarah Keegan.
   The space agency confirmed a report, broadcast by Cable News
Network, that the crew handled the short circuit by unplugging a
teleprinter. The cause, NASA said, appeared to be damage to
insulation on a cable that connected the printer to the spaceship's
electrical system.
   A redesigned cable has been installed aboard Atlantis for the
Galileo space probe mission next week. The covering has been
changed to Teflon to make it more flexible, Miss Keegan said.
   The shuttle, with five astronauts aboard, was on a military
mission on the Aug. 8-13 flight and the crew maintained radio
silence throughout.
   ``The crew reported seeing some sparks and some smoke was
recorded by one of the cabin smoke detectors,'' NASA said in a
response prepared for questions that were raised about the incident
in late August.
   ``While the detector recorded the smoke twice, it was not enough
to sound the alarm aboard the orbiter,'' NASA said. ``There is no
evidence that the short was caused by the teleprinter in any way.
The most likely cause is physical damage to the cable conductor
insulation material.''
</TEXT>
