<FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     10-12 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>152 Boat People Arrive in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship carrying 152 Vietnamese refugees arrived
Thursday at the Japanese island of Iriomote Shima, 125 miles east
of Taiwan, Japan's Maritime Safety Agency said.
   An official of the agency, which is Japan's coast guard, said an
agency patrol boat would tow the ship to Naha, Okinawa, for
questioning of the boat people because engine trouble had left the
ship unable to sail under its own power.
   The ship is to arrive in Naha on Saturday, said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   One of the boat people told authorities the group left Vietnam
on Sept. 10 and visited China's Hainan Island and Taiwan before
arriving at Iriomote Shima, the official said.
   With the new arrival, 3,371 Vietnamese boat people have arrived
in Japan this year, compared with 219 in all of 1988, Justice
Ministry officials said.
   At least 754 of the recent arrivals, however, were Chinese
nationals trying to enter Japan by posing as Vietnamese refugees,
they said.
   On Sept. 13, Japan began a policy of screening boat people and
accepting those deemed to be fleeing political persecution but
refusing permission to stay for those who came to seek economic
betterment.
   On Monday, Vietnamese Ambassador to Japan Vo Van Sang said his
goverment would take back economic migrants only if they wanted to
return home.
</TEXT>
