<FIRST>r a AM-APAssessment     10-12 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Assessment,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Board Approves 4.9 Percent Assessment Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of The Associated Press
approved a 1990 general assessment increase of 4.9 percent for
newspaper and broadcast members.
   The increase takes effect Jan. 14, 1990, for AP's 1,705
newspaper and 5,800 broadcast members.
   William J. Keating, AP board chairman and chief executive
officer of the Detroit Newspaper Agency, said the increase was
needed to help pay for new services for the members, necessary
staff additions and election year expenses, as well as other new
costs.
   Keating noted that for the fourth year in a row, the increase
was less than next year's predicted rate of inflation.
   ``Tight cost controls and growing revenues from non-traditional
sources enabled the board to limit the increase and continue to
improve service,'' Keating said. ``Those other sources now
contribute 22 percent of our revenue.''
   Keating said the AP's proposed operating and capital budgets
were examined by the board on a detailed, line-by-line basis.
   The budgets provide for launching of AP's high speed photo
delivery system, PhotoStream; expansion, installation and training
for the new SelectStocks market services; and other new products
for AP members.
   The general assessment increase will be combined with another
step in the phase-in of the circulation-based newspaper formula for
those members that have not yet reached their appropriate
assessment level. The 1990 assessment will also reflect any
circulation changes at the member newspaper.
   Each member will receive exact figures on the assessment change
by Nov. 1, Keating said.
</TEXT>
