<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GrainReserves     10-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain Reserves,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker, Experts Criticize Grain Reserve Depletion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Dakota lawmaker and food-supply
experts said Thursday that the Bush administration's depletion of
grain reserves has artificially held down prices and taken away the
nation's buffer against shortages.
   ``It appears to me ... that the USDA has intentionally used our
reserve programs to soften the price of wheat,'' Rep. Byron Dorgan,
D-N.D., told the House Agriculture subcommittee on wheat, soybeans
and feed grains.
   Prices, he said, are shaped by supply and supply is determined
by the amount of grain in the fields, granaries and the pipeline.
   ``USDA used the reserve grain to keep the pipeline full, so even
though the supply in the granaries is dwindling, the pipeline
remains full and millers and exporters don't have to look far for
wheat,'' Dorgan said.
   But with reserves dwindling, the price-stabilizing buffer is
nearly gone, said Rodney Leonard, executive director of Community
Nutrition Institute, a consumer group.
   ``Grain and food prices in the U.S. and the world have been
relatively stable over the past three years only because the U.S.
had unintentionally built an enormous stockpile of wheat, corn and
feed grain,'' Leonard said.
   The United States' emergency grain reserve of 4 million tons of
wheat, or about 170 million bushels, will be gone by next spring,
he said.
   ``Secretary of Agriculture Clayton Yeutter, who is guardian of
this reserve, released it last month, but under circumstances that
hardly qualify as an emergency for which the reserve was
designed,'' Leonard told the subcommittee.
   On Sept. 13, Yeutter gave wheat farmers permission to increase
production for 1990 to allow the government to replenish wheat
reserves. The next day, President Bush announced Yeutter would have
the authority to take grain out of reserve for food aid.
   Leonard said that in the past food-aid needs have been supplied
by the open market and benefited farmers by causing prices to go
up. The administration's action, however, kept prices from rising.
   ``It is our judgment that the flexibility in the management of
reserves has been overdone,'' said Don Reeves, a Nebraska farmer
and policy analyst for Bread for the World, a 40,000 member
Christian organization that wants to help alleviate world hunger.
   ``We are distressed at the more recent drawdown of reserve
stocks to levels we regard as risky, if not dangerous,'' he said.
   Dorgan, Leonard and Reeves were among witnesses called by
subcommittee chairman Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., in his effort to
formulate a policy for use of grain reserves that could become part
of the 1990 farm bill.
   Neither Congress nor the White House has determined the specific
purpose of withholding grain, leading the reserves to be used for a
variety of things, such as emergency aid to foreign countries, feed
for livestock in time of drought, export subsidies or manipulation
of market prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
