<FIRST>r a AM-TelephoneStrike     10-12 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telephone Strike,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYNEX Phone Company And Striking Unions Agree To Mediation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NYNEX Corp. and union officials agreed Thursday to
have mediators intervene in a 10-week-old strike involving 60,000
telephone workers.
   ``We're looking optimistically on this since we've been asking
for months and months to have (a mediator),'' said Adele Stacy, a
spokeswoman for the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   She said unions first requested an independent mediator Aug. 3
but telephone company officials had resisted the idea until
reversing their stance Thursday.
   ``All parties acknowledge that it is in the best interest of
employees and customers to bring the strike to a conclusion as
quickly as possible,'' the company and unions said in a joint
statment.
   Officials for both sides said further details regarding
scheduled meetings and progress in the mediation process would be
jointly announced. It was not immediately clear whether discussions
would be conducted on a state or federal level, officials said.
   Negotiators had arrived at a standoff Wednesday after talks
abruptly broke off under conditions each side blamed on the other.
   IBEW spokesman Robert Silva said union officials were developing
a counterproposal to the latest offer by New England Telephone Co.,
a NYNEX subsidiary, when they were told the company would not
consider an alternative.
   But Peter Cronin, a spokesman for New England Telephone, offered
a different version. He said union officials had been
``unresponsive to the needs of its striking members'' and failed to
show up for talks Wednesday on the ``improved'' proposal offered by
the company.
   That proposal was laid on the table Tuesday in the first
bargaining session held this month.
   Workers walked off the job Aug. 6 after contract discussions
broke down over salary and health care issues. The Communications
Workers of America, which represents 40,000 workers at NYNEX's New
York Telephone subsidiary, and the IBEW, whose 20,000 workers are
at New England Telephone, struck over NYNEX's insistence that the
workers pay up to $1,500 a year in health care costs.
   Negotiations have progressed slowly or not at all since
employees walked off the job, leaving customers throughout New
England and New York with delays in directory assistance, repairs
and installation.
   Strikes that broke out in several other regional telephone
companies were settled in relatively quick order. The regional
companies were created in 1984 by the breakup of American Telephone
&amp; Telegraph.
</TEXT>
