<FIRST>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     10-12 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preschool Molest,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Begins Final Argument in Marathon Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution in the lengthy McMartin
Pre-School molestation trial began his closing argument Thursday,
telling jurors the school's young students were snared in a web of
gradually escalating abuse.
   The chief defendant, Raymond Buckey, 31, appeared calm and
relaxed when Deputy District Attorney Roger Gunson began his
summation of the case, which at 2{ years is the nation's longest
criminal trial.
   Buckey said in the courthouse hallway he felt ``OK'' and added:
``I'm relieved. It's now down to just weeks, and we're finally
getting to a jury.''
   Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62, are charged
with a total of 64 counts of molestation and a shared count of
conspiracy involving 11 children at the family-owned Manhattan
Beach preschool.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders, who has worried aloud
about completing the trial because no alternate jurors are left,
said each side would have 6{ days for arguments and he expects a
lengthy deliberation.
   Gunson sought to explain how crimes were committed by people who
have been portrayed in court as not being like molesters, and how
they went unreported.
   ``Although parents would expect their child to tell them if they
were abused, they don't,'' Gunson said.
   Referring to expert testimony, Gunson said this was because it
was not a case of a stranger molesting and injuring a child, but
rather a gradual entrapment and web of secrecy growing up around
the defendants' actions.
   The web tightened by means of gifts and games, and benefited
from children's fears of being blamed and not being believed,
according to the theory.
   Expert testimony also showed that molesters often feel genuine
affection toward children who return that affection, the prosecutor
said.
   ``We have Mr. Buckey saying he loved children,'' he said.
   Gunson told jurors they should not assume that some stories
changed because children had talked with prosecutors and therapists
from Children's Institute International, a child-abuse detection
and treatment center.
   The defense has argued that the children were, in effect,
brainwashed.
   Gunson launched into a detailed summary of events, focusing
first on a girl who testified she was molested and made to play a
``naked movie star'' game.
   The girl was 2 years, 8 months old when she entered the school
in September 1977 and was 5{ years old when she left in 1980. She
was 9 years old when she first talked to therapists at Children's
Institute International and was 12 by the time she testified at the
trial.
   More than 1,000 pieces of evidence have been entered, $15
million has been spent, 124 witnesses have testified and every one
of the six alternate jurors has been used because of illness and
employment problems. Court proceedings have produced 60,000 pages
of record.
   The case began in 1983 as the largest child molestation
prosecution ever. Authorities said hundreds of children were
molested over five years. Seven teachers were arrested and charged
with 207 counts.
   Prosecutors said children were molested during rituals with
satanic overtones, then terrified into silence by teachers who
mutilated animals and threatened to harm the pupils' parents.
   After an 18-month preliminary hearing, District Attorney Ira
Reiner dismissed charges against five defendants, saying there was
too little evidence to try them. The hearing alone cost the
government $6 million.
   The trial became the longest criminal trial in U.S. history in
April, surpassing the two-year record of California's Hillside
Strangler case.
</TEXT>
