<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Oranges     10-12 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Oranges,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Orange Harvest Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's orange harvest for the 1989-90
crop season is forecast at 194.4 million boxes, down 6 percent from
last season, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   ``This decline is due mostly to Florida's 11 percent decrease
from last year,'' the department said. ``Freezing weather in
Florida during late February killed most of the open bloom and
damaged new growth.''
   In its first forecast for 1989-90, USDA estimated Florida's
orange harvest at 130 million boxes, down from 146.6 million last
season.
   California production was forecast at 61 million boxes, up from
57 million last year, and the Arizona crop was put at 1.4 million
boxes, down from 1.7 million. The Texas crop was indicated at 1.95
million boxes, up from 1.85 million.
</TEXT>
