<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2000EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSDoctors     10-12 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Doctors,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds AIDS Attitudes, Behavior Out of Sync</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people realize the chances of getting AIDS
from an infected doctor are remote, but nearly 45 percent believe
physicians with the disease should not be allowed to practice
medicine, according to a survey.
   More than half _ 55.7 percent _ said if they learned their
doctor had AIDS, they'd change doctors, according to survey results
published in Friday's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   There have been no documented cases in the United States of a
patient contracting AIDS from his physician, a spokesman for the
federal Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta said Thursday.
   The AMA said the survey results indicate Americans need to be
better educated about AIDS, and it cautioned that doctors must be
afforded the same civil liberties as other citizens.
   ``Education alone is not enough,'' said AMA board member Dr.
Nancy Dickey. ``While education is necessary, we must reaffirm the
rights of physicians.''
   The survey of 2,000 people was conducted by telephone during the
summer of 1988. Half of the respondents, who were selected at
random, lived in areas with a high number of AIDS cases while the
other half were chosen from all areas of the United States. The
authors said there was no significant difference in the two groups'
responses.
   Two-thirds of those polled said they believe the chance of
contracting AIDS from an infected doctor is unlikely or
non-existent, while 11 percent said they consider the chance of
infection very likely and 22 percent considered it somewhat likely.
   Eighty percent of the respondents said a physician with AIDS
should be obligated to tell his patients and 32 percent felt they
should be told if their doctors were even treating patients with
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``There is a generalized fear of AIDS that's not just related to
concern about getting infected,'' said Bryan Maguire, co-author of
the article.
   ``I think it shows that AIDS education is not the solution to
the whole problem,'' said Maguire, a research associate at the
University of California, San Francisco's Dentistry School.
   ``That's why we need anti-discrimination legislation. Just
having the knowledge isn't enough to counteract'' fears, Maguire
said.
   In an editorial accompanying the study, Dickey said physicians
have the right to confidentiality in matters that are not pertinent
to their practice.
   ``There is no ethical obligation'' for a doctor to tell his
patients he has AIDS, the editorial said.
   ``It is imperative that physicians be extended at least the
simplest of civil liberties that are extended to all other citizens
_ the right to privacy and the right to work so long as others are
not at risk.''
   The editorial reiterated the AMA's ethical position that
physicians who run even a minimal risk of infecting their patients
must refrain from practicing. Doctors who carry the AIDS virus must
consult with their own physicians to establish any limits necessary
to ensure the disease is not passed on, the editorial said.
   The CDC, however, recommends that AIDS-infected surgeons with
open lesions who run the risk of direct contact with patients
refrain from work, said CDC spokesman Charles Fallis.
   ``That's the only case in which the CDC recommends that any
health-care worker refrain from practice.''
   AIDS cripples the body's defenses against disease, leaving a
person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers. The
fatal, incurable disease is caused by a virus that is spread mainly
through sexual intercourse, sharing of contaminated hypodermic
needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during
birth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
