<FIRST>r w BC-Congress-Abortion-SwitchersCORRECTIVE     10-12 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Congress-Abortion-Switchers CORRECTIVE,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Members who used a0751, BC-Congress-Abortion-Switchers, sent
Oct. 11 under a Washington dateline are asked to use the following story.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press erroneously reported on
Wednesday that Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., was among a group of House
members who voted in favor of looser restrictions for federally
funded abortions for poor women after voting against a similar
provision a year ago.
   The error resulted from a mistake in the Congressional Record
listing of votes from Sept. 8, 1988.
   Ms. Martin was listed on a roll call vote from Sept. 8, 1988 as
being ``paired'' against a proposal to expand Medicaid abortion
coverage to women who are victims of rape or incest.
   But in the Congressional Record of Sept. 13, 1988, Martin said
her vote of four days earlier had been paired incorrectly, and she
should have been recorded as favoring the broader coverage.
   A paired vote means a member was not in the chamber, but was
matched with another lawmaker who voted the opposite and both were
recorded as voting accordingly.
</TEXT>
