<FIRST>u w AM-HUD 1stLd-Writethru a0702 10-12 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Reform Proposals Encounter Congressional Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 15th graf pvs, Just two, and last graf to CORRECT style
on ``rock 'n' roll.'' ^By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack
Kemp ran into opposition Thursday from members of Congress to some
of the measures he is recommending for cleaning up his
scandal-ridden department.
   Both Republicans and Democrats on the House Banking Committee
sharply criticized Kemp's proposal to target more of the
politically popular Community Development Block Grant (CDBG)
program to strict antipoverty efforts.
   ``That was not the original intent of that program _ a targeted
war on poverty,'' said Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, the ranking
Republican on the banking panel, which has oversight
responsibilities for HUD.
   ``To stifle the certain degree of flexibility that CDBG has with
its intentions would be absolutely outrageous to me,'' echoed Rep.
Mary Rose Oakar, a Democrat from Cleveland. ``I don't want to see
some guidelines changed to inhibit my city's opportunity to use
that money.''
   Under current regulations, only 60 percent of the $3 billion
that HUD funnels annually to state and local governments through
CDBG grants for downtown revitalization projects must directly
benefit poor people.
   As part of a 58-point plan to address widescale fraud,
mismanagement and influence-peddling at HUD during the Reagan
administration, Kemp last week proposed raising poverty-related
targets for CDBG grants and housing subsidy programs to 75 percent.
   ``To avoid both the appearance and reality of favoritism,'' Kemp
also proposed eliminating as political ``slush funds'' the
discretionary programs that allow HUD to ignore merit and
competition requirements in awarding community development and
housing grants.
   ``I want to kick politics out of those decisions,'' he said
Thursday. ``There would be no decision at HUD by Kemp, staff,
assistants or anyone based on who you know, what political party
you belong to, how many consultants you hire or how much you pay
them.''
   While generally praising the thrust of Kemp's proposed reform
measures, members of Congress as well as several mayors have
fidgeted the last week over the prospect of removing politics
entirely from the process.
   ``Since the loss of revenue sharing, many mayors have used this
as revenue sharing,'' Wylie told Kemp. ``The implication that if a
congressman calls about a project in his district there's something
wrong is most unfortunate.''
   Citing a litany of well-publicized past abuses, Kemp said the
discretionary funds and community development grants had often gone
toward financing golf courses, swimming pools, high-rise hotels and
scores of other projects with little or no benefit to the poor.
   ``If I don't have criteria, you're going to haul me before this
committee and have my head for doing things that are not figthing
poverty, building houses, taking care of the poor ...,'' Kemp said.
   However, Ms. Oakar and other members of the panel expressed
fears that past abuses will be cited as a reason to allow an
erosion in many of the programs.
   ``I'm not responsible because somebody in New York got a
swimming pool,'' she said. ``My city operates that program well. I
get the impression what we're going to do now is have this fortress
built up as an overreaction and as a substitute for programing.''
   Just two weeks ago, HUD rejected Cleveland's application for a
$6.9 million Urban Development Action Grant for a $48 million rock
'n' roll museum. Ms. Oakar said then she still hoped to get the
federal aid through one of the so-called ``discretionary'' accounts
that Kemp wants abolished.
   At Thursday's hearing, she repeatedly voice irritation.
   ``If I want housing for downtown Cleveland and I have some
phoney baloney regulations put up as a smokescreen so that our area
does not get housing, you better believe I'm going to fight you on
that,'' she told Kemp.
   ``Good, I'm a fighter,'' Kemp retorted. ``I want to be a
successful HUD secretary. ...But I have to call them as I see them,
and we don't think a UDAG grant for a rock 'n' roll museum was
necessary. It did not fit the criteria.''
</TEXT>
