<DOCNO> AP891012-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1747EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Matter 1stLd-Writethru a0715 10-12 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Matter, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0715,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atom-Smasher Experiments Point to Three Families of Matter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Everyday matter...', to delete reference to
leptons being a families of particles.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicists trying to mimic the birth of the
universe inside an atom smasher said Thursday they found strong
evidence that the building blocks of matter belong to only three
families, a discovery that ``puts a lid on the complexity of
nature.''
   ``This brings us closer to really understanding the physical
universe and how it's put together,'' said Burton Richter, a 1976
Nobel laureate in physics and director of the Stanford Linear
Accelerator Center 30 miles southeast of San Francisco.
   Experiments on the 3-mile-long, $125 million Stanford Linear
Collider showed the odds are 25-to-1 that there are only three
families or ``generations'' of fundamental particles that make up
matter, physicist Michael Riordan said by telephone from Stanford.
   ``It means that somehow the universe is comprehensible, that
it's not a total mystery, that it can be grasped by the human
mind,'' Riordan said. ``It puts a lid on the complexity of nature
at its most fundamental level.''
   Until now, atom smasher experiments indicated only that there
were no more than five or six families of fundamental particles
such as electrons and quarks, Richter said.
   The universe contains more matter than antimatter. If there were
fewer than three families of basic particles, the universe would
contain equal amounts of matter and antimatter, said David Schramm,
a University of Chicago astrophysicist.
   Because matter and antimatter destroy or ``annihilate'' each
other, existence of fewer than three families means ``we wouldn't
be here,'' he said. ``The whole universe would be filled with
radiation and very little else.''
   On the other hand, if the building blocks of matter belonged to
more than three families, the universe would contain more helium
gas than it does, Schramm said.
   Everyday matter is made of four particles belonging to the first
family. They are up quarks, down quarks, electrons and electron
neutrinos. Electrons and electron neutrinos are both classified as
``leptons.''
   Protons and neutrons in the nucleus of an atom are made of the
two types of quarks. Electrons orbit the nucleus. Electron
neutrinos are produced by exploding stars.
   The second family of particles can be found today only in atom
smashers and cosmic rays from space. The particles are the strange
and charmed quarks, and two leptons named muons and muon neutrinos.
   Particles in the third family _ first discovered in the
mid-1970s _ are the bottom quark, the yet-undetected top quark, the
tau lepton and the tau neutrino.
   They can be created today only in atom smashers but, like the
other families of particles, existed naturally in the first few
seconds after the ``big bang'' that scientists believe created the
universe roughly 15 billion years ago.
   If there were more than three families of particles, experiments
in Stanford's particle smasher should have produced evidence of
more than the three known types of neutrinos and possibly evidence
for other quarks and leptons, but no such evidence was found,
Riordan said.
   The machine, shaped like a giant tennis racket, includes a
2-mile-long linear accelerator that speeds up electrons _ the
particles that create television pictures _ and their antimatter
counterparts, called positrons.
   In the 1-mile-long part of the machine that looks like the head
of the tennis racket, the particles are smashed together,
annihilating each other in a way that comes close to re-creating
the incredible temperatures and pressures that existed during the
big bang.
   The collisions produce Z particles, which are so heavy they
existed naturally only for moments after the big bang. The Zs
produced in Stanford's machine then decay into lighter particles
such as quarks and leptons, which are studied with an 1,800-ton
detection device.
   The atom smasher has produced nearly 500 Z particles since it
made its first one last April, without yielding signs that more
than three families exist.
   Cosmologists _ scientists who study the universe _ predicted in
1977 there should be only three or four families of fundamental
particles.
   That was based on the amount of helium gas produced by the big
bang and observed in the universe, which contains about 74 percent
hydrogen, 24 percent helium and only 2 percent other elements,
Schramm said.
   ``The big bang in some sense was a big hydrogen bomb turning
hydrogen to helium, and the amount of helium made in that big bang
depends on the number of families,'' Schramm said.
   He said he was very pleased with Stanford's findings because
``it's the first time an accelerator experiment has confirmed a
theoretical prediction made from cosmology.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
