<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-12 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 18 People Killed in Fighting Between Extremists, Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals and troops fought
in southern Sri Lanka and at least 18 people were killed, the
government said Thursday.
   Meanwhile, President Ranasinghe Premadasa convened a conference
of Sri Lanka's political parties in the hopes of finding a
negotiated means to end the ethnic violence that has wracked this
island nation for six years.
   The killings were reported over the past 24 hours, during which
the radicals burned at least 39 government buildings, the
government said in a statement.
   It said the victims included nine civilians, two policemen and a
soldier in the Sinhalese-dominated south. Six unidentified burned
bodies also were found in the region, said the statement, which
gave no further details.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne told reporters that more
Indian peacekeeping troops will leave Ampara district on Monday.
Ampara is about 125 miles east of Colombo. India has withdrawn
about 3,300 soldiers this year and promised to pull out the
remaining 39,000 troops by Dec. 31.
   ``Details of the exact numbers leaving cannot be revealed. ...
But the whole withdrawal process ... will keep to the Dec. 31
deadline,'' Wijeratne said.
   The government has worked out a plan to replace the withdrawing
Indian soldiers with Sri Lankan troops, said Wijeratne, also the
deputy defense minister.
   Sri Lankan soldiers have been confined to barracks in the
northeast under terms of a 1987 accord that allowed Indian troops
to police the region.
   The accord aimed to end the ethnic Tamil insurgency for a
separate homeland by giving them limited autonomy. It also allowed
Indian soldiers to be deployed in the northeast to supervise an
arms surrender by Tamil guerrillas and to maintain law.
   The accord sparked a violent backlash by Sinhalese in the south
that was led by the People's Liberation Front, an anti-government
Sinhalese guerrilla group.
   The government says more than 5,000 people have been killed in
two years of fighting between the People's Liberation Front and
government forces.
   The front said the 1987 peace plan gave too many concessions to
the minority Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. It also said the presence of Indian troops
compromised the country's independence.
   Asked about the continued violence in the south, Wijeratne said
the ``backbone of the (front) has not been broken yet, but we will
begin operations against them in a day or two.''
   In yet another attempt to end the fighting, Premadasa hosted an
inter-party conference Thursday that was attended by 90 delegates
from 22 political parties. Premadasa said he would accept until the
end of the month suggestions on how to end the violence.
   The People's Liberation Front had not accepted an invitation to
participate in the conference, but delegates, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said Premadasa's latest offer was aimed at them.
   Tamil militias, including the largest Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, are attending the conference.
   At least 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
died in the 6-year-old Tamil separatist war, which grew out of
complaints of discrimination in jobs and education by the majority
Sinhalese.
   Sinhalese who are mostly Buddhists make up 75 percent of the
population and control the government and the military. Tamils are
mostly Hindus.
</TEXT>
