<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     10-12 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Grain Harvest Higher Than Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's 1989 grain harvest is
turning out larger than previously forecast, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   Production is now estimated at 205 million metric tons, up 5
million tons from the previous forecast. Officials said the upward
revision was due mostly to preliminary yield results published by
Moscow.
   The latest estimate includes 89 million tons of wheat, an
increase of 2 million tons, and 103 million tons of coarse grains
such as corn and sorghum, up 3 million tons. The balance is made up
of pulses, rice, buckwheat and ``miscellaneous'' grains.
   Officials also said the USDA's estimate of Soviet grain imports
have been reduced 2 million tons to 35 million tons for the trading
year that runs through June 30, 1990.
   In a related report, the USDA announced an additional sale to
the Soviet Union of 100,000 tons of U.S. corn for delivery in
1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement.
   Orders announced the last two weeks now total 3.8 million tons
of corn and 325,000 tons of soybean meal. In addition, 143,700 tons
of soybeans that had been sold for delivery earlier were carried
over into the seventh year of the agreement between the two
countries, which began Oct. 1.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans.
</TEXT>
