<FIRST>r w AM-Vuono     10-12 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vuono,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Chief of Staff: No Surprise Manpower Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Chief of Staff Gen. Carl Vuono said
Thursday that he would prefer to have long-term cuts in armed
forces personnel worked out through the arms control process than
have them ``dropped on us right now'' during budget negotiations on
Capitol Hill.
   Vuono, in a meeting with reporters, noted that Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney has already proposed a cut of 8,000 Army personnel in
the 1990 fiscal year.
   Out of the more than 2.1 million people on active military duty,
a cut of 16,800 positions was proposed by Cheney in May.
   Some 8,000 were to come from the Army, 5,600 from the Navy and
3,200 from the Air Force, while the Marine Corps was untouched.
   But in current House-Senate negotiations on the Pentagon budget,
lawmakers have eyed cuts of up to 40,000 individuals to meet
spending limits in the 1990 fiscal year.
   ``I would hope that we can see our way clear in '90 and '91
without taking any major end strength reductions and enable us to
shape that (Army) figure based on the president's proposal right
now on the arms control table. That gives us a better opportunity
to shape it, rather than piecemeal in '90 and piecemeal in '91,''
Vuono said.
   The Army chief of staff said that if an arms control proposal is
signed in 1992 or beyond, ``we'll have to take some additional
number out of the Army. We can plan for that. We are planning for
that.''
   Vuono said he didn't care for the idea of ``a cut dropped on us
right now in addition'' to the cuts currently proposed on Capitol
Hill.
</TEXT>
