<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Syria     10-12 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Syria,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Appeals For Calm Over Syrian Defection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Thursday
appealed for calm and for trust in the military, despite failure to
detect a Syrian warplane flown by a defector into northern Israel.
   The seven minutes the Syrian air force pilot spent over Israel
before landing the MiG-23 supersonic fighter-bomber caused a public
uproar over possible flaws along one of Israel's most sophisticated
defense lines.
   In Damascus, the Syrian capital, International Red Cross
official Ulrich Lenhartz said the Geneva-based organization was
trying to arrange the return of pilot and plane at Syria's request.
   Israeli radio stations and most newspapers said the air force
failed to scramble inteceptors before the plane landed near Haifa,
a city of 250,000.
   ``There is a question that people justly ask: how and why it
happened that a plane came in without being detected immediately,''
Shamir told high school students in Raanana. ``There is an
investigation regarding this. ... I think that people of Israel,
with their experience of many years, can certainly trust and give
full confidence to its air force.
   ``Let's not turn an event that should be joyful into a cause for
arguments and worries. It's good for Israel that such an important,
significant, valuable plane ... abandoned Syria and came to us.''
   Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron appointed a team to
investigate, the army command said in a communique. It will look
into control, anti-aircraft and command operations and report by
Monday.
   Whether the investigators had power to recommend action against
individuals who may have failed in their duties was not clear.
   Israel's eight leading dailies asked on their front pages how
the pilot, Maj. Adel Basem, 34, managed to land without
interference on a crop-dusters' airstrip at Megiddo, 57 miles north
of Jerusalem, and spend 20 minutes on the ground before security
officials arrived.
   Davar newspaper said the plane crossed the Golan Heights at an
altitude of 100 feet at about 780 mph.
   Syria is Israel's implacable foe. Israel annexed the Golan
Heights after capturing them from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Yaakov Abudi, an airfield official who was the first to meet
Basem, quoted the pilot as saying one major reason he defected was
being beaten after asking for better housing.
   A Syrian official in Damascus said the pilot did not defect but
had to make an emergency landing. Israeli officials denied the
plane had technical problems.
   An Israeli army spokesman said a Red Cross request to meet Basem
would be examined but added the Red Cross ``routinely visits
detainees in Israel, and he is not a detainee.''
   Officials refused to say where or under what conditions Basem
was staying.
</TEXT>
