<FIRST>r a AM-NursingHomeFire     10-12 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Fire,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Reopens Week after Fatal Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursing home ravaged by a fire last week
that killed 12 residents reopened Thursday after passing state and
local inspections.
   State Health Commissioner Dr. C.M.G. Buttery said the Hillhaven
Rehabilitation and Convalescent Center was authorized to let
residents back on the third and fourth floors.
   The second floor, where the fire started, is being renovated and
was not approved for patient care. The first floor houses services
such as the dining room and therapy rooms.
   Lori Peacock, regional marketing director for Hillhaven Corp.,
said the first resident returned Thursday afternoon.
   ``We've only heard about a half a dozen residents who are not
planning to return,'' she said.
   The city fire marshal said earlier this week that a blown fuse
prevented an alarm from being relayed to authorities when the blaze
broke out shortly after 10 p.m. on Oct. 5.
   The alarm system also releases magnets holding fire doors open.
Had the system functioned properly and closed the doors, smoke
would not have filled part of the second floor, where most of the
deaths occurred, officials said.
   Fire inspectors cited the nursing home for failing to ensure the
alarm system worked, and for failing to notify the fire department
when the alarms were shut down for three days in September to
fumigate the building.
   Assistant City Fire Marshal William D. Beisch said Thursday that
the nursing home had repaired the alarm system and that fire
officials were satisfied that the home complied with the city fire
code. The city building inspector also gave the home permission to
resume operations.
   Authorities said the fire started when a patient who was
smoking, in violation of regulations, accidentally tossed a lighted
match onto a bed. The fire was contained to one room on the second
floor, but smoke poured through the building.
   Nine people were killed in the fire and three other residents
died Monday and Tuesday in hospitals. Those three were among 98
injured in the fire. The home had 161 residents.
   In another development, a resident of the nursing home filed a
$3 million lawsuit against the home's owner Wednesday in Norfolk
Circuit Court.
   Edna D. Carroll, 88, who is in stable condition at a hospital,
alleges that her injuries resulted from negligence and breach of
duty by the nursing home.
   Pete Moore, the Hillhaven Corp.'s director of operations,
declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
