<HEAD>Bush to Nominate Sweet to Juvenile Justice Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate Robert W. Sweet
Jr., who stirred controversy in the Reagan administration as acting
head of an Education Department branch, as administrator of the
Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention, the White
House announced Thursday.
   Sweet clashed with then-Secretary of Educaton T.H. Bell during
Sweet's tenure as deputy director and acting director of the
National Institute of Education in 1982-83.
   Sweet was aligned with conservatives who wanted the Education
Department abolished, as former President Reagan had promised in
his 1980 campaign. Bell opposed its abolition.
   Sweet, 52, subsequently served as a Reagan White House aide and
deputy executive secretary of the Domestic Policy Council until
this year, when he became an education analyst for the Senate
Republican Policy Committee.
   He would succeed Verne L. Speirs at the juvenile justice post.
   The announcement was made by the traveling White House as Bush
campaigned for Republican candidates Thursday in Mississippi and
New York.
