<FIRST>u i AM-Walesa     10-12 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa: Can Solidarity Save Poland Again?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa said Thursday that Solidarity
saved Poland from civil war, but he wonders whether the independent
trade union movement can now lead the country out of economic chaos.
   The Solidarity leader predicted the worst of the process of
rescuing the economy, which is beset by inflation, product
shortages and low industrial productivity, could be over in a year,
but he said the government will have to do a better job of
explaining its policies to a restless populace.
   Walesa also said that if the first non-communist government in
the East bloc, led by Solidarity journalist Tadeusz Mazowiecki as
prime minister, fails, ``We will have the moral right to accuse the
world of not helping us.''
   The Bush administration is supporting a $119 million, three-year
package of economic aid and $100 million in food aid to Poland.
Congressional critics are calling for more.
   
   Walesa made the comments at his weekly news conference at
Solidarity headquarters in Gdansk, a forum he has used to make a
series of dramatically worded commentaries on worsening conditions
in Poland.
   ``I claim that it was Solidarity that saved this country from a
civil war. Is it capable of saving it now? That's a question I'm
asking myself,'' he said.
   ``I'd like to emphasize that we avoided civil war and there is a
chance for rescue in the nearest future. If society understands
this maneuver and joins in, it will all take not more than a year.''
   Solidarity, banned after martial law was declared in December
1981, was re-legalized this year after a wave of strikes in August
1988 brought a series of talks and sweeping reforms in April. The
Solidarity-led government came to power in August after free
elections in June.
   The new government proposes a rapid shift to a market-oriented
economy but acknowledges the situation _ inflation is 600 percent
annually _ will likely worsen before it gets better.
   Walesa said the new government is not explaining its changing
policies well enough.
   ``When I don't understand something, it means that at least 60
percent of the society doesn't understand it,'' the union leader
said.
   Walesa also said local government elections, expected to
challenge the last bastion of communist control, should not be held
too soon.
   ``It will only divide the nation, which will concentrate on
electoral struggle and not on the reforms that must unite us,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
