<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summer-Like Weather As Far North As Central Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front chilled the north-central section of the nation
Thursday, but a broad area had summer-like temperatures. There was
relatively little rain.
   Morning temperatures in the northern Plains and upper
Mississippi Valley were only in the 30s and 40s Thursday, about 10
degrees cooler than the day before. Temperatures dropped into the
freezing range around the northern Rockies.
   Thursday's low in the Lower 48 states was 14 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Strong wind accompanied the cold front, with gusts to 50 mph,
the National Weather Service said.
   But temperatures rose into the 80s from the central Plains to
the Southeast and parts of the Southwest, with some readings in the
90s.
   In Florida and the Southwest, morning lows early Thursday only
went down into the 60s and 70s.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed over the northeastern Gulf
of Mexico during the afternoon, with a few showers over central
Florida.
   Elsewhere, a few showers moved over the Pacific Northwest and
the lower Great Lakes region.
   Dense morning fog was reported in central Georgia, southern
Louisiana and the coastal region of Texas during the morning, as
well as in the Los Angeles basin.
