<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Rights     10-12 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Rights,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Official Estimates 77 Dead After Failed Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian human rights official
said Thursday that 77 people were killed and 200 arrested following
last week's coup attempt against Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Raul Escoffery, executive director of the Panamanian Human
Rights Committee, said the casualty figure was based on sketchy
evidence but challenged the Panamanian Defense Forces to disprove
it.
   ``If it's not true, we will say it publicly,'' Escoffery said.
``But until the government cooperates with us, we presume our
information to be true.''
   Robert Troncoso, the rights committee's vice president, said he
believed the information the committee has is too sketchy to give
any estimates.
   The day after the Oct. 3 coup attempt, the Defense Forces issued
a communique that said 10 rebels were killed and 37 detained in the
uprising.
   Troncoso and Escoffery said the rights group had received dozens
of telephone calls, most of them anonymous, from people who said a
relative, friend or neighbor in the military had not been seen
since the uprising.
   ``We presume there are many more than this,'' Troncoso said. But
he said repeatedly that the evidence was too sketchy to be precise.
   The committee wrote to Noriega, head of Panama's Defense Forces
and therefore leader of the country, three days after the failed
coup asking permission to visit imprisoned mutineers.
   ``We are still awaiting a reply,'' Troncoso said.
   The rights officials and family members contacted by The
Associated Press said they did not know where prisoners were being
held.
   President Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela has accused the
Defense Forces of carrying out summary executions.
   Defense Forces spokesmen have denied reports an enraged Noriega
personally shot the coup leader minutes after the uprising was
quashed. That was one question foreign journalists permitted to
interview Noriega were forbidden to ask.
</TEXT>
