<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     10-12 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Rail Woes Ease, But Two Die in Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports Thursday from the Soviet Caucasus region
said Armenia's railroad woes were easing but political tension rose
anew in Georgia.
   The Azerbaijani rail blockade that left Armenia critically short
of basic supplies and Georgia hurting for fuel was all over, the
Azerbaijani news agency Azerinform said Thursday.
   ``Freight traffic from Azerbaijan to Armenia has been fully
restored,'' it said, but admitted fewer trains than expected
arrived in the two republics.
   The unrelenting conflict in the Caucasus, a jigsaw puzzle of
nationalities set among the mountains between the Black and the
Caspian seas, is proving one of the Kremlin's most intractable
ethnic problems.
   In the Nagorno-Karabakh region, two men were killed this week in
clashes with authorities, the Soviet newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda
said Thursday.
   In Georgia, activists said a mass meeting in the capital,
Tbilisi, drew thousands Wednesday night to support calls for
Georgian independence and against the Soviet draft.
   ``Fifty people have declared a sit-in near the Sports Palace
against the occupying army,'' Tea Daraselyan, a member of a
Georgian independence group, said Thursday in a telephone interview
from Tbilisi.
   She said the meeting Wednesday asked Georgian youths to refuse
to serve in the Soviet army and asked all Georgians to boycott
upcoming elections.
   Nationalist fervor has run high in Georgia since spring, when 19
Georgians died in a clash between pro-independence protesters and
Soviet troops. Ethnic unrest also turned bloody in the Georgian
enclave of Abkhazia this summer.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has been the source of a vicious territorial
dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan for 18 months. The ethnic
Armenian majority wants the region taken from Azerbaijan and
annexed to Armenia. Kremlin officials imposed direct rule there
trying to calm tensions.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said S. Akonyan of the region's main city
Stepanakert was killed late Tuesday in a clash between soldiers and
local residents. It said R.E. Sadikov, another resident of the
area, was killed Monday.
   It quoted military officials as saying they arrested Sadikov and
took a rifle from him, but he then attacked a soldier and was
killed trying to escape.
   In both cases, soldiers were injured, said the report.
   Akonyan apparently was killed in a clash reported Wednesday by
Interior Ministry spokesman Yuri M. Arshenevsky. Independent
Armenian reports identified the victim as 38-year-old Spartak
Hacobian.
   Arshenevsky said a crowd attacked a convoy of firefighters with
stones and firearms, and they were forced to defend themselves.
   He reported eight people hurt, two critically.
   Rail shipments through Azerbaijan to Nagorno-Karabakh and
Armenia were cut off late this summer. The blockade also affected
Georgia.
   The Azerbaijan People's Front political movement, which
organized a general strike that included the rail tieup, decided
this week to end the blockade.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said freight began arriving in
Nagorno-Karabakh, but not food or fuel shipments, the two most
needed items.
   In Armenia, the blockade halted much reconstruction work in
areas devastated by December's earthquake, which left 25,000 dead.
</TEXT>
