<FIRST>u w AM-Cheney 410   10-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney, 410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Lauds Star Wars Advances; Warns of Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said Thursday
that he's encouraged by advances in the ``Brilliant Pebbles''
component of Star Wars, but that he would recommend President Bush
veto the Pentagon budget bill unless Congress improves funding for
the program.
   Cheney, locked in negotiations with Congress in an attempt to
stave off cuts in the program's billion-dollar budget, acknowledged
he's got a tough battle ahead.
   ``We've got to convince people that it's necessary,'' Cheney
said of the Strategic Defense Initiative in a speech to the
National Security Industrial Association.
   House and Senate conferees hammering out the Pentagon's budget
for the 1990 fiscal year that began Oct. 1 are at loggerheads over
the program.
   The Senate approved $4.5 billion for Star Wars in its
authorization bill last month, while the House adopted a funding
level of $3.1 billion. President Bush had requested $4.9 billion.
   If the House recommendation prevails, Cheney said he would be
forced to eliminate some technology options, cancel contracts and
scale back research.
   ``Should the Congress produce legislation with inadequate
funding levels for SDI, I will recommend to the president that he
veto the bill,'' he said.
   Cheney, holding up a camera that would be used in the Brilliant
Pebbles program, lauded scientists for developing a ``lighter,
smaller and cheaper'' system he said would save ``enormous sums of
money.''
   ``I'm very encouraged,'' Cheney said. ``We are using mostly
off-the-shelf technology. No scientific breakthroughs have been
necessary to create Brilliant Pebbles. We are basically using what
we have.
   ``We haven't yet settled on a final design ... but the work is
going well, and, most important, we see no major scientific
roadblocks to the program.''
   Brilliant Pebbles refers to the swarm of thousands of small
computerized rockets that would be put in space to locate, track
and smash enemy missiles by bumping into them rather than through
explosive force.
   It is only one possible component of Star Wars, which has gained
greater opposition as budget cuts soak up scarce defense funds.
Some critics contend Star Wars experiments could derail U.S.-Soviet
advances in arms control.
   Cheney spoke positively about other aspects of Star Wars,
including research in laser-beam technology and ground-based
interceptor systems. He repeated assertions that the Soviet Union's
strategic defenses have improved, not weakened, under Mikhail
Gorabachev.
</TEXT>
