<FIRST>r i AM-Ireland-IRA     10-12 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ireland-IRA,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ireland Says It Won't Try Ex-Priest Britain Wants as IRA Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republic will not prosecute an
Irish former priest accused by Britain of plotting IRA violence, a
government legal officer said Thursday.
   Eamonn Barnes, director of public prosecutions, said material
submitted by Britain to bring Patrick Ryan to trial, as well as
Irish police inquiries, were ``not sufficient to justify a
prosecution.''
   Ryan, 59, still wears clerical garb although the Roman Catholic
leader in England, Cardinal Basil Hume, archbishop of Westminster,
has said he is no longer a priest.
   Britain last year failed to secure Ryan's extradition on charges
of murder and bombing conspiracy and explosives possession on the
British mainland between 1975 and 1988. Irish Attorney General John
Murray said press coverage in the case was prejudicial to a fair
trial.
   Murray indicated Ryan might be tried in Dublin on the explosives
charges but Barnes decided against it.
   In London, Barnes' decision was described as a ``most
disappointing outcome'' in a statement by Allan Green, British
director of public prosecutions.
   Delegates to Britain's governing Conservative Party annual
conference in Blackpool said the decision would strain Anglo-Irish
relations. Ivor Stanbrook, a lawyer and Conservative Party
legislator, said, ``Clearly, there was enough evidence to prosecute
Ryan. The decision was made on political grounds.''
   Peter Brook, the government's Northern Ireland secretary,
commented: ``I think we necessarily have to consider it as a
disappointing decision but it is a decision the Irish government
took on the papers before them.''
   A long history exists of British failure to extradite suspected
members of the outlawed Irish Republican Army from the republic.
   The guerrillas, fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland
and unite the partitioned island, are often regarded as fighters
for a political cause.
   Belgium returned Ryan to the Irish Republic early in 1988 after
refusing a British request for his extradition.
   Ryan denies British allegations that in addition to being an IRA
activist he collected money for the IRA in the United States and
Europe.
</TEXT>
