<FIRST>u a AM-Academy-Blacks     10-12 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Academy-Blacks,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coach: Academies Canceling Football Games Because of Black Player</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private school official says other
academies are refusing to play scheduled football games against his
team because he recently added a black player.
   ``They haven't actually said that. I don't know that that's the
reason they're not playing, but all indications point that way,''
Ray Wooten, headmaster and head football coach at Heritage Academy,
said Thursday.
   Scott Fuller, a 15-year-old black student, transferred to
Heritage from nearby West Point High School four weeks ago.
   Wayne Pinkerton, headmaster at Sharkey-Issaquena Academy, said
Wednesday his school would forfeit Friday night's game against
Heritage because his Mississippi Private School Association Class A
team was plagued with injuries and needed time for players to heal.
   Frank Drake said Wednesday that East Holmes Academy, where is
headmaster, would likely forfeit an Oct. 20 game at Heritage, but
added: ``If we don't (play), it won't be because of that black.''
   Drake refused to elaborate and neither he nor Pinkerton returned
telephone calls Thursday from The Associated Press.
   Wooten said Sharkey-Issaquena officials had told him they wanted
their players fit for the remainder of the school's games against
Class 1A schools in the MPSA. The association divides schools into
classes of 1A, 2A and 3A with 3A being the largest schools.
Heritage, with 540 students, is a 2A school.
   Wooten said Sharkey-Issaquena ``has as many people on the roster
as we do.
   ``East Holmes is in our conference and they really haven't given
me any particular reason. We only have a 2-5 record, so it's not
like we're awesome and beating everybody to death because we're
not.''
   Wooten said his athletes were disappointed.
   ``Other than that they're taking it very well. They know what
the problem is,'' he said.
   Fuller said he was ``just a kid who likes to play sports. I'm
not trying to change the world.''
   The sophomore is the first black football player in the MPSA
North Central AA Conference.
   He said he wasn't bothered by the attitudes of the other schools.
   ``You can't be upset with them. It's like their religion. If
that's what they believe, there's nothing I can do,'' he said.
   Scott has two younger brothers who attend West Point public
schools. His father, Julius Fuller, said he wanted his eldest son
in a school with a strong academic program that could provide more
individual attention, knowing his son would be the only black team
member.
   ``I think our students see him as another kid in school,''
Wooten said. ``He's mature and likable. His teammates like him.''
   Fuller, at 5 feet 5 and 130 pounds, returns kicks and is a
substitute at tailback and defensive back. He isn't a starter.
   Wooten said he expected to hear a final decision from East
Holmes by the end of the week.
   Lloyd Lindsey, president of the Academy Activities Commission,
the governing body of the MPSA, and headmaster at Wilkinson County
Christian School in Gloster, said there were about 80 to 85 blacks
enrolled in the MPSA.
   He said several academies have or have had black athletes. The
association has 99 member schools.
   MPSA director Don Souder did not return telephone calls to his
office in Jackson.
</TEXT>
