<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     10-12 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Blames Britain For Immigrant Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Thursday its refusal to let Hong Kong
return illegal Chinese immigrants is Britain's fault, and refused
to say when it would start accepting them again.
   China suspended the repatriations Sunday, apparently in
retaliation for Hong Kong's decision to let Yang Yang, a Chinese
swimmer who sought asylum after participating in pro-democracy
demonstrations in Hong Kong, to leave for the United States.
   Cooperation on returning mainland Chinese who flee to the
British colony ``was damaged by the British-Hong Kong government
unilaterally,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing said at a
weekly briefing.
   ``We hope Britain and the British-Hong Kong government will
express their sincerity in cooperation so that the agreements'' on
border issues can be implemented, he said.
   Asked by a Hong Kong reporter about reports that China may stop
supplying water and non-staple food to Hong Kong, Li said Beijing
``has always been very concerned about the compatriots in Hong Kong
and Macao.'' He described such reports as ``irresponsible and with
ulterior motives.''
   China has not directly linked the swimmer to the immigrant
matter, but the official news agency Xinhua said the Yang case
``will for sure adversely affect the normal contacts between the
residents of the mainland and Hong Kong.''
   Li said, without elaborating: ``Recently, the British government
did something that was harmful to the prosperity and stability of
Hong Kong.''
   Hong Kong authorities have intercepted nearly 50 illegal
immigrants a day since Sunday.
   The crushing of pro-democracy dissent in China this spring has
seriously damaged the confidence of Hong Kong's 5.5 million
residents in the 1984 British-Chinese agreement to return the
colony to China rule in 1997.
   Li denied knowledge of a reported slowdown of repatriation of
Chinese illegals in the Portuguese colony of Macao, near Hong Kong.
He said cooperation between China and Portugal over Macao, which is
to revert to China in 1999, was going ``very well.''
</TEXT>
