<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0649 10-12 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technicians Race to Replace Flawed Shuttle Computer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `The astronauts ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with NASA saying weather would have prevented Thursday launch, environmentalists
filing notice of appeal; picks up 10th graf: `The West ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technicians worked six at a time in
a cramped engine compartment Thursday to remove a flawed computer
in time to meet a Tuesday target for launching the shuttle Atlantis
and its Galileo space probe.
   The workers had to stand on platforms to unhook the computer so
it can be replaced Friday with a spare that will be tested for
about 16 hours.
   ``The odds are still 50-50 that we'll be able to make a Tuesday
launch,'' said NASA spokesman Karl Kristofferson. Space agency
officials said they would decide Saturday whether to delay liftoff
until Wednesday.
   Liftoff on Tuesday is scheduled for 12:57 p.m., the start of a
24-minute period in which the planet Jupiter will be in the proper
position to nearly cross paths with the Galileo spacecraft in 1995.
Wednesday has a 27-minute launch window, and Nov. 21 is the last
day Jupiter will be in the proper position until mid-1991.
   After launch, Atlantis' crew of five astronauts is to release
the 6,700-pound probe for the six-year journey to Jupiter.
   The launch originally was scheduled for Thursday, but NASA
postponed the flight Tuesday after the engine computer, called a
master controller, gave a false fuel pump pressure reading.
   Similar computers are located in the shuttle's other two main
engines. They each weigh 230 pounds, cost $6 million and control
all functions of their individual powerplant during the climb into
orbit.
   Had NASA tried to launch Atlantis Thursday as originally
planned, the effort would have been halted by bad weather,
officials said. Clouds and high winds prevailed throughout the day,
with intermittant rain.
   The astronauts were at their main training base in Houston on
Thursday, rehearsing in a shuttle simulator.
   A federal judge rejected a request by environmental groups to
halt the flight for fear the nuclear-powered probe could scatter
plutonium over Florida if the shuttle exploded.
   The groups filed a notice with the judge Thursday that they were
going to appeal his ruling to the U.S. Court of Appeals.
   The West German Green Party, which focuses on environmental
issues, is asking to join in legal actions to delay the launch. It
hopes to gain time to get the issue of the space shuttle's nuclear
cargo before the world court.
   ``Because of the shortness of time, they asked that we represent
them,'' said Lanny Sinkin, a lawyer for the Christic Institute, one
of three U.S. environmental groups that tried to stop the launch.
</TEXT>
