<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Hurricane     10-12 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Hurricane,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Government To Pick Up Greater Share Of Virgin Islands Recovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday ordered the federal
government to pick up a larger share of the recovery costs from
Hurricane Hugo in the Virgin Islands.
   Bush earlier had taken similar action for Puerto Rico and South
Carolina.
   The traveling White House announced the action before Bush's
appearance at a fund-raiser for Republican New York mayoral
candidate Rudolph Giuliani.
   The change that Bush ordered in the federal disaster relief
formula should save the Virgin Islands more than $69.3 million,
according to the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   State and local governments normally must pay 25 percent of the
costs of debris removal, road repair and other public assistance in
disaster areas.
   Bush ordered FEMA to pay a 100 percent share of relief under the
Individual and Family Grant program once the Virgin Islands pays
$500,000.
   FEMA estimated that the disaster will cost $25 million for
grants to individuals and $254 million for aid to local governments.
   Bush acted in response to a request from Gov. Alexander A.
Farrelly.
</TEXT>
