<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0688 10-12 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Respond to Latest Violence by Rejecting Idea of Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to ADD background on traffickers' call for
talks, papers' circulation. Picks up 14th graf `On Sept. ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's two leading daily newspapers
on Thursday denounced the idea of government talks with narcotics
traffickers after assassins working for drug barons killed two
newspaper employees.
   Because of fear on the part of truck drivers and delivery boys,
one of the newspapers, El Espectador, suspended home delivery in
Medellin, where the employees were killed Tuesday, a newspaper
executive told The Associated Press.
   Many kiosks in Medellin were not selling El Espectador, hotel
employees and employees of other newspapers in Medellin said by
telephone. Vendors who were selling it kept it stashed beneath
counters and were slipping issues to customers like contraband,
they said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Medellin, a city of 2 million people in northwestern Colombia,
is the headquarters for the world's biggest cocaine cartel.
   El Espectador said in a lead editorial that drug traffickers'
suggestion of talks ``under their irrevocable threats of
extermination and continuing their injustices if they are not not
heard out would resemble a veritable surrender.''
   The newspaper, whose publisher was murdered by drug traffickers
three years ago, said it is too late to forgive and forget.
   El Tiempo, also in a leading editorial, said El Espectador is
experiencing ``the gravest threat against the freedom of the press
in the entire history of our republic.''
   On Wednesday a letter signed by Pablo Escobar, godfather of the
Medellin cartel, asked for mediation by the press, political and
church leaders and the judicial branch in a ``direct dialogue''
between the government and drug traffickers.
   The letter, addressed to Juan Carlos Pastrana, director of La
Prensa newspaper in Bogota, was read over the Caracol radio network.
   Drug traffickers claimed responsibility for the slayings Tuesday
of the El Espectador workers and threatened the kill the
newspaper's 11 remaining employees in Medellin.
   El Tiempo and El Espectador are fierce competitors in Bogota but
have joined forces in the fight against drug traffickers and
traditionally have supported each other in times of threats to the
free press. El Tiempo has a daily circulation of 350,000 and El
Espectador 285,000.
   Both papers have called for government action against drug
cartels, but El Espectador has been more outspoken, calling the
Colombian congress cowardly for not getting involved in the fight.
   There have been accusations that some congressmen have been
elected with contributions from drug traffickers.
   Escobar was a backup member of the congress from 1982 to 1986.
Each congressman is elected along with a backup member to vote when
the real congressman is not present, which is frequent.
   On Sept. 2, a car bomb exploded alongside the El Espectador
building, seriously damaging the building and forcing the newspaper
to suspend advertising and cut back on the size of the paper.
   The newspaper closed its office in Medellin on Wednesday and
said it will remain closed until the newspaper can figure out what
to do about security.
   The government said Thursday it had captured two more suspected
drug traffickers and was holding them while the United States
decides if it wanted to extradite them.
   The suspects were identified by Colombia's federal
Administrative Scurity Police as Manuel Palma and Leonidas Vargas.
   Palma, according to the U.S. State Department, is wanted in
Miami on charges of participating in a money laundering operation.
   Vargas was described by El Espectador as chief of operations for
the Medellin cartel's vast operation of jungle laboratories in
southern Colombia.
   U.S. authorities have not said if he is wanted in the United
States.
   Colombia has extradited one suspected trafficker to the United
States during the 8-week-old war on traffickers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
