<FIRST>r a AM-NTSB-Burnett 1stLd-Writethru a0680 10-12 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NTSB-Burnett, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Bush Will Nominate Kolstad to Chair NTSB ^Eds: LEADS
with 5 grafs to RECAST, restore dropped firt name of Kolstad, UPDATE with
reax from Kolstad. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Last week ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate acting Chairman
James Kolstad to run the National Transportation Safety Board
rather than Jim Burnett, the candidate chosen by President Reagan,
a newspaper reported Thursday.
   The Atlanta Constitution quoted congressional and administration
sources as saying Burnett, an ardent critic of government and
industry safety practices, will not get the nomination.
   Burnett, whose term on the board expires in December 1990, was
renominated as chairman by Reagan in 1988, but Kolstad became
acting chairman when the Senate failed to act on Burnett's
nomination.
   Burnett had served as chairman of the NTSB since 1982.
   Kolstad, contacted in Washington, said he had heard no word of
an appointment but he was ``hopeful and encouraged'' by the
reports. Both Kolstad and Burnett have said they want the job and
have deplored the delay in appointment of a permanent chairman.
   Last week, Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark., said chances of
Burnett's reappointment were not good because he is opposed by Sen.
Wendell H. Ford, D-Ky., chairman of a Senate aviation subcommittee
that regularly deals with the NTSB.
   Kolstad, former head of corporate communications for Frontier
Airlines, has Ford's backing for the job, the newspaper said.
   John Galipault, president of the non-profit Aviation Safety
Institute, rated Burnett among the board's best chairmen and said
he was worried that the agency could lose some of its independence
without his leadership.
   ``Without an effective leader, the board could lose its
independence and be owned by somebody else _ the airlines or
whoever,'' he said.
   Kolstad has been acting director since August 1988, after
Burnett failed to win senatorial approval for a fourth two-year
term.
   Burnett, who acquired a reputation as a strong, independent
safety advocate, is believed to have angered Ford and the chairman
of the Senate aviation subcommittee, with a speech blasting Ford's
proposal to separate the Federal Aviation Administration from the
Transportation Department.
</TEXT>
