<FIRST>r a AM-NovelSentence     10-12 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Novel Sentence,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers Convicted In Drug Case Ordered To Read Five Books Each</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When two brothers pleaded guilty to drug
charges, the judge didn't throw the book at them _ he just told
them to read 10 books.
   Circuit Judge John E. Rochester ordered Henry McQueen, 31, and
Isaac McQueen, 30, of Montgomery to read five novels each, write
reports on them and keep a weekly diary on what each is doing with
his life and what he's learned from his experience in the judicial
system.
   Henry McQueen was ordered to read ``The Grapes of Wrath'' by
John Steinbeck, ``Lie Down in Darkness'' by William Styron,
``Animal Farm'' by George Orwell, ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' by
Tom Wolfe and ``The Reivers'' by William Faulkner.
   Isaac McQueen was ordered to read ``Lord of the Flies'' by
William Golding, ``Crime and Punishment'' by Feodor Dostoevski,
``The Trial'' by Franz Kafka, ``Confessions of Nat Turner'' by
Styron, and ``East of Eden'' by Steinbeck.
   The McQueens, who pleaded guilty Wednesday to cocaine possession
charges, were given a suspended sentence of one year and a day, in
addition to five years supervised probation, which the judge said
could be revoked if they failed to do their book reports or keep
their diaries.
   He also said the sentences would remain suspended so long as
they hold jobs and obey the law.
   Rochester, a Clay County jurist serving in the Montgomery
circuit as a visiting judge, said he has been imposing book-reading
sentences for about nine months to a year in his rural circuit.
   He said generally he sentences defendants to read books or keep
diaries ``for the educational value. I don't think corrections is
doing enough.''
   The judge startled the courtroom when he imposed the novel
sentence.
   ``As the sentence was being read, I looked around the courtroom
and people's eyes were getting big,'' said David Belser, the
assistant district attorney who handled the case. ``People were
nodding in the affirmative, `That's great.'''
   Given the normal course of criminal justice system proceedings,
he said, the sentence was ``a breath of fresh air.''
   But Elna Reese, defense attorney for Henry McQueen, said
Thursday the judge would be asked to reconsider the sentence. She
said five years probation for first offenders was too harsh.
</TEXT>
