<FIRST>r a AM-RocketdyneEvacuation     10-12 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocketdyne Evacuation,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Fire At Aerospace Company Prompts Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small fire near a 900-gallon acid vat at a
suburban aerospace complex Thursday prompted the evacuation of
about 1,000 workers, officials said.
   There were no significant injuries reported at the Rocketdyne
plant in Canoga Park, but about 40 people who were in the area of
the fire were given emergency showers and six were taken to
hospitals for precautionary checks.
   The aerospace company, a division of Rockwell International
Corp., makes main engines for the space shuttle.
   The fire broke out on wooden grating near a 900-gallon vat of
hydrofluoric acid and was extinguished by company employees at
about 9:30 a.m., said city Fire Department spokesman Greg Acevedo.
   None of the acid spilled, he said.
   The cause of the fire was not immediately known.
   ``We manufacture the space shuttle main engines in this
particular building and there are about 1,000 people in the
building,'' said Rockwell spokesman Pat Coulter. Hydrofluoric acid
is used to clean parts for the reusable main engines, he said.
   Hydrofluoric acid can damage the eyes, respiratory system and
skin, according to a U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
hazardous chemical guide. The chemical is so strong that it is
incompatible with metal, glass, ceramics and concrete.
</TEXT>
