<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Falklands     10-12 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Falklands,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falklands Elect New Legislative Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN LEONARD</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANLEY, Falkland Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-eight percent of voters
dotted about this remote South Atlantic archipelago chose a
legislative council this week, undeterred by lack of roads and
helped by one overworked pilot hopping islands to collect ballots.
   In Stanley, the capital and only town of this British colony of
1,800 people, 82 percent of registered voters cast ballots in a
4-day election that ended with a vote-count Wednesday night.
   The numerous islands cover 4,700 square miles, 300 miles east of
Argentina and 8,000 miles from Britain.
   Because of the almost total absence of roads in the farm areas
of this sheep-raising community, election officials visited sites
outside the capital by plane and Land Rover so farmers could vote.
   The government air service, crippled by recent resignations, had
to rely entirely on veteran pilot Andy Alsopp, who was recruited on
an emergency basis from the Shetland Islands of Scotland.
   Ninety-four percent of the total farm electorate of 553 voted.
   Eighteen candidates stood for the eight council seats _ four to
represent Stanley and four the farming community.
   All the candidates stressed their total opposition to resuming
any contacts with Argentina, let alone any discussions of
Argentina's claim to sovereignty over the Falklands, the issue that
brought Britain and Argentina to war for six weeks in 1982.
   However, a general feeling of support was shown for improved
relations between Britain and Argentina.
   The first substantive talks between the two former combatants
are to take place in Madrid Oct. 17-18.
   Winning candidate Terence Peck, decorated for bravery in
assisting the British forces that drove out the Argentine
occupation, cautioned against forging economic links with Argentina.
   ``We are content to trade with other Latin American countries,
but we want nothing to do with Argentina,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
