<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Columbus     10-12 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Columbus,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftists Protest At Columbus Monument</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftists shouting anti-government slogans
protested at Mexico City's monument to Christopher Columbus on
Thursday, Columbus Day, and tore away wreaths laid by city
officials.
   About 300 protesters began the demonstration at midday at the
statue of Cuauhtemoc, the last of the Aztec emperors, who were
conquered by the Spaniards in the 16th century.
   After dancers in colorful indigenous costumes and feathered
headdress paid tribute to the native chief, the protesters walked
the two blocks to the Columbus statue, where they chanted slogans,
threw flowers at a few dozen police officers and desroyed the
wreaths.
   There were no violent incidents during the protest, which lasted
only a few minutes. Protesters called Columbus a killer and shouted
that the police should stop harassing citizens.
   Some marchers handed out handbills alleging government
repression of peasants.
   ``We call on the public not to let our dignity be trampled,''
the leaflets said.
   Mexico observes Columbus Day as ``Dia de la Raza,'' Day of the
Races, honoring the nation's racial mix. The majority of Mexicans
have indigenous and European blood.
   Last year's celebration resulted in a melee, when leftist
protesters at the Columbus statue threw rocks at police.
