<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0742,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Campaigns for Republican Candidates </HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf: ``Painting a,'' and SUBS 10th graf, Bush also,
with three grafs bgng: ``So take,'' to past-tense Bush appearances and
give further quotes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush beat the drum for Republican
candidates from the Mississippi Gulf Coast to Gracie Mansion
Thursday, ending up by urging New Yorkers to vote for ``America's
greatest crime-fighter'' _ mayoral hopeful Rudolph Giuliani.
   Bush capped a day of campaigning with an effusive speech at a
fund-raising dinner in Manhattan expected to reap upwards of $1
million for Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor. Polls indicate
he is trailing badly in his bid to keep Democrat David Dinkins from
becoming New York's first black mayor.
   Painting a bleak picture of a city beset by ``neighborhood
tensions,'' crumbling bridges, homelessness and a declining school
system, Bush said, ``Rudy's the one to turn around New York City.''
   Earlier, Bush was in Gulfport, Miss., to rally support for
Republican Tom Anderson, fighting uphill for a congressional seat
that has been in GOP hands since 1973.
   While Bush extolled Anderson, a longtime aide to Mississippi
Sen. Trent Lott, as a sorely needed House vote for his war on drugs
and fight against tax increases, the endorsement paled in
comparison to the accolades he showered on Giuliani.
   Bush said New York ``isn't the city it used to be. But Rudy
holds out the hope that it can again become the city it once was.''
   ``Most of us know him as America's greatest crime-fighter,''
Bush said, likening Giuliani to such ``larger than life'' crime
busters as Teddy Roosevelt, Thomas E. Dewey and Elliot Ness.
   ``In the war on drugs, no man in America has a better chance of
succeeding. Let's take back the streets. Let's bring back New
York,'' said Bush.
   ``Rudy may be an underdog, but New York loves an underdog,''
said the president.
   ``So take your polls and do what you want with them,'' Bush said.
   Bush quipped that the candidate ``knows that when he becomes
mayor he'll have the second toughest job in America. The first, of
course, is managing the New York Yankees.''
   Bush also attended a reception for Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y.,
who is running for borough president of Staten Island, and shook
hands for the cameras with Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J., who is seeking
the governorship of New Jersey, at the Newark Airport.
   Bush went first to Mississippi, with Republican National
Chairman Lee Atwater in tow, to try to help the GOP retain the seat
left vacant by the death of Rep. Larkin Smith in a plane crash in
August.
   In Gulfport, Bush said he hopes the drug summit he will attend
with the presidents of Colombia, Bolivia and Peru ``will bring us
to a new level of international cooperation in this war we must
win'' against narcotics. No time or place for the summit meeting
has been announcecd.
   Anderson, who trailed Democrat State Sen. Gene Taylor in the
Oct. 3 open primary, was not shy in making party comparisons
between himself and Taylor.
   ``There is a difference between the two candidates,'' said
Anderson. ``The party of Michael Dukakis, Walter Mondale and Ted
Kennedy belongs to Gene Taylor. My party is the party of President
George Bush.''
   Anderson, who was ambassador to Barbados from 1984 to 1986, also
vowed to ``do everything we can to make drugs eradicated from this
country.''
   Bush said that as ambassador, Anderson was a ``point-man in the
drug interdiction effort and he knows what it (takes) to stop the
drug runners from reaching our shores.''
   He said he also needs Anderson's vote in Congress to enact a
crime package and on the environment and to push ``more
accountability'' in education.
   Bush said Anderson ``won't be your average freshman in Congress
because he's already ahead of his class.,
   Bush's campaign appearances followed criticism from some fellow
Republicans for failing to campaign personally for Republican Bob
Lanier, who narrowly lost a bid for the Fort Worth, Texas, seat of
former House Speaker Jim Wright last month.
   Bush also saluted Sheila Smith, widow of the freshman
congressman killed in an August plane crash, who was also at the
Gulfport rally.
</TEXT>
