<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     10-12 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Demonstration in Paraguay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and firemen used electric prods
and water cannon Thursday to disperse about 500 people preparing to
march on congress to demand land for landless peasants.
   The marchers, organized by peasant organizations and labor
unions, gathered in a downtown plaza in preparation for the
10-block march. Witnesses said hundreds of police and firemen
blocked streets out of the plaza and used force when marchers tried
to break through police lines.
   ``We are complying with ministerial orders,'' Gen. Francisco
Sanchez, chief of Asuncion police, told reporters at the scene.
``There is a regulation that prohibits demonstrations in the city's
downtown area.''
   An Interior Ministry decree issued in April bans all large
gatherings downtown on grounds they hinder traffic.
   After initial police efforts to contain the marchers, officers
and march organizers agreed 30 marchers could walk to congress to
present a petition. Many more people tried to join the procession,
however, and this time police responded with clubs and blasts from
water cannon to disperse them.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez ousted former dictator Alfredo Stroessner
in a Feb. 3 coup and was installed as president after winning May 1
elections.
   Peasant organizations want his government to distribute free
land to thousands of poor farmers in the interior of the country.
