<FIRST>u w AM-RockHall 1stLd-Writethru a0735 10-12 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rock Hall, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Says He Won't Change His Mind on Rock 'n' Roll Grant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Kemp comments. ``Rock And Roll'' CQ in 13th
graf bgng: ``The New York,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can't always get what you want when you
ask the government.
   Cleveland, Ohio, wanted $6.9 million to help build a rock 'n'
roll Hall Of Fame. But the Department of Housing and Urban
Development said the museum will have to rock without the federal
bankroll, and HUD Secretary Jack Kemp said Thursday there's no way
he'll change his mind.
   ``My children love rock 'n' roll. I love rock 'n' roll. But I
have no discretion,'' Kemp told The Associated Press.
   ``The rock 'n' roll museum is a worthwhile project for Cleveland
and rock 'n' roll but it couldn't meet the criteria for a UDAG
grant,'' Kemp said. ``There is no possibility of a UDAG grant for
the rock 'n' roll museum.''
   HUD two weeks ago rejected the request for an Urban Development
Action Grant to build an 18-story glass pyramid to display rock 'n'
roll memorabilia.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, a Democrat whose district includes part of
Cleveland, had hoped to persuade Kemp the project was worthy of
discretionary funds.
   She was visibly annoyed Thursday when Kemp brought up the
request during a House Banking Committee discussion of unrelated
HUD grant programs.
   Later in the day Kemp called Oakar to clear the air. ``He
apologised for misunderstanding what I was getting at,'' Oakar said.
   Kemp confirmed that he apologised to Oakar. He said he expressed
his friendship and desire to work with Cleveland on housing
programs. But Kemp stressed that he made no promises and held out
no hope for the music museum.
   ``I have no discretionary money,'' Kemp said. ``I don't want
people to be calling me for discretionary political decisions.
   ``There is nothing that I can do about the rock 'n' roll museum
aside from urging the private sector and the rock 'n' roll
musicians and the music industry to put up some more money,'' he
said.
   Oakar sees the $48 million project as the city's best hope for
putting 600 people to work while turning a decaying warehouse
district into a glistening tourist draw. Hall of Fame officials
have estimated that the museum will attract as many as 700,000
visitors and up to $85 million in revenue each year.
   The New York-based Rock And Roll Foundation has set a Nov. 15
deadline for the city to raise $40 million in construction money.
HUD's denial cast doubt on whether the city would be able to meet
the deadline.
   Cleveland is where late-night disc jockey Alan Freed introduced
a generation of teeny-boppers to the term rock 'n' roll.
   The city has approved the sale of $18 million of tax-exempt
bonds to pay for construction, the state promised to kick in about
$4.4 million, Cuyahoga County committed $5 million and corporations
and other donors pledged $7.4 million.
</TEXT>
