<SECOND>AM-Chile-Campaign, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0723-a0705,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Rallies by Government, Opposition Candidates for President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with huge rally for pro-government
candidate, details. ADDS byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FEDERICO QUILODRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 people jammed the
country's largest soccer stadium Thursday in a raucous show of
support for pro-government presidential candidate Hernan Buchi.
   Earlier in the day, thousands of supporters of opposition
candidate Patricio Aylwin filled a downtown street in a rally
organized by the country's most powerful labor federation.
   Both demonstrations were largely peaceful and no injuries or
arrests were reported. As the end of the opposition rally ended,
some small groups clashed with police but were quickly dispersed
with water cannon.
   The young crowd in the National Stadium cheered, chanted and
waved banners for Buchi, 40, who was finance minister under
right-wing military President Augusto Pinochet for four years
before resigning in April to campaign for the Dec. 14 elections.
   ``We are the future and we are going to win,'' Buchi told the
crowd.
   The event appeared to provide badly needed momentum for Buchi,
the underdog who has trailed Aylwin by as much as 30 points in
opinion polls. An independent, Buchi is backed by the conservative
political groups.
   He reiterated a charge that Aylwin, a Christian Democrat backed
by a coalition of 17 centrist and leftist parties, is allied with
violent Marxist groups and hinted that a labor activist killed in a
hit-and-run accident in southern Chile this week was run down
because he backed Buchi's campaign. Aylwin denies soliciting
Marxist support. Police say they have no evidence of a political
motive in the accident.
   The street rally for Aylwin, about 15 blocks from the city's
center, also drew a youthful crowd. Over loudspeakers an organizer
read a statement from Manuel Bustos, leader of the Workers' United
Central, in which he declared that the organization would
faithfully back Aylwin.
   Bustos and his vice president, Arturo Martinez, were unable to
attend because they are serving 541 days in internal exile in small
towns. They were convicted of violating national security laws by
calling a violence-marred general strike against the right-wing
military government in 1987.
   Lech Walesa, leader of the Solidarity free trade movement in
Poland, plans a Sept. 26-28 visit to Chile to meet with Bustos and
lobby for his freedom.
   Aylwin, a 70-year-old statesman, told the crowd he would fight
for greater social justice. He said the workers' cause suffered
severely during Pinochet's 16 years of military rule.
   Also running is Francisco Errazuriz, a populist businessman who
trails the other two candidates in the opinion polls.
   Pinochet, 73, seized power in a 1973 military coup that toppled
an elected leftist government. In October 1988, voters rejected a
referendum proposal that he remain in power eight more years. He
was obliged to call elections. The new government will take over
next March 11.
</TEXT>
