<FIRST>r a AM-CityHomicides     10-12 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Homicides,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Die Violently In 24-Hour Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baptist minister shot to death in his church
was among 13 people who died violently in New York during a 24-hour
period that ended early Thursday, city police said.
   Crime statistics released later the same day showed the city was
close to equaling or breaking last year's record, when 1,896 people
were slain.
   There were 1,019 homicides committed in the city during the
first seven months of the year. In the first seven months of 1988,
1030 people were slain.
   ``It's not a good sign,'' said Assistant Chief Raymond W. Kelly,
who heads the police Office of Management Analysis and Planning.
``We could still go over last year's number.''
   The body of the Rev. Irving Wilson, 52, was found at 6:30 p.m.
Wednesday, inside the King Emanuel Baptist Church by two members of
his congregation, police said.
   The clergyman, a resident of Freeport, had been shot twice in
the head; six shell casings from a .25-caliber handgun were found
nearby. Investigators speculate that Wilson was killed when he
interrupted a burglary.
   The other 12 people whose lives ended violently Wednesday and
early Thursday included a Manhattan doorman shot near his Brooklyn
home; a man who was shot to death by an off-duty U.S. Customs
undercover agent during an attempted robbery at a subway station;
and a 23-year-old Brooklyn man who was shot for no apparent reason.
