<FIRST>r p AM-VaGovernor     10-12 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Governor,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Candidate Accuses Democrat of Insensitivity to Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican candidate for governor is
airing advertisements on issues of interest to women, including a
commercial portraying his Democratic opponent as insensitive to
rape victims.
   Former state Attorney General J. Marshall Coleman's ad, first
aired Wednesday, says Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder introduced a bill
in 1972 that would have allowed defense lawyers to interrogate rape
victims ages 13 and under about their sex lives.
   Wilder's campaign calls the commercial Coleman's ``most vicious
and untruthful ... to date.''
   The 30-second commercial, produced by nationally prominent
Republican advertising consultant I. Robert Goodman, shows a court
scene in which a supposed rape victim is questioned by a defense
attorney.
   The female announcer says: ``Remembering, after the rape. The
ordeal of questioning by the rapist's lawyer. It was Doug Wilder
who introduced a bill to force rape victims age 13 and under to be
interrogated about their private lives by lawyers for accused
rapists. So, next time Mr. Wilder talks about the rights of women,
ask him about the law he tried to pass.''
   Coleman also released an ad emphasizing his commitment to tax
credits for child care and expanded day care for working parents in
state government.
   Coleman accused Wilder during a televised debate Monday night of
being insensitive to women by trying to spread fear that the
Republican would seek to restrict abortions if he wins the Nov. 7
election.
   Published polls show the majority of voters share Wilder's view
that the state's abortion laws should be left alone following a
U.S. Supreme Court decision freeing the states to enact new
restrictions on abortion.
   Polls on the governor's race show Coleman about even with
Wilder, who is trying to become the nation's first black elected
governor.
   Wilder press secretary Laura F. Dillard said the bill, which
failed, was intended to broaden the age category for statutory rape.
   At the time Wilder introduced the bill in the state Senate,
Virginia law said a defendant could not be convicted of the
statutory rape of a girl between the ages of 14 and 16 if the judge
or jury determined she had consented or was lewd or of bad moral
repute. The bill submitted by Wilder extended the age category to
include girls under age 14.
   Dillard said that defense attorneys, in rape cases involving
minors, had already been free to question victims about their
sexual history.
</TEXT>
