<FIRST>u a AM-ChicagoSchoolReform 2ndLd-Writethru a0815 10-12 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago School Reform, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0815,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council Voting Shifts to High Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 gdrafs to UPDATE with late tally, official reaction;
picks up 6th graf pvs: ``We have ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters turned out by the thousands on Thursday to
elect new high school councils, taking the first step in an
ambitious experiment in grassroots control of the city's ailing
school system, officials said.
   Board of Education officials said they were pleased with the
two-day turnout to elect members to 71 city high school and 469
elementary school councils.
   An early tally of ballots show that 104,000 people voted
Thursday to elect members to the 71 high school councils, said
school board spokesman Bob Saigh.
   ``There are some close races, but there are no major disputes,''
Saigh said late Thursday. ``It's been a terrific success in that
it's been so trouble free.''
   Turnout for the elementary vote was below projections made by
some activists, and officials said less than 5 percent of the
eligible parents had voted in the high school elections.
   School board officials estimate about 300,000 people voted in
both high school and elementary school elections _ twice the vote
turnout in New York City's most recent election.
   ``We have nothing to compare it with,'' said Maxey Bacchus, an
election organizer at the Board of Education offices. ``You know at
one time we thought there wouldn't be contested elections. Every
school had contested elections.
   ``That was the first benchmark, and we are absolutely pleased
that people signed up in the numbers they did to vote and the
numbers they did to run as candidates,'' he said.
   The elections were part of a reform package passed last year by
the Illinois General Assembly that also called for cutting
administrative jobs and shifting money in the $2.26 billion school
budget to target low-income students.
   The 17,256 candidates in the two-day election sought 5,400
unpaid positions on the 540 councils, each of which will include
six parents, two teachers and two community residents without
schoolchildren. School staffs will elect the teacher members. The
11th member of each council will be the principal of the school or
schools the council oversees.
   The councils, scheduled to begin their monthly meetings within
in a week of the elections, will have authority to hire and fire
principals, develop school-improvement plans and spend money.
   Enrique Munoz, who was elected as a community representative to
an elementary school, said one of the first steps of his council
would be to ``build a relationship with the principal and the
teachers, rather than them looking at us as the enemies.''
   A tally of votes cast Wednesday showed that 175,275 people cast
ballots at the system's elementary schools. Officials said 85,102
parents of school students voted in the election, with 64,863
ballots cast by community residents and 25,310 ballots cast by
Chicago Public School staff members.
   Officials said there were a number of reports of irregularities
in Wednesday's balloting, most of them caused by inexperienced
election judges and ballots that had more than 20 candidates at
some schools.
</TEXT>
