<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:MiracleNoMore Adv16   10-12 1038</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Miracle No More, Adv 16,1064</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, Oct. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lights Go Out On The Massachusetts Economic Miracle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Leonard sees the impact of the
state's faltering economy each day at his Union Market Station
restaurant. He sees it in the empty seats and in the regulars who
still show up.
   ``I have clients come in every day and talk about layoffs,''
said Leonard, whose 180-seat eatery offers burgers, salads and
sandwiches for lunch.
   Leonard's restaurant, built around an old railroad car, is a
short ride from Route 128, where the high-tech industry that fueled
a boom economy of the 1980s is running out of steam.
   ``I can tell you business is lousy,'' said Leonard, who can also
see it in his family. His 24-year-old daughter, who studied to be a
teacher, can't find a job and is living at her parents' home in
Arlington.
   ``She hasn't got an inkling of a job anywhere,'' Leonard said.
   That's not surprising, since school systems in Massachusetts may
lay off as many as 5,000 teachers due to budget cuts.
   Layoffs, cutbacks and the politics of penny-pinching were once
alien concepts here. But this is the new Massachusetts _ not the
miracle state Gov. Michael S. Dukakis ballyhooed during his
presidential campaign. It's the state where some towns are turning
off street lights to save money and others are asking kids to pay
to play high school sports.
   This is the Massachusetts where just two years ago the economy
was so strong that Leonard and other merchants had to practically
drag people off the street to work for them. Now, Leonard fields
two to three applications a day.
   State officials say that September's unemployment rate of 4.4
percent was higher than before but still was third lowest among the
11 largest industrial states. And 1988 per capita income was the
third highest in the nation.
   However, the slowdown in the high-tech industry _ the result of
more companies in the field and slower sales and growth _ prompts
regular reports of belt-tightening, such as Wang Laboratories'
recent layoff of 2,200 people.
   And the real estate market, once one of the hottest in the
country, has gone ``mushy,'' said James Howell, a Bank of Boston
economist. ``I would look at this as a flattening out.''
   In the cycle under way, people are spending less, and the state
is reaping less from sales taxes. Budget cuts are hurting,
especially the poor and sick.
   ``There is a mean spirit out there about the poor,'' said Michal
Regunberg, spokeswoman for the state Department of Public Welfare.
``When times get tough, the poor become the easiest target. We are
seeing that all over the state.''
   Karen Rock, who lives in Pelham in the western part of the
state, said she already has trouble feeding two children on a
welfare check of $178 every two weeks. ``I don't have enough as it
is. The last week of every month is a real struggle for me,'' she
said. Rock has epilepsy and her doctor has advised her not to
drive. Her 18-year-old son has bone disease.
   Meanwhile, the Legislature, which agonized over budget deficits
through most of the spring, must still cut or raise $500 million in
a $12.3 billion budget this year, because revenues are falling
short again.
   Taxes have haunted Dukakis since his presidential campaign. He
originally supported taxes to save state programs, but a wave of
anti-tax sentiment left him nothing but budget-cutting, and he's
pledged to eliminate 2,300 jobs.
   Dukakis did manage to get through an 18-month income tax
increase that would shave about $85 off a $20,000 income this year
and $170 next year. But an anti-tax group has started a petition
drive to halt that measure.
   The anti-tax sentiment is so widespread that Dukakis is
considering endorsing a more palatable revenue-raising measure _ a
bill to allow betting on professional football. Normally he
``wouldn't touch this with a 10-foot pole.''
   But cuts in the past year, especially in aid to cities and
towns, have been severe. There is little left.
   In Middlesex Superior Court, officials have asked for volunteers
to help with mounting paperwork. ``We need clerk typists and
stenographers and filing clerks,'' said Edward J. Sullivan, the
clerk magistrate. There are four junior clerk vacancies at the
county's superior courthouses in Cambridge and Lowell.
   ``We can't fill these positions. They're frozen,'' Sullivan
said. ``This place is going to fall apart if we don't get some
funds.''
   Essex, a town of 3,000 north of Boston, has turned off street
lights to make ends meet. The town had already stopped garbage
collection and its turn-of-the-century town hall may have to close
because repairs are impossible as long as residents refuse to
override a statewide 2{ percent property tax limit. The Town Hall
bell no longer is rung for fear it may fall through the steeple.
   Samuel Hoar, the town's chairman of selectmen, describes the
building as ``a DC-10 with a bomb in the luggage compartment.''
   What's left to cut next year? ``Nothing. We may find a few towns
going bankrupt,'' Hoar said.
   The state's economic future is ``a mixed bag,'' said Anthony
Ferrara, commissioner for the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics in
Boston. He pointed out that the state is still in better shape than
many others. Ironically, he said, anger and fear about the state's
economic future may continue to cause damage as people refrain from
spending that could keep the economy moving.
   ``There seems to be a lot of negative psychology out there,''
Ferrara said.
   While the state's economic future is in doubt, there's no
question that a political change is coming soon. Dukakis won't be
running for re-election in 1990, and candidates from both parties
are lining up in the starting box.
   In the last gubernatorial election, Republican candidates won
more jokes than votes. Now, economic trouble has pumped new blood
into a lifeless GOP.
   Leonard, a lifelong Democrat, sees a political conversion in his
future. ``I favor the Democratic Party, but I wouldn't vote for a
Democrat right now if it was my brother,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
