<FIRST>a a PM-YouthSuicide Adv17   10-12 1039</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Youth Suicide, Adv 17,1074</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Tues PMs, Oct. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trooper Works To Prevent Teen Suicides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Davis was particularly disappointed
when the General Assembly adjourned without dealing with youth
suicide.
   The few programs that exist in North Carolina are in mental
health departments, but most young people who kill themselves
aren't ill and those who contemplate suicide are reluctant to call
because of the stigma, Davis said.
   The state Highway Patrol trooper has reason to research the
problem and to know the pain from a young person's suicide. His
daughter, Lee Ann, used his .357-Magnum service revolver to kill
herself in March 1986. She was 15.
   ``On going through our own grief and searching for a way to cope
with our grief I discovered there was very little for suicide
survivors. It was such a dark subject. There's a taboo and stigma
attached to suicide. People feel shameful, guilty and can't talk
about it.''
   Yet the problem of youth suicide is on the rise. As the national
rate of youth suicide increased slowly from 1960 to 1980, in North
Carolina the rate from 5.2 per million people to 12.3 per million.
   Davis, a state trooper for 23 years, decided to do something
about it.
   At his house Clyde in the North Carolina mountains, he had an
extra telephone line installed and started Parents Against Teen
Suicide, a non-profit support group that has 450 paying members and
is 2 years old this month.
   Davis spends most of his off-duty hours working for PATS, gets
up to 40 calls a day from troubled youths and parents and travels
hundreds of miles to speak at churches and schools about youth
suicide.
   ``This thing has grown so rapidly. My wife had to quit her job
to become a full-time secretary'' for PATS, he said.
   ``Last year we were involved with 16 people that had the gun to
their head or the knife in their hands, and we were able to
intervene and stop it.'' Twelve of those were youths.
   A 13-year-old girl with a learning disability wrote that
classmates were making fun of her. The girl's mother found her on
the bathroom floor after an overdose of a pain-killer, and Davis
visited the girl the next day and has provided her with counseling.
   In another case, a deputy sheriff called one night about a young
man who held a bayonet to his own throat. The deputy wanted to know
what to do. After the incident ended, Davis arranged for counseling
for the young man.
   Davis helped develop a suicide intervention class that is being
used mainly in western North Carolina high schools. He has
presented a grant proposal to the state Department of Human
Resources for a suicide crisis center and hotline for western North
Carolina, and hopes the idea will spread statewide.
   The legislation not considered by the General Assembly before it
adjourned in August would establish a Youth Suicide Advisory Board
to coordinate state efforts in youth suicide prevention. The board
also would help educate the public about the problem and provide
training in the schools.
   ``There's a need to help classroom teachers and school personnel
to be aware of the danger signs. Reducing class sizes would help
the teacher to see here's a student that's in serious trouble,''
said state Rep. Coy Privette.
   The measure included $10,000 for pilot projects, but the bill
lost out to a push for improved pay for teachers and state
employees. If it is enacted during the session this spring, the
state will join Texas, California, Pennsylvania, Connecticut and
Florida in having youth suicide prevention acts.
   Davis said the public doesn't realize the magnitude of the
problem.
   Each year between 1980 and 1987 an average of 130 youths _
between the ages of 15 and 24 _ committed suicide in North
Carolina. Nationally, more than 6,000 young people killed
themselves last year _ one every 90 minutes.
   There are warning signs, but most people don't recognize them,
Davis said. ``They become hopeless, helpless, hapless. They try
getting involved in several things to take away their emotional
pain. ... When these things fail then suicide becomes a solution to
the problem.
   ``One of the things that young people do a lot of times is
romanticize death, but they don't realize that it's final.''
   Broken homes and relationships, problems in school, drugs and
the strain of adolescence are some of the factors that lead to
youth suicide, experts say.
   Davis' daughter _ tall, with dark hair and blue eyes _ was an
academically gifted student at Tuscola Senior High School in
Waynesville and was active in basketball and volleyball. ``She was
always smiling,'' Davis said.
   She didn't have a drug problem, but she had a turbulent
relationship with her boyfriend. For more than a year, Lee Ann
masked her suicidal feelings.
   But on a Sunday night in March 1986, Lee Ann walked into her
parents' bedroom, where Davis kept his revolver by the headboard of
his bed. She hid it under her blouse and, as she passed her mother,
she said she was going to iron some school clothes for the next
day. Lee Ann stepped outside, pulled out the gun, put it to her
head and pulled the trigger. She died immediately.
   ``Now you can look back and see other symptoms _ an irregular
pattern in her eating and her sleeping,'' Davis said. ``In her last
few weeks she seemed to become overburdened.''
   Victims of suicide often send out signals that are cries for
help, he said. ``Most suicidal people don't really want to die.
They are torn between life and death.''
   This was among several poems Davis and his wife, Joyce, found
after their daughter's death that revealed her anguish:
   ``I'm an actress on the stage
   Playing the role of a comedian.
   Laughing, singing, acting dumb.
   Now the show is over,
   The room is clearing out.
   The lights go off, yet I act on.
   I can't let them see me hurt.
   I can't show them the real me.
   I'm in pain, but they can't know.
   So I just have to keep acting.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Oct. 17</NOTE>
