<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Fonda Adv15_1stAdd 1stLd-Writethrestroika 10-12
0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Fonda, Adv 15 _ 1st Add, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0778,0923</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``In 1977, Fonda,'' to CORRECT name of production
company, changing to IPC; SUBS 11th graf, ``In the late,'' to change number
of videos from eight to nine.</HEAD>
<TEXT>NEW YORK: ``... about it.''    Oscar Jane:    Politics and all,
Hollywood honored Fonda. In 1969, she earned an Academy Award nomination
for her role as a Depression-era marathon dancer in ``They Shoot Horses,
Don't They?'' Two years later, when she won the best actress Oscar as a
prostitute in ``Klute,'' she gave a surprisingly subdued acceptance speech
and snubbed the traditional Governors' Ball.    ``I have not bought in
to my celebrity,'' she said in the interview. ``I'm not a snob, I don't
just like people who are famous. My friends aren't famous. I don't live
like a Hollywood star.    ``Everybody couldn't believe my father and Katharine
Hepburn didn't know each other _ as if Hollywood is this little community
where everybody knows each other. Very often, father was quite reclusive.''
   She won the actress trophy again in 1978 for ``Coming Home.''    There
were other Oscar nominations for Hollywood's political princess: actress
in ``Julia'' (ting actress in ``On Golden Pond'' (r981).    Capitalist
Jane:    In 1977, Fonda and producer Bruce Gilbert formed IPC, an independent
company that would make ``thought-provoking and commercial'' films. Two
of their projects, ``On Golden Pond'' and ``Nine to Five,'' each grossed
over $100 million.    ``I have an instinct for what's happening,'' Fonda
said. ``I've only had one failure _ `Rollover' was the only film that didn't
work. I don't know, it's timing, timing. `China Syndrome,' then Three Mile
Island. `Nine to Five.' The National Union of Secretaries formed right
after it. `On Golden Pond,' my dad was going to die. `Coming Home,' the
first real film about vets.''    Deltoid Jane:    In the late '70s, the
onetime revolutionary empress became a leotard liberal with her entry into
the fitness market. Today, she has nine videos on the market, and all have
been in the Top 20 selling videocassettes.    It began in 1979 with a
fitness studio in Beverly Hills. Two years later, ``Jane Fonda's Workout
Book'' was in the stores with more than a million copies in hard
cover alone. The video is the biggest seller ever, earning close to $40
million.    Did she worry that her movie career would be forgotten? 
  ``In the very beginning I did, because when I started the workout business
I was not making many movies,'' she said. ``I thought that might overtake
the other. But I realized pretty quickly it wasn't the case. And even if
it did, I am pretty much someone who lives not according to image. I do
what I want.''    Whither Jane?    ``Old Gringo'' was conceived in 1980
when Fonda met Carlos Fuentes, the celebrated Mexican author, and saw herself
for the part of schoolteacher Harriet Winslow, an American spinster whose
life is transformed during the Mexican revolution.    Cary Grant once
said that Ingrid Bergman was the only actress whose name alone could guarantee
a film's financial backing. That's changed over the years, and Fonda was
an actress who helped when she and Oscar-winner Vanessa Redgrave starred
in ``Julia,'' a critical and commercial success.    ``There's certainly
more than one woman now, but it's definitely double-tiered, there's no
question. Forty years ago, it would have been unthinkable,'' Fonda said.
   ```Old Gringo' went through a number of administrations and the first
few just humored me. Sometimes that happens in studios. They want to keep
a star happy.''    Burt Lancaster was supposed to play the role of iconoclastic
author Ambrose Bierce, but couldn't get medical insurance for the strenuous
location work. Peck stepped in.    ``He and my father are the two male
legends I have worked with,'' Fonda said. ``There's a kind of combination
of smoothness of craft, depth of experience, combined with the willingness
to really work hard, probe deep and not take it for granted.    ``You
could expect that at a certain point in someone's life, but not many would
be ready to still do that _ turn themselves inside out. It's very painful;
it's risky. My dad did it in `Golden Pond.' Peck did it here.'' 
  And what's next for the ever-changing Jane? ``Stanley and Iris'' is due
for release later this year. Fonda is also considering an American remake
of the popular Spanish comedy, ``Women on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown.''
   And the Kennedys pop up once again. Fonda has the rights to Neil Sheehan's
Pulitzer Prize-winning book on Vietnam, ``A Bright Shining Lie,'' a recipient
of the Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Book Award.    All that money and eight
years of Ronald Reagan have softened Fonda just a little. She's no subversive,
but don't expect a book called ``Second Thoughts.'' Neo-liberals don't
appeal to her. Causes never run out. Retirement is doubtful: After more
than nine lives in the public eye, she has no interest in landing gently
on her feet.    ``I am in the streets, in theaters, in restaurants, in
grocery stores. I run in the park. I run in streets. I talk to people.
I take buses. I won't have it any other way,'' she said.    ``Could I
give it up some day for life on the farm? Yeah, absolutely. But I wouldn't
retire, I'd probably organize the neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
