<FIRST>r f PM-Europe-TV     10-12 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-TV,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Defends TV Plan Against American Complaints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angered by U.S. complaints, the
European Community says its plan to limit U.S. and other foreign TV
programs is ``perfectly compatible'' with international trade rules.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said Tuesday in Washington
that measure was ``blatantly protectionist'' and vowed to file a
complaint challenging the policy with an international trade agency.
   But a spokesman for the 12-nation trading bloc, who demanded
anonymity, defended the move Wednesday as legal and said the United
States would do better under the new plan than under the current,
fragmented broadcasting system in Europe.
   European officials consider the measure ``perfectly compatible _
I repeat perfectly compatible _ with the international obligations
of the community,'' he said.
   At issue is last week's decision by European foreign ministers
to press their local television stations to reserve ``where
practicable'' a majority of air time for European-made
entertainment programs.
   The measure is part of the community's campaign to lift by the
end of 1992 the many trade barriers preventing the free flow of
money, people, goods and services among the dozen nations.
   The United States strongly opposed the plan and Mrs. Hills
underscored her disapproval in her statement Tuesday in Washington.
   ``The directive is blatantly protectionist and unjustifiable,
and discriminates against U.S. and other non-EC film goods,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Hills promised to file a complaint with the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a 97-nation forum and agreement for
removing trade barriers.
   Reacting to her complaint, the community spokesman said foreign
ministers' measure has a ``non-binding character.'' The foreign
ministers agreed last week their decision would be considered a
political commitment, not a legal obligation.
   Moreover, he said, a majority of the community nations already
have some type of restrictions on broadcast content. Therefore, he
said, there would be advantages to the United States and other
countries from the new plan, even if it were not ``100 percent
liberalization.''
   The spokesman also said TV programs were considered services,
not commercial products, and therefore were not covered by the GATT
rules.
   Even so, he said the community would be willing to hold talks
with the United States about the measure.
   The dispute has revived American concerns about the community's
1992 transformation.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher last week told a U.S. House
of Representatives panel that the United States may have to
reassess its position if the European Community moves toward local
content rules in such areas as TV, computer chips,
telecommunications equipment and cars.
   According to industry figures, the United States has a trade
surplus of about $3 billion from its TV and film exports. Europe is
the leading buyer of such programs with about $700 million in
annual sales.
   The surge in American TV programs in Europe, such as ``Dynasty''
and ``Dallas,'' has prompted worries among some politicians about
their impact on European culture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirlinerProp-Fan     10-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airliner Prop-Fan,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Drops $100 Million Prop-Fan Jet Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. is
discontinuing development of a revolutionary prop-fan jet engine
because customers have shown no interest in the $100 million design.
   Instead of extending research on the innovative exposed
propeller engine, the aircraft builder will focus on a new
generation of fuel-efficient aircraft, the MD-90 series, which it
previewed Tuesday.
   ``After a number of years of research, this is what the
customers are telling us they want,'' said Walter Orlowski,
McDonnell's MD-90 program general manager.
   McDonnell Douglas introduced the experimental prop-fan engine in
February 1988. It resembles a standard jet engine housing fitted
with external blades similar to aircraft propellers, but with 16
curved blades.
   The novelty and designers' claims about increased fuel
efficiency failed to excite customers in the airline industry,
officials said.
   Despite projections that the engine could reduce fuel
consumption by 40 percent, McDonnell Douglas failed to get a single
order for the engine type, company vice president John Wolf said.
   ``Our customers indicated they were not interested in buying
it,'' Wolf said.
   The gamble to develop the prop-fan engine was based on the
belief that the price of jet fuel would increase in the 1980s, but
prices have held steady.
   The MD-90 models, which come in two sizes, are designed to be
more fuel-efficient than the MD-80 models from which the new series
was derived. A 114-seat version is expected to be 13 percent more
fuel-efficient, and a 153-seat version will save 17 percent,
company officials predicted.
   The company declined to say how much it planned to invest in the
new planes, but industry analysts estimate the development cost at
between $300 million and $400 million.
   The MD-90 series will be powered by a V2500 engine produced by
the consortium International Aero Engines. The consortium included
the American manufacturer Pratt &amp; Whitney and the British firm
Rolls-Royce, and West German, Italian and Japanese companies.
   Wolf would not say how many orders the company needs before it
can begin production of MD-90s but it has already begun its pitch
to airlines. McDonnell Douglas hopes to begin making deliveries as
early as the fourth quarter of 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
