<FIRST>r f PM-Phones-Dumping     10-12 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phones-Dumping,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Charges Far East Firms With Dumping Phone Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some small business telephone systems and
subassemblies from Japan and Taiwan are being dumped in the United
States at less than fair value, the Commerce Department said.
   The department ruling Wednesday means the International Trade
Commission must decide within 45 days whether the imports, totaling
more than $1 billion last year, injure or threaten the U.S.
industry.
   If the ITC agrees with Commerce, the department will order its
Customs Bureau to collect duties on the products equal to the
unfair price advantage the foreign products have over similar U.S.
products.
   Commerce said the companies involved in the dumping include
Toshiba Corp. and Matsushita of Japan and Taiwan Nitsuko and Sun
Moon Star of Taiwan.
   The dumping charges were filed last December on behalf of the
U.S. industry by the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Comdial
Corp.
   The department said the Japanese imports in 1988 totaled $775.7
million and those from Taiwan totaled $341.9 million.
</TEXT>
