<DOCNO> AP891012-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-ElectronicsTrade     10-12 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Electronics Trade,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Group Reports Rise in US Trade Deficit in Electronics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit in electronics
increased 5.4 percent to $3.9 billion in the first six months this
year, the American Electronics Association said.
   U.S. electronics exports in the first half of 1989 rose to $29.9
billion from the $27.9 billion sold in the first half of 1988, but
imports also grew from $31.5 billion to $33.8 billion in the same
period, AEA said Wednesday. The electronics trade imbalance in
first-half 1988 was $3.7 billion.
   Topping the imports list again was Japan. The U.S.-Japanese
electronics trade imbalance climbed 2 percent to $9.8 billion from
$9.6 billion in first-half 1988, the AEA said, despite improved
sales of U.S. electronics items to Japan.
   Japan increased its U.S. sales to $13.5 billion in first-half
1989 from $12.5 billion in the first six months of 1988.
   U.S. electronics exports to Japan were $3.5 billion in 1989's
first half, up from $2.9 billion in the first half of 1988, AEA
said.
   ``Although our exports to Japan increased, the overwhelming,
virtually constant size of the electronics trade deficit presents
little reason to be optimistic,'' AEA President J. Richard Iverson
said in a prepared statement. ``We want and expect the same trade
opportunities in other countries that are available here.''
   The overall U.S. merchandise trade deficit fell 10.2 percent
from $60.2 billion to $54.1 billion in the same period.
   The AEA represents some 3,400 electronics and information
technology companies in the United States.
</TEXT>
