<FIRST>r f PM-IntegratedResources Bjt   10-12 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Integrated Resources, Bjt,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitehall Halts Buyout Talks With Integrated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another sign of weakness in the nation's junk
bond market, Whitehall Financial Group has called off negotiations
to buy the core financial services businesses of struggling
Integrated Resources Inc.
   Privately held Whitehall said Wednesday it could not obtain
financing for the planned $310 million transaction, citing
``worsening conditions'' in the junk market and concerns over the
value of the businesses.
   The collapse dealt another blow to tottering Integrated, once a
high-flying real estate concern that is seeking to sell key assets
to pay some of its $1.75 billion in outstanding debt and avoid a
bankruptcy court filing.
   ``We're trying to recapture whatever asset values are in this
company and they're going to the creditors,'' Integrated Chairman
Stephen Weinroth said in an interview. ``We're not exactly trying
to snarf them off for ourselves.''
   Weinroth, who took a leave from the investment firm Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. to run Integrated, put the liquidation value
of the company at about $1.1 billion, depending on the price it
gets for the core businesses.
   New York-based Integrated has not paid any principle or interest
to its bondholders since June, when it said it would have to
default because of worsening troubles stemming from its difficulty
in diversifying out of real estate and into financial services.
   ``If the main firm they were talking to didn't have an ability
to finance, it's got to place into question any other potential
deals they have,'' said Tom Fendrich, a managing director at
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., an investment-rating firm.
   Integrated stock fell 12{ cents Wednesday to close at $1.75 in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading. Integrated was trading
above $15 a share in June shortly before it announced it could not
make interest payments on nearly $1 billion in debt.
   Whitehall, a New York-based partnership, had agreed in August to
buy most of Integrated's core financial business.
   But it announced Tuesday it could not find financing for the
transaction and said Wednesday it suspended negotiations because of
``serious concerns regarding the value of the core companies and
the risks associated with the proposed acquisitions.''
   ``These same concerns and the worsening conditions the debt
financing markets made acceptable acquisition financing unavailable
despite Whitehall's willingness to provide substantial equity
funding,'' Whitehall said in a statement.
   The collapse comes amid growing unease in the nation's junk bond
market, which was sent reeling last month by financial woes at
retailer Campeau Corp. Also Wednesday, Ramada Inc. called off a
restructuring because it felt it couldn't complete a planned $400
million junk bond offering.
   Weinroth said Integrated was continuing negotiations with
another party to try to sell the subsidiaries but did not expect
them to fetch the originally hoped-for $450 milion. The company had
said it hoped to complete a sale by Sunday.
   Whitehall had agreed to buy Integrated Resources Life Insurance
Co. of Des Moines, Iowa; Integrated Resources Equity Corp. of
Englewood, Colo., and New York, its principal investment products
distributor; Integrated Resources Asset Management Corp.; Resources
Trust Co.; and Financial Clearing Services.
   After the spinoff, Integrated's main business would be
management of existing public and private limited partnerships and
real estate investment trusts.
   Whitehall is half-owned by members of the de Gunzburg branch of
the Bronfman family of Canada, heirs to the Seagram Ltd. distilling
fortune, and half-owned by the Moross family of London, which has
extensive financial services interests. Whitehall has holdings in
life insurance and property and casualty brokerage.
   Other Integrated businesses include Capitol Life Insurance Co.
of Denver, its tax-sheltered annuity business, its ordinary life
insurance business and United Resources Insurance Services Inc. of
Santa Ana, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
