<DOCNO> AP891012-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AlleghenyInternational     10-12 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Allegheny International,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Plans Filed To Emerge From Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. on Wednesday
filed two alternate plans for emerging from Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws.
   The first plan is similar to the proposal the Pittsburgh-based
appliance maker filed in August. The exception is that the latest
plan does not provide for a stock sale to raise $140 million in
cash to pay off some creditors.
   Under the revised plan, those creditors would receive bonds
instead of cash.
   Allegheny International said it will offer its second plan as a
backup if the first one is rejected in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   The backup plan calls for the issuance of shares of common and
preferred stock in the reorganized company to pay off most general
creditors. Exceptions would be creditors of Allegheny
International's Sunbeam unit and a secured group of bank lenders,
which will get cash, the company said.
   Allegheny International has a loan commitment of $400 million
from Wells Fargo Bank to make those cash payments and fund
continued operating expenses.
   Robert Sable, an attorney for the unsecured creditors, said his
clients will not support either plan.
   Court hearings on the proposed plans begin next month.
</TEXT>
