<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ramada Bjt   10-12 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ramada, Bjt,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citing Junk Bond Market Woes, Ramada Halts Restructuring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. said it postponed a restructuring
that includes selling its 825 hotels and giving itself a new name
because of the continuing upheaval in the nation's junk bond market.
   The hotel chain on Wednesday canceled a $400 million debt
offering that was a prerequisite for the restructuring and said it
could offer ``no assurance'' the deal would be completed.
   Ramada earlier this year said it would sell its worldwide hotel
business to New World Hotel Holdings Ltd. of Hong Kong for about
$540 million and rename itself Aztar Corp., a company that would
operate its Nevada and New Jersey casinos.
   The deal was conditioned on arranging $400 million in financing
for Aztar. But Ramada said it decided not to proceed because of a
junk bond market tailspin that began when retailer Campeau Corp.
announced financial problems last month.
   Ramada's stock plunged Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange,
losing $2.25 to close at $11.
   Nicholas Meris, first vice president of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in Phoenix, said difficulties in the market ``have
made it hard to create new financing.''
   ``(Ramada) had a plan that they believed was viable at the time,
and it was, but now they are going to have to sit down and come up
with something new,'' he said.
   Also Wednesday, Whitehall Financial Group cited the junk bond
jitters in canceling a planned $310 million purchase of several
units of struggling Integrated Services Inc. In August, Ohio
Mattress Co. withdrew a $475 million junk bond offering after
investors shunned the securities.
   The Ramada deal included issuing $230 million in subordinated
debt and $170 million in first-mortgage notes secured by the
TropWorld Casino and Entertainment Resort in Atlantic City, N.J.
   TropWorld is one of three gaming properties Ramada intends to
continue to operate after restructuring. The others are the
Tropicana Resort and Casino in Las Vegas and the Ramada Express
Hotel Casino in Laughlin, Nev.
   Ramada announced Oct. 3 it would consider issuing warrants for
10 percent of Aztar stock as part of the bond offering to make it
more attractive.
   Ramada said it plans to develop a revised restructuring plan but
said it ``can offer no assurance that a restructuring will be
completed and it cannot specify the timing of the next steps.''
   In a new restructuring, Ramada said it would modify a planned
payment to shareholders of $7 per share and a half-share of stock.
Ramada also plans to seek an extension of a Nov. 30 deadline for
the hotel sale to New World.
   Shareholders and gaming officials in Nevada and New Jersey would
have to approve an amended plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
