<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-12 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Keeps Rising, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar kept rising against the Japanese yen
today despite central bank efforts to stop it, and the Tokyo Stock
Exchange reacted with a selling wave that caused the second largest
one-day drop this year in its key index.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 445.02 points, or 1.26
percent, to 34,795.05. The decline was second this year only to a
489.90-point drop on June 15 to 32,913.09.
   Today marked the index's first closing below 35,000 since Sept.
25.
   Meanwhile, the dollar gained 0.70 yen from Wednesday's
143.90-yen close, ending at 144.60 yen. It opened at 144.25 yen and
ranged between 143.70 yen and 144.60 yen.
   The dollar had climbed 1.67 yen on Wednesday, the day the Bank
of Japan raised the nation's official discount rate by 0.5
percentage point to 3.75 percent. Higher interest rates usually
tend to make a currency more attractive to investors, boosting its
value.
   ``The hike by 0.5 percentage points was too small to have much
power in the market to reverse the dollar's uptrend,'' said a
trader with Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Gaps between Japan's discount rate and those of other
countries with major currencies are still wide, and the dollar
remains a good investment,'' he said.
   Japan's discount rate is the lowest among the Group of Seven
industrial nations. It compares with 6 percent in West Germany and
7 percent in the United States.
   The Bank of Japan also was selling dollars today in an effort to
check the dollar's rise, but the amount was unknown. The central
bank does not comment on its exchange market activities.
   ``Unless the United States eases its credit, the dollar's
bullish trend will continue,'' the trader said, ``although the
United States would not change its policy just for the sake of
stability in currency exchange.''
   On the stock market, ``the Nikkei plunged partly because of the
discount rate hike yesterday,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a stock
analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``What hit the market most, however, was the fact that it didn't
work,'' he said, noting the dollar had continued to rise.
   Nikko Securities dealer Masaya Hashizume said investors were
afraid of another discount rate hike sometime soon, believing the
central bank could not sell dollars endlessly in its efforts to end
the dollar's rise.
   Other dealers said investors sold issues in anticipation of
further price declines amid uncertainties about interest rate
movements. The discount rate, the fee charged for commercial bank
borrowings from the central bank, in turn affects other interest
rates.
   Trading was moderate, with first section trading estimated at
650 million shares, down from Wednesday's 750 million.
   Prices were lower across the board, dealers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
