<HEAD>Dollar Declines, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated against major currencies in
European trading this morning after gaining against the Japanese
yen earlier in the day.
   Gold prices crept higher.
   In Tokyo, the dollar gained 0.70 yen from Wednesday's 143.90-yen
close despite central bank intervention, ending at 144.60 yen. The
dollar had gained 1.67 yen in Tokyo trading on Wednesday, even
though the Bank of Japan raised its discount rate from 3.25 percent
to 3.75 percent.
   Later in London, the dollar eased to 144.43 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.9087 West German marks, down from 1.9185; 1.6725
Swiss francs, down from 1.6785; 6.4680 French francs, down from
6.4925; 2.1594 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1630; 1398.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,403.25; and 1.1735 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1750.
   In London, the British pound gained against the dollar, trading
at $1.5551 this morning compared to $1.5425 late Wednesday.
   The five major gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price
of $362.55 a troy ounce this morning, up from $361.25 an ounce late
Wednesday.
   ``Gold looks a little healthier even though it's still sickly,''
said one dealer in London.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $362.70 bid per troy ounce, up from
$361.50 per ounce late Wednesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose the equivalent of 84 cents an ounce
today, to close at $363.20, compared with Wednesday's $362.36.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.10 bid per troy ounce,
compared with Wednesday's $5.05.
</TEXT>
