<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 0734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CorporateTravel Bjt   10-12 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corporate Travel, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Corporations Usually Restrict Executives Traveling Togther</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives at many major corporations travel
separately to reduce the risk that top management would be wiped
out in a fatal accident, officials said the day after three Trump
Organization executives died in a helicopter crash.
   On Tuesday, three of developer Donald Trump's highest ranking
gaming executives died when their helicopter crashed en route from
New York City to Atlantic City.
   One of the executives oversaw all casino operations in Atlantic
City for Trump, another headed the $1 billion Taj Mahal casino
under construction on the Boardwalk, and the third was senior vice
president of one of Trump's operating casinos.
   ``In general terms, top executives would not travel on the same
aircraft,'' said Peter J. Peterson, a spokesman for General Motors
Corp. ``In the interest of continuity at the highest levels of
management, you limit your risk.''
   Not all corporations, however, have policies about their
executives traveling together, said Francis H. Goranin, the
immediate past president of the American Society of Travel Agents.
   ``Some companies do; some companies don't. There is no set
rule,'' he said, adding that concern over executive safety and
travel had increased since the bombing of Pan Am flight 103 last
December.
   Trump Organization spokesman Dan Klores said Wednesday that
Trump at one point planned to be on the helicopter that crashed in
a heavily wooded area along New Jersey's Garden State Parkway, but
changed his mind.
   Klores said he was unaware of any travel policy in the Trump
Organization.
   Even those companies with such policies, however, said having
executives part company at the airline terminal is difficult to
enforce unless the officers themselves are concerned.
   A 1988 survey by Runzheimer International Ltd., a Northbrook,
Ill., management consulting firm, found that 56 percent of 108
companies responding to a survey had policies on employee travel.
   Sixty-eight percent of the companies with policies include
limits on executives traveling together. Those limits include air
travel at 93 percent of the companies, and ground restrictions at
27 percent of the companies.
   Fifteen percent of the companies with limitations place
restrictions on executives checking in to the same hotel.
   Bradford Burris, executive vice president with Runzheimer, said
most companies usually can't police their executives to make sure
they adhere to travel policies.
   ``It is a policy that is difficult to enforce unless the
travelers themselves are concerned,'' Burris said.
   ``You'd never know it is adhered to until the plane crashes,''
he said.
   Some companies' limits reach into the middle-management level.
   ``We restrict the number of divisional people that can travel
together,'' said Robert T. McDonough, a spokesman for the Upjohn
Co., a pharmaceutical manufacturer in Kalamazoo, Mich. ``We
basically say that our most senior executives will not travel
together at all.''
   Peterson said GM's policy also included division heads.
   ``It would just appear to be good judgment,'' he said.
   At AT&amp;T, ``our chairman does not fly with either of our first
vice chairmen,'' said Lynn Newman, a spokeswoman for the
Bedminster, N.J.-based company. ``We don't want more than two of
our senior managers on the same flight.''
   As with most other companies who discussed their policies with
The Associated Press, Ms. Newman said AT&amp;T's restrictions did not
result from a particular incident.
   One company, however, declined to discuss policy for security
reasons.
   ``Our policy is not to discuss publicly the company's travel
policy,'' said Harold Carr, a spokesman for the Boeing Corp. in
Seattle. ``We have executives traveling around the world every day
of the week.''
   And the policy goes far beyond the corporate world.
   Even when appearing at the same function, President Bush and
Vice President Quayle take separate planes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891012-0274 </DOCNO>
