<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     10-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Declines Overall, Rises Against U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States
widened in September, although rising purchases abroad reduced
Japan's overall trade surplus from year-ago levels for the fifth
consecutive month, the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
   Total exports exceeded imports by $7.24 billion, down from $7.76
billion in September 1988. The surplus was up, however, from $3.44
billion in August.
   Although September imports from the United States surged 12.3
percent from a year ago to $3.88 billion, Japan's surplus with the
United States rose to $4.78 billion from $4.65 billion a year
earlier. U.S. imports from Japan rose 6.8 percent to $8.67 billion.
   It was the first increase in three months in Japan's surplus
with the United States.
   On a global basis, Japan's exports rose 4.8 percent from
September 1988 to $24.29 billion while imports climbed 10.6 percent
to $17.05 billion. The import growth was down from the 15.8 percent
between August 1988 and August 1989.
   While analysts say they do not anticipate a major export
expansion soon, some cited fears that the yen's continued weakening
against the U.S. dollar, which makes Japanese goods cheaper abroad,
could add to already firm foreign demand for Japan's products.
   The weakening yen also makes Japanese purchases abroad more
expensive, but government officials have said demand in Japan is
robust.
   Japan registered a trade surplus of $2.02 billion with the
European Economic Community in September, up from $2.01 billion a
year earlier. Exports rose 4.4 percent to $4.08 billion, while
imports increased 8.7 percent to $2.06 billion.
</TEXT>
