<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-CocaCola     10-12 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Coca Cola,0358</SECOND>
<UNK>Coca-Cola Reports 22 Percent Rise in Quarterly Income</UNK>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. reported today that the sale of its
bottled water business and increased international soft drink
volume helped boost its third-quarter profit 22 percent from the
same period a year ago.
   Net income for the three-month period totaled $361.3 million, or
$1.03 a share, compared with $295.6 million, or 81 cents a share,
in the same 1988 period, the Atlanta-based soft drink company said.
Net operating revenues rose 8 percent to $2.3 billion from $$2.1
billion.
   For the first nine months of 1989, net income was up 19 percent
to $966.6 million, or $2.73 a share, from $809.2 million, or $2.20
a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 6 percent to $6.7 billion
from $6.3 billion.
   The results included a non-recurring after-tax gain of about $36
million, or 10 cents per share, from the sale of the bottled water
business, the company said.
   A much larger after-tax gain _ $530 million or $1.53 per common
share _ is expected to be added to fourth-quarter earnings because
of the sale of Coca-Cola's 53.8 million shares of Columbia Pictures
Entertainment Inc. to Sony Corp., company officials said. The
Coca-Cola board approved the sale Oct. 2.
   Chairman Roberto C. Goizueta said third-quarter earnings also
were helped by an 8 percent increase in worldwide sales of soft
drink syrups and concentrates. International syrup sales were up 14
percent, but domestic sales of syrups and concentrates was down 2
percent during the three months ended Sept. 30, he said.
   Case sales of soft drinks in the United States were even with
the previous year.
   The Coca-Cola Foods subsidiary, which markets Minute Maid
brands, reported a 25 percent increase in chilled orange juice
volume and a 33 percent decline in frozen orange juice volume for
the quarter.
   The company also reported that it completed a 40 million-share
stock repurchase plan during the third quarter. The plan was
initiated in 1987.
   The board of directors has authorized the repurchase of an
additional 20 million shares through 1991, the company said.
</TEXT>
