<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-12 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Rise Slightly Ahead of Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures prices were
slightly higher this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade in
cautious trading in advance of the Agriculture Department crop
report.
   The USDA is expected to forecast larger corn and soybean crops
than last month's estimates of 1.89 billion bushels of soybeans and
7.32 billion bushels of corn.
   The report is scheduled for release at 2 p.m. Central time.
   Today's slight early gains extended Wednesday's modest advance.
   The markets drew further support from the National Weather
Service's latest six-to-10-day forecast, which predicts a chance
for normal rainfall in the eastern Corn Belt in the latter half of
next week, although the western Corn Belt is expected to remain dry.
   The unusually dry weather of the past three weeks has kept the
Midwestern crop harvest moving at brisk pace and put pressure on
the crop futures markets.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent to 1{ cents higher
with December at $4.05} a bushel; corn futures were \ cent lower to
} cent higher with December at $2.35{ a bushel; oats were unchanged
to { cent higher with December at $1.41 a bushel; and soybeans were
{ cent lower to 2 cents higher with November at $5.54\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .13 cent higher with October
at 73.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent
higher with October at 83.25 cents a pound; live hogs were .40 cent
lower to .28 cent higher with October at 47.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .17 cent lower to .25 cent higher with
February at 47.95 cents a pound.
   Cattle and pork-belly futures advanced on Wednesday while hog
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
