<HEAD>Trump Execs Say Suspicion About Trump Bid for AMR is Misplaced</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 2 new grafs after 4th graf pvs, More than ... to UPDATE
with midday stock price and report on Bass. Picks up 5th graf pvs, The
market ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Market suspicion surrounding Donald Trump's $7
billion offer for the parent of American Airlines is misplaced and
incorrect, say some airline analysts and Trump officials.
   ``Everybody that I speak to says that the Street (the financial
community) doesn't believe it, but I think people should give
(Trump) more credit,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an analyst with
Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in New York.
   Nevertheless, Buttrick agreed with other analysts that
skepticism over Trump's intentions and general profit-taking
combined Wednesday to drive down the price of AMR Corp. stock by
$4.25 to close at $97.12{, the lowest level since the billionaire's
$120-per-share offer was revealed a week ago.
   More than 2.6 million AMR shares changed hands Wednesday in
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In midday trading today, AMR was up $1.75 a share at $98.87{ in
fairly active dealings.
   The Wall Street Journal reported today that representatives of
Fort Worth billionaire Robert M. Bass were willing to help AMR fend
off Trump. Group officials refused to discuss the report, although
Bass has been mentioned from the first as a possible ``white
knight.''
   The market ``may not believe it,'' Trump attorney Jack Nusbaum
said Wednesday, but ``he has not sold his shares, and doesn't plan
to. This is not a stock play.''
   Officials of Fort Worth-based AMR have refused to discuss the
bid for the parent of the nation's largest airline, and Nusbaum
said there had been no meetings between the two sides.
   Until there is some visible action, industry analyst David
Pizzimenti said the softness in AMR's price is likely to continue.
   ``I think that until you see some concrete kind of action by
either party, ... the stock will continue to trade at a discount''
to Trump's offer, said Pizzimenti, who works for Nomura Securities
International Inc. in New York.
   AMR, considered one of the nation's best-run carriers, has said
it will consider the offer ``in due course,'' but gave no
indication when it might respond.
   There has been speculation that AMR may seek a competing bid
either from an employee-management group or a friendly buyer, that
it would push Congress for quick legislation to require government
review of airline takeovers, or that it would restructure and pay a
special dividend.
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee has
approved a bill giving the transportation secretary authority to
review takeovers, but the bill is not scheduled for debate. A
similar bill has been introduced in the House, but is far from
being adopted.
   Legislative concern has centered over the use of debt to finance
the recent wave of airline takeovers, fearing that maintenance
might suffer while companies work to pay off debt.
   While Congress considers the legislation, Nusbaum said Trump has
received Justice Department clearance to pursue the offer. Under
the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act, the government must review the antitrust
implications of certain transactions involving the acquisition of
$15 million worth of a company.
   Meanwhlie Wednesday, the airline's largest union said it had
retained a financial consultant to advise it on any possible buyout.
   Ed Koziatek, vice president of the Transport Workers Union, said
officials had had no contact with American officials, but were
seeking financial advice. The union represents 33,000 ground and
support workers.
   Earlier, the Association of Professional Flight Attendants said
its officials were meeting with advisers, and the Allied Pilots
Association is reported to have retained an adviser.
   Meanwhile, one of AMR's large institutional stockholders said it
would hold onto its stock.
   ``We think the risk-reward is good at this point,'' said Gerald
R. Smith, senior vice president of Aetna Equity Investors in
Hartford, Conn. ``The worst case is that AMR will do something to
make the stock worth more than it was selling before offer. We peg
that in the low 90s. The upside we don't think is limited to $120
necessarily.
   ``We knew that when the offer was made ... that there was going
to be a bumpy road and the stock was going to fluctuate,'' he said.
   Smith said Aetna holds a substantial amount of AMR stock, but
would not be specific.
   Another institutional investor, the Windsor Fund, said it sold
its AMR holdings recently, cashing in on the higher prices since
Trump's bid.
</TEXT>
