<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted lower today, extending
the shallow decline of the past two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 18.05 points over
the last two sessions, slipped 8.20 to 2,765.16 by noontime on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 469 up, 751 down and
558 unchanged.
   Interest rates declined in the credit markets this morning. But
analysts said stock traders had other concerns on their minds.
   The government is due to report Friday morning on the producer
price index of finished goods for September.
   Adavnce estimates on Wall Street call for an increase in that
measure of inflationary pressures of somewhere between 0.5 percent
and 1 percent, reversing the downward trend that prevailed through
the summer.
   ``Forthcoming reports are likely to show fairly strong readings
in both producer and consumer prices,'' observed Jack Lavery at
Merrill Lynch in his latest market commentary.
   ``Such readings may raise concern that inflation is heating up,
but we believe that such a conclusion would be unwarranted.''
   Losers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, down ] at 52[;
Philip Morris, down ] at 44|; Sears Roebuck, down [ at 42];
McDonald's, down [ at 30, and General Electric, down \ at 57~.
   GE reported third-quarter earnings of $1.04 a share, up from 90
cents in the like period a year ago.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.67 to 197.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off .34 at 395.34.
