<FIRST>r f BC-Philips-Japan     10-12 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Philips-Japan,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>American-Made TV Sets Shipped to Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a reversal of an electronics trend,
Philips Consumer Electronics Co. on Thursdasy began shipping
American-made television sets to Japan.
   Philips plans to export 1,500 table-top sets to the land of the
rising sun this year, ``with significantly increasing exports
projected for the 1990s,'' the company said in a statement.
   Philips President and Chief Executive Donald F. Johnstone called
the shipment ``a significant first step in gaining a much-needed
equilibrium in the balance of trade between the U.S. and foreign
nations, particularly Japan.''
   The 27-inch sets were specially designed following an intensive
study of Japanese consumers. They have special colors and exterior
finishes that proved appealing to Japanese buyers.
   ``They like complexity and features,'' said A.L. Rodgers,
director of international marketing, adding that simplicity in
using the product also is important to the Japanese consumer.
   Rodgers said the sets will be marketed to ``upscale Japanese
consumers ... the same purchaser who buys a Mercedes Benz imported
from Germany.''
   The sets will be sold as products of Philips International,
rather than as American-made sets. But with control buttons in
English, the fact that the sets are American-made will not be
hidden, Rodgers said.
   The sets were manufactured at the Philips' Greenville plant,
which employs 4,800 people.
   In addition to these direct-view sets, Philips plans to
manufacture projection TVs for export in 1990 and 1991.
</TEXT>
