<HEAD>United Machinists Asks U.S. To Block Buyout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``On Tuesday ... to CORRECT figure to $200 million
sted $20 million; Picks up 4th graf: The banks...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Machinists union at United Airlines has asked
the Labor Department to block the proposed employee buyout of the
airlines' parent company, claiming it violates laws governing the
use of retirement funds.
   In a three-page letter sent Wednesday to Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, the union charged that the tax benefits of the
proposed $6.75 billion buyout ``are effectively subsidizing a
substantial and excessive windfall'' to UAL Corp.'s management and
United's pilots, the employee group spearheading the takeover
effort.
   On Tuesday, United's pilots voted overwhelmingly to commit $200
million from their $1.2 billion pension fund to buy preferred stock
in an employee stock ownership plan.
   The banks financing the deal wanted to see such a commitment
before providing financing for the takeover.
   A group led by the pilots and UAL's management, with the
participation of British Airways PLC, has offered to buy the
Chicago-based company for $300 a share in a tender offer that
expires Oct. 26.
   The pilots are the only UAL employee group so far committed to
participating in the buyout. The machinists previously declared
their opposition to the plan and United's flight attendants are
continuing to negotiate with UAL's management on contract
concessions in exchange for partial ownership of the company.
   The deal also is being examined by the Transportation
Department, which has expressed concern about leveraged buy-outs
and foreign stakes in U.S. airlines.
