<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 1557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-India-Pepsi     10-12 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-India-Pepsi,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsi Soft Drinks to be Sold in India Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAHURA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PepsiCo Inc., the soft drink, restaurant
and snack foods giant, will sell its cola and other beverages in
India next year, the company said Thursday.
   The announcement was released after Punjab Governor Sidharth
Shankar Ray presided over the placement of the cornerstone for a
food and vegetable processing plant, partly owned by PepsiCo, at
this remote village.
   The plant is the second unit of Pepsi Foods that was formed as a
joint venture of PepsiCo and two Indian companies _ the Punjab
government's Agro-Industries Corp. and the privately owned Tata
group.
   The other unit, also located in Punjab at the Channo village,
will manufacture concentrate for soft drinks which will be
distributed to independent bottlers throughout the country.
   The compnay said it expects its beverage and food products will
be on the market by the summer of 1990. It said the cola will be
sold under the brand name Pepsi Era.
   PepsiCo's share in the $15 million project is 39.9 percent, in
line with an Indian law which restricts the holding of foreign
partners in a joint venture to 40 percent. The law also forbids use
of foreign brand names.
   According to the government's terms, soft-drink production will
be restricted to 25 percent of the project's sales and exports of
food products will have to be five times the value of imports.
   Indians were cut off from U.S. soft drinks after Coca-Cola Co.
ended 27 years of business here in 1977 when the government
insisted that the company disclose its secret formula.
   PepsiCo left India in the 1950s because of poor sales.
</TEXT>
