<FIRST>r f BC-TomatoVirus     10-12 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tomato Virus,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Virus Discovered in Florida Tomato Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plant pathologists have discovered a
previously unknown virus in Florida's tomato crop but say they
don't have enough information about it to predict the impact on the
state's vegetable industry.
   ``It's a new virus for most of us,'' said George N. Agrios,
chairman of University of Florida's department of plant technology.
``Since we really need to study the virus ... we have no
recommendation on what to do about it.''
   Tomatoes comprise about one-third of all vegetables grown in
Florida. Last year growers shipped to market 64.87 million 25-pound
cartons valued at more than $600 million.
   With an estimated 54,000 acres planted in tomatoes, Florida
produces much of the winter domestic crop sold November through May.
   With no way now to defend against the still-unnamed virus,
researchers plan simply to learn what they can about its behavior.
   Researchers said the suspected virus is similar to one that has
stunted plant grown and reduced the quantity of tomatoes produced
in Mexico. Symptons include green and gold mottled leaves, leaf
curl and stunting.
</TEXT>
