<HEAD>Saatchi Names New Chief Executive and Finance Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saatchi and Saatchi Co. PLC, the world's largest
advertising agency, on Thursday named a new chief executive and a
new finance director.
   The company, which recently has been the target of takeover
speculation, said Robert Louis-Dreyfus, 43, is to join the company
as chief executive Jan. 1. A Frenchman, he currently is president
and chief executive of IMS International Inc., where he has worked
since 1982, Saatchi said.
   IMS is the leading market research firm in pharmaceuticals. It
was acquired last year by Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. of the United
States, Saatchi said.
   Saatchi's new finance director, also effective Jan. 1, is to be
Charles Scott, 40, who currently is chief financial officer of IMS.
   Maurice Saatchi serves as chairman of the company, and his
brother Charles is a member of the board of directors.
   Saatchi's statement didn't say who Louis-Dreyfus and Scott were
replacing, or if the posts were vacant. Repeated attempts to reach
Saatchi officials in London and New York and at Saatchi's public
relations firm in London were unsuccessful.
   Saatchi's shares have been buoyed by takeover speculation.
   Southeastern Asset Management Inc., a Memphis, Tenn.-based
investment company, has acquired a 10.2 percent stake in Saathchi,
and said earlier this week that it had been approached by third
parties it did not identify who are interested in restructuring
transactions involving Saatchi.
