<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-12 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heating Oil Prices Rally, Most Other Energy Futures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale home heating oil prices rallied
Thursday amid speculation about temporary tightness in supplies.
Crude oil futures prices also posted gains while gasoline futures
finished mixed.
   The contract for November delivery of No.2 heating oil surged
1.36 cents to 61.17 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile
Exchange after rising 0.17 cent the previous session. Other
contract months also rose.
   James Steel, an energy analyst at Refco Inc., said reports of
disruptions in heating oil shipments from the Soviet Union to
Western Europe caused some speculative buying on world markets. A
low water level on the Rhine River was said to be delaying barge
travel.
   The heating oil market also has been pumped up by a belief that
supplies in Europe could be tight because earlier this year an
abundance of gasoline was processed, at the expense of heating oil.
   Domestically, industry figures on oil inventories encouraged
some bullish sentiment toward heating oil, said Steel. The American
Petroleum Institute's weekly report was released after the market
closed Wednesday.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 22 cents to settle at $20.47 per
42-gallon barrel after rising 8 cents on Wednesday. Contracts
calling for delivery December through February sported gains also.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the New York Merc,
the November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoine fell 0.16 cent
to 55.57 cents a gallon, but contracts for later delivery settled
with moderate increases. On Wednesday, the November gas contract
declined 0.26 cent.
</TEXT>
