<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-12 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in subdued dealings Thursday as
traders awaited the release of fresh economic data.
   Gold prices rose worldwide.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $363.40 a troy ounce, up $1.40 from Wednesday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold at
$363 an ounce, $1.50 higher than Wednesday's late bid.
   Many traders stayed on the sidelines while awaiting the
government's release Friday of retail sales and producer prices
data for September.
   ``If the Producer Price Index comes in on the high side, the
(Federal Reserve) won't have room to ease (interest rates) any
further,'' said Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at the Bank of
Boston's New York office.
   ``While the Fed is concerned about the level of the dollar,
their major priority is to keep inflation'' down, he added.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was undermined by
speculation that the Fed was considering a cut in the discount
rate, its interest charge on loans to member banks. Lower interest
rates make U.S. investments less attractive to foreigners, thereby
diminishing their need for dollars.
   Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers Hanover
Trust Co., said that despite the fact that the dollar is holding to
key levels, the U.S. currency is likely to come under pressure
because interest rate differentials have narrowed considerably.
   U.S. interest rates currently are about 2.5 percent higher than
those in Japan, he said.
   ``And historically, as it gets under 3 percent, the dollar comes
under pressure,'' Flanagan said, adding that earlier this year the
spread was as high as 5 percent, ``which had kept the underlying
support of the dollar all year.''
   Separately, the British pound got a boost from comments by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who told the governing
Conservative Party's annual conference he would continue to fight
inflation with high interest rates for as long as necessary.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose to 144.60 Japanese yen, from 143.90 yen.
Later in London, the dollar traded lower at 144.25 yen. In New
York, the dollar finished at 144.15 yen, down from 144.50 yen on
Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5520, more expensive for
buyers than Wednesday's late $1.5425. In New York, it cost $1.5527
to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5460 on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.9075 West German marks, down from 1.9155;
1.6735 Swiss francs, down from 1.6800; 6.4670 French francs, down
from 6.4900; 1,399.25 Italian lire, down from 1,403.00, and 1.1749
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1748.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's
late rates included: 1.9068 West German marks, down from 1.9185;
1.6715 Swiss francs, down from 1.6785; 6.4650 French francs, down
from 4.4925; 2.1510 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1630; 1,397.50
Italian lire, down from 1,403.25, and 1.1737 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1750.
   Gold traded late in London at a bid of $362.75 a troy ounce, up
from $361.25 Wednesday. The Zurich late bid was $363.10, up from
$361.50. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $362.75, up from
$361.25.
   Silver traded late in London at a bid $5.10 a troy ounce, up
from $5.05. On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery closed
at $5.090 a troy ounce, up from $5.076 on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
