<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-USSteel     10-12 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-US Steel,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC, US Reach Tentative Agreement on Steel Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community and the United
States reached tentative agreement on a new accord increasing
slightly the European share of the American steel market, the
trading bloc announced Thursday.
   The European Commission, the community's executive body, said
the European share would rise from 6.68 percent to 7 percent under
the new arrangement, which will remain in effect until March 31,
1992.
   The accord, which still must be approved by the 12 nations of
the European Community, means European producers could increase
exports to the United States by almost 300,000 metric tons.
   The trading bloc exported 5.9 million metric tons of steel
products to the United States in 1988.
   Frans Andriessen, the community's top trading official, told
members of the European Parliament, ``The results are not
unsatisfactory but (we are) bound to see it with mixed feelings.''
   ``There was no need for an agreement. .. Objectively speaking,
it was unnecessary,'' he said.
   The arrangement stems from a decision in July by President Bush
to extend steel import quotas, which were first put in place in
1984. They had been set to expire on Sept. 30.
   The restrictions set annual limits on the amount of steel that
can be brought into the United States from 29 countries, including
those of the European Community, Japan, South Korea and Brazil.
   The European Commission said the new agreement covered the same
steel products and that some terms of the arrangement were
improved, particularly for the export of goods in short supply in
the United States.
   It said the 30-month extension of the U.S. restrictions was a
``credible step toward the liberalization of the steel trade.''
   In Strasbourg, France, the European Parliament, the community's
legislative body, said it regretted the new agreement limiting
European sales in light of the improvement in the American steel
industry. It said the accord could complicate international trade
talks for a broader steel pact.
   The U.S. quotas were first imposed at a time the American steel
industry was suffering heavy losses. Steelmakers complained they
were hurt by foreign producers who were helped by big government
subsidies and import restrictions.
   They say they have benefited from the quotas but argue they
still need more time to modernize their operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
