<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-SallieMae     10-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Sallie Mae,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Quarter Earnings Rise 15 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Student Loan Marketing Association, known
as Sallie Mae, reported Thursday that third quarter earnings were
up 15 percent because of continued strong student loan purchase
volume.
   Net earnings for the period ending Sept. 30 were $65.9 million,
or 65 cents per share, compared to $57.5 million, or 55 cents per
share, for the same period a year ago.
   Sallie Mae is a federally-chartered, publicly-traded corporation
that buys insured student loans from the originating institutions,
such as banks, to increase the availability of education loans for
college students.
   As of Sept. 30, total assets for the Washington-based
corporation were $33.8 billion, up 28 percent from the $26.5
billion total for the same period in 1988.
   Student loan purchases for the third quarter totaled $1.2
billion compared to $1.4 billion for the 1988 third quarter. That
brought Sallie Mae's total student loan portfolio to $14.9 billion,
up 20 percent from $12.5 billion for the third quarter of 1988.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Sallie Mae earned $189.6
million, or $1.87 per share, compared with net income of $166.2
million, or $1.57 per share, for the nine months that ended Sept.
30, 1988.
   Earnings per share data for the year-ago periods were restated
to reflect a 2.5 to 1 stock split in May.
