<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-12 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Bellies Soar The Limit As Supply Fears Mount</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frozen pork-belly futures prices soared the permitted
2-cents-a-pound daily limit Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange Thursday amid growing supply fears rooted in the
government's decision to ship pork bellies to Poland.
   On other commodity markets, copper and precious metals futures
advanced, grains and soybeans were mixed; and energy futures were
mostly higher.
   Frozen pork bellies futures settled 2 cents higher across the
board with the contract for delivery in February at 49.72 cents a
pound.
   The rally followed a surge of buying on Wednesday and may
reflect the market's uneasiness about the government's plan to ship
$10 million worth of U.S. pork bellies to Poland as part of a
food-aid package.
   Pork bellies are the part of a pig from which bacon is made.
   With stocks of frozen pork bellies at historically high levels,
supply tightness would seem to be low on the market's list of
concerns.
   But under the rules of the futures market, only bellies frozen
after Nov. 1 are deliverable against any of the futures contracts
currently trading. And some of the surplus bellies produced this
winter _ perhaps as much as 15 million pounds' worth _ are destined
to be sent to Poland instead of being packed away in commercial
freezers for domestic use later on.
   Traders fear that the large stockpile of bellies currently in
freezers may be too old to guarantee their quality if they were to
be shipped to Poland. But the government has not yet decided on the
specifications for the Polish shipment.
   ``The longer the government delays in outlining the
specifications of the product that has to go to Poland, the more
uncertain the situation becomes ... and the more nervous the
futures market becomes,'' said Chuck Levitt, senior livestock
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   In livestock trading on the Chicago Merc, live cattle futures
settled .20 cent lower to .07 cent higher with October at 73 cents
a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .42 cent higher with
October at 83.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower to
1.05 cent higher with October at 48.67 cents a pound.
   Copper futures rose on New York's Commodity Exchange after the
Arizona-based copper producer Magma Copper Co. announced it was
forced to cancel some shipments due to equipment problems.
   Copper settled 1.2 cents to 1.45 cents higher with December at
$1.3035 a pound.
   In precious-metals trading on the Commodity Exchange, gold
settled $1.30 to $1.50 higher with October at $363.40 a troy ounce;
silver was 1 cent to 1.4 cents higher with December at $5.153 a
troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures ended narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Board of Trade ahead of the Agriculture Department's
eagerly-awaited monthly crop report.
   The report, which was released after the close, estimated the
1989 U.S. corn crop at 7.45 billion bushels, up 2 percent from last
month's projection of projection of 7.32 billion bushels and 51
percent higher than the drought-shriveled 1988 crop of 4.92 billion
bushels.
   The USDA estimated the 1989 U.S. soybean crop at 1.93 billion
bushels, up 2 percent from last month's projection of 1.89 billion
and 24 percent larger than last year's harvest of 1.54 billion.
   And the USDA estimated total 1989 U.S. wheat production at 2.04
billion bushels, up 13 percent from last year, but 1 percent below
the September forecast of 2.06 billion bushels.
   The corn and soybean numbers were above market expectations and
analysts said the report may send corn and soybean futures prices
moderately lower at Friday's opening.
   Wheat futures were expected to open slightly higher Friday in
response to the report.
   Wheat futures settled 2 cents to 2} cents higher with December
at $4.06} a bushel; corn futures were 1} cents lower to \ cent
higher with December at $2.35\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to {
cent higher with December at $1.40} a bushel; soybeans were 2{
cents lower to \ cent higher with November at $5.52{ a bushel.
   Wholesale home heating oil prices rallied strongly on the New
York Mercantile Exchange amid speculation about temporary tightness
in supplies. Crude oil futures prices also posted gains while
gasoline futures finished mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 26 cents
higher with November at $20.47 a barrel; heating oil was .57 cent
to 1.36 cents higher with November at 61.17 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .16 cent lower to .55 cent higher with
November at 55.57 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
