<SECOND>AM-GM Vans,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Moving Full-Size Van Production to Michigan from Ohio, Ontario</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production of General Motors Corp.'s full-size
vans will be moved to Flint, Mich., from plants in Ohio and
Ontario, leaving production lines there idled in late 1991, company
and union officials said Thursday.
   The 4,700 workers at GM's Truck and Bus Group plant in Flint had
been waiting for such an announcement and it was greeted with
relief and celebration.
   The news wasn't good for the 2,500 van workers at Lordstown,
Ohio.
   ``No further product is scheduled for the (Lordstown) van
plant,'' said GM spokesman Philip Workman. ``At Lordstown, the
focus will be on passenger cars in the future.''
   In addition to the full-size vans, the sprawling Lordstown
complex makes Chevrolet Cavalier and Pontiac Sunbird automobiles.
There are about 11,500 people employed at the plant in the
Youngstown suburb about 50 miles southeast of Cleveland.
   GM said it was looking for another product to put in its
Scarborough, Ontario, plant, which employs about 2,700 people.
   Earlier this year, GM said it would end production in Flint of
three light-duty trucks and move it to Janesville, Wis., in late
1991. At that time, GM said it was looking for another product to
put in the Flint truck factory.
   ``Last February we said we would have a vehicle to be named
later at Flint,'' GM spokesman Tom Klipstine said Thursday in a
statement. ``We have now named that product.''
   He said the timing of the move, how many employees may be
affected and how much time it would take to retool the factory for
full-size van production hadn't been determined.
   But Gary Pruett, president of United Auto Workers Local 598 at
the plant, said the change would be completed in time for late 1991
production of 1992 models, employment at Flint shouldn't be
affected too much and the plant would be shut down for about five
months for the changeover.
   ``We've got people jumping up and down here,'' he said by
telephone. ``We had some people who were really scared. This is
really great for us.''
</TEXT>
