<SECOND>AM-Northwest-Boeing, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0279,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Confirms Boeing Planes Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Boeing, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 3rd graf pvs, Northwest ordered ...
to note strike at Boeing. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Value of ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines said Thursday it has
placed orders and options for $5.2 billion worth of Boeing jets,
the largest order in Northwest's history.
   ``This order is a testament to the new ownership's and new
management's commitment to the people of Northwest and the growth
of the company,'' said Fred Malek, who last month was named
president of the nation's fourth-largest carrier by its new
chairman, Alfred Checchi.
   Northwest ordered six Boeing 747-400s and secured options on
four more of the 420-passenger, high-technology jumbo jets. In
addition, the airline bought 40 Boeing 757-200 twin jets and placed
options on 40 more.
   The order comes even as Boeing has been hit with a strike by
production workers.
   In Seattle Thursday, Chris Longridge, vice president of sales at
Boeing Commercial Airplanes, said the show of confidence in Boeing
was appreciated. Striking Boeing workers said the reports of the
impending order bolstered their contention that Boeing can afford a
better wage and benefit offer.
   Value of the firm orders in today's dollars is about $2.7
billion and the options represent another $2.5 billion, Malek told
a news conference at Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport.
   Deliveries of aircraft included in this order are scheduled
between the second half of 1993 and 1998.
   Northwest, which earlier this year became the first airline to
fly the 747-400, will power the new 747-400s with Pratt &amp; Whitney
PW4000 engines. Northwest already operates the world's largest
fleet of 747-400s with five in service now and five more scheduled
for delivery by the end of 1990.
   Malek said Northwest plans to use the new 747-400s on routes to
and from Asia. Projections show that trans-Pacific markets will
continue to grow at a double-digit pace, he said, adding that the
range, payload and fuel efficiency of the 400 make it an excellent
choice for high density Asian routes.
   The 757 orders and options will bring Northwest's fleet of these
184-passenger twin jets to 113 aircraft. The 757s will be powered
by Pratt &amp; Whitney PW2037 engines, which are designed for fuel
efficiency and low community noise levels.
   Northwest, purchased in June by a group of investors led by
Checchi, received its first 757 in 1985 and currently operates 33
of them. The 757s, with transcontinental range, will be used on
medium- and long-haul domestic routes, Malek said.
   With Thursday's $5.2 billion transaction, Northwest has 229
aircraft on order for delivery through the 1990s for a total value
of more than $11.5 billion.
</TEXT>
