<HEAD>Reports Earnings Growth In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raytheon Co., boosted by successful bids
for military contracts, reported Thursday its third quarter
earnings for 1989 rose 8.5 percent compared with the same
three-month period a year earlier.
   Earnings rose to $137.4 million, or $2.08 per share, on sales of
$2.189 billion in the quarter that ended Oct. 1. In the third
quarter last year, the company earned $126.7 million, or $1.91 per
share, on sales of $1.993 billion.
   For the first nine months of the fiscal year, earnings were
$391.9 million, or $5.94 per share, on sales of $6.552 billion. In
the same period last year, earnings were $362.3 million, or $5.43
per share, on sales of $5.983 billion.
   Thomas Phillips, Raytheon chairman and chief executive officer,
said in a prepared statement that all of the company's segments
produced higher sales and operating profits in the third quarter
compared with the year before.
   Electronics, which is Raytheon's largest segment, continued to
benefit from defense contracts, the company said. Raytheon won a
contract to develop a ground-launched missile system, in addition
to other contracts with the U.S. Air Force and Navy.
   The company reported its Beech Aircraft sales and profits
improved significantly during the quarter, as domestic orders for
commuter and business turboprops improved at a strong pace.
