<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CBOE-MarketBasket     10-12 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CBOE-Market Basket,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Options Exchanges Plans First Non-Option Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange won't be just
for options anymore, officials of the exchange announced Thursday.
   The world's biggest options marketplace is planning to launch a
stock market basket during the week of Oct. 23, pending Securities
and Exchange Commission approval.
   The new product, a basket made up of all the stocks in the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index, represents the Options Exchanges'
latest attempt to boost its trading volume, which dropped
dramatically after the 1987 stock market crash.
   The exchange reported volume of 9.69 million trades last month,
up 10 percent from 8.84 million in September 1988 but still 46
percent below the pre-crash September 1987 volume of 17.78 million
trades.
   The market basket, the exchange's first non-option product, is
designed for use by institutional investors.
   Investors who buy the market basket will actually be buying
shares in each of the 500 stocks represented in the S&amp;P 500 index,
with the number of shares in each stock determined by its relative
weight in the index.
   The basket's value will be equal to $5,000 times the S&amp;P 500
index level, or about $1.79 million currently.
   The product will lend itself to various trading strategies
involving stocks and stock options, the exchange said in a
statement.
   The Options Exchange trades options on 204 stocks, on the S&amp;P
500 and S&amp;P 100 indexes, on interest rates and on U.S. Treasury
bonds and notes.
   An option is a right, but not an obligation, to buy or sell a
commodity or financial product at a specified price by a specified
date.
</TEXT>
