<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AffiliatedPublications     10-12 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Affiliated Publications,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affiliated Publications Reports Profit for Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affiliated Publications Inc., parent company of
The Boston Globe, reported Thursday it earned $8.48 million in the
third quarter though revenue declined.
   The profit for the quarter ended Sept. 24, which amounted to 12
cents a share, compared with a loss of $25.6 million, or 38 cents a
share, in the third quarter of 1988.
   Affiliated said declining newspaper income in the third quarter
led to a 2.9 percent drop in overall revenue, to a total of $126.3
million, compared with revenue of $130.1 million for the same
period last year.
   Income from the company's continuing operations declined 20
percent in the third quarter, from $10.69 million to the $8.48
million net income figure, the company said.
   That figure excludes charges that stemmed from losses in
Affiliated's investment in McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. of
Kirkland, Wash. Earlier this year, Affiliated restructured that
investment, separating its publishing operations from the troubled
cellular business.
   Newspaper revenue declined 4.1 percent in the third quarter, and
operating income from the newspaper declined 16.6 percent.
   William O. Taylor, chairman and chief executive officer, said
the company's earnings continued to be affected by softness in
advertising volume at the Globe.
   For the first nine months of this year, income totaled $2.9
million, or 4 cents a share, compared with a loss of $51.4 million,
or 74 cents a share, in the year-ago period. Revenue this year
totaled $394.4 million, compared with $397.2 million for the same
period in 1988.
</TEXT>
