<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-89 2207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     10-12 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Share Prices Rebound Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened sharply lower against the
Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchage shot up.
   The dollar started trading at 143.60 yen, down 1.00 yen from
Thursday's Tokyo finish. In New York, it closed at 144.20 yen
overnight.
   The dollar's plunge at the opening of Tokyo trading followed its
downswing overnight in New York, where investors sold the currency
following a downtrend in the federal funds rate, said a trader with
Bank of Tokyo, speaking anonymously.
   The federal funds rate, the rate charged by a bank that loans
excess reserves to another bank overnight, is considered a
sensitive indicator of monetary conditions.
   Falling interest rates in the U.S. tend to lower the dollar's
value.
   The Bank of Tokyo trader said, however, that the dollar should
go up as participants bought back the currency to cover their short
dollar positions.
   Investors also were awaiting the release of the U.S. wholesale
price index for September later Friday to see if it would bring any
relaxation in U.S. monetary policy.
   Because the Bank of Japan's discount rate hike Wednesday by 0.5
percentage point to 3.75 percent and its massive dollar-selling
intervention has not been very successful in stemming the dollar's
continuting rise, a discount rate cut by the U.S. would be expected
to add stability in currency movements, he said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 242.52 points, or 0.70
percent, to move to 35,037.86 shortly after the morning session
started.
   On Thursday, the index shed 444.73 points, the second-largest
one-day loss, ending at 34,795.34.
   Dealers said the index rebounded sharply as market players
picked up issues whose prices plunged the previous day, while
traders also were reassured by the yen's overnight recovery.
</TEXT>
